<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MercyKilling 1stLd-Writethru a0724 03-19 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mercy Killing, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0724,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rules State Cannot Get Name Of Author Of Story Of Mercy
Killing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, `Terry Levin ...' with two grafs to UPDATE
with Daley statement.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge on Friday quashed a subpoena in which a
prosecutor sought to force a prominent medical journal to reveal
the name of a doctor who wrote an anonymous first-person account of
a mercy killing.
   ``We're very pleased with the decision. We think it vindicates
the decision to publish it,'' Kirk Johnson, counsel for the
American Medical Association, which publishes the Journal of the
American Medical Association, said.
   ``We continue to believe that the debate over euthanasia _ which
we oppose _ will help in determining the proper treatment of the
terminally ill,'' added Johnson.
   Terry Levin, a spokesman for Cook County State's Attorney
Richard Daley, said Daley had no immediate comment on whether he
would appeal.
   But in a statement, Daley charged that the journal is
``protecting the identity of a killer who may kill again _ indeed
who may well have already killed again.'' He said the article
``appears to be a confession to murder.''
   Chief Cook County Circuit Judge Richard Fitzgerald ruled the
state's attorney's office failed to prove a crime was committed,
and had not exhausted all other avenues to obtain the information _
as required by the state's free press-law.
   Fitzgerald also said the state's attorney had not demonstrated
the information being sought was essential to the public interest,
another requirement of the Illinois Reporters' Privilege Act.
   The article, ``It's Over, Debbie,'' was published in the Jan. 8
edition of the journal in its regular ``A Piece of My Mind'' column.
   In the article, a doctor described injecting a lethal dose of
morphine into a woman dying of ovarian cancer. He wrote that he did
not know the patient, but was asked to check on her and was moved
by her plea of ``Let's get this over with.''
   AMA officials said they did not verify the account, but believed
it was based on fact. They said the author had requested his name
be withheld. The essay did not indicate where the doctor lived or
where the incident occurred.
   The state's attorney's office served the subpoena in
mid-February and AMA attorneys moved to quash it the following week.
   Dr. George Lundberg, editor of the 105-year-old journal, said he
received unanimous support from the AMA board on his decision to
run the article.
   Lundberg has said he believed the essay describes an actual
event, but noted, ``The account does have enough vagueness to
welcome critical analysis as to whether it happened, or happened in
this way.''
   ``Whether the case is valid or not is irrelevant,'' he added,
``as long as the discussion is purposeful or educational for the
people involved.''
   Between 90 and 100 letters sent to the journal commenting on the
decision to publish were about evenly split.
   The AMA is the nation's largest physician organization, with
about 280,000 members, including about half the doctors in the
United States.
</TEXT>
