<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BrownCloud     03-19 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brown Cloud,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Clear Days Fewer in Dallas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also in Saturday AMs report</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT ROTHSCHILD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On a clear day in Dallas, you can't see forever.
   In fact clear days in Dallas are becoming about as scarce as
construction cranes.
   A study released Friday by federal and state air pollution
experts shows that visibility of 15 miles or greater has fallen
from about 320 days a year in 1950 to 70 in 1986. The study was
prompted by the apparent deterioration in the city's air in recent
years.
   The pollution that drapes the city's skyline has two forms: the
brown cloud phenomenon, a locally produced effect that usually
occurs in the winter, and a white haze phenomenon, which drifts in
from industries elsewhere in the state year-round.
   The cloud and the haze are equally effective in obscuring the
city's vistas, officials say. But their health effects, if any,
aren't clear.
   ``We do not feel there is an acute health effect,'' said William
Hathaway, director of the air, pesticides, and toxics division of
the regional Environmental Protection Agency. ``Long term, we do
not know.''
   Scientists with the EPA, Texas Air Control Board, and Sandia
National Laboratories of Albuquerque, N.M., said the brown cloud
contains pollution from vehicles, particularly those with diesel
engines, and from wood burning.
   The cloud appears on calm, cold mornings and often completely
obscures the city from a distance of 12 miles.
   About 70 percent of the vehicle pollution in the brown cloud
comes from diesel trucks and cars, although diesel engines account
for a small fraction of the vehicles, according to the report. ``A
diesel vehicle is the equivalent of 25 cars as far as emissions,''
said Wayne Einfield, of the Sandia National Laboratories.
   Hathaway said the EPA will require manufacturers to install
controls on diesel emissions on cars and pickup trucks beginning
next year. He also said his agency is working on converting city
bus systems from diesel to natural gas or methane fuel, and perhaps
will eliminate diesel buses in 10 to 12 years.
   He said the brown cloud also could be reduced by restricting
wood burning, as has been done in Denver. That would have to be
decided by city officials.
   The white haze is most noticeable when winds prevail from the
south and east, Hathaway said. It is composed mostly of sulfate
aerosols that probably come from coal- and lignite-fueled power
plants in East Texas and petroleum industry operations on the Gulf
Coast.
   As the results of the study, which ran from December 1986 to
March 1987, became evident, Hathaway said he began to review
emission levels from these plants, but has found no violations. He
declined to say whether he thought existing standards are adequate.
   Neither the cloud nor the haze are unique to Dallas, officials
said, but the nature of the two phenomena gives the city little
relief. If the still, cold conditions which produce the brown cloud
aren't prevailing, the white haze usually blows in from the south
and east, they said.
</TEXT>
