<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TaxpayerRights     03-19 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taxpayer Rights,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Taxpayer Rights Bill Would Soften Iron Hand Of IRS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ``bill of rights'' approved by the Senate
Finance Committee aims at improving the odds for taxpayers who find
themselves in trouble with the IRS.
   But the committee, fearing the original version of the
legislation was so restrictive that tax collections might suffer,
watered down the bill significantly before approving it without
dissent on Friday. Its future is still in doubt because of
opposition from the Reagan administration and some members of the
House Ways and Means Committee.
   Even after being weakened, the measure would require greater
notice before the Internal Revenue Service seizes taxpayers'
property; prohibit imposition of penalties that result from faulty
written advice from the IRS; and formally bar the agency from
requiring employees to meet a collection quota in order to win
promotion.
   Sen. David Pryor, D-Ark., chief author of the bill, said he has
received 11,000 letters from disgruntled taxpayers since raising
the issue. One that he read aloud while the bill was being debated
asked simply: ``Please put me in contact with a human being at the
IRS.''
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, chairman of the committee, said ``a
bully mentality'' infects parts of the IRS. ``This bill is not an
attempt to bash the IRS ... but to protect taxpayers from
heavy-handed abuse,'' he said.
   Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., recalling abuses of
taxpayer privacy during the Johnson and Nixon administrations,
asked IRS Chief Counsel William Nelson whether officials of the
Reagan White House have pressured the agency for political purposes.
   ``They are afraid to even speak to us on the street ...,''
Nelson replied. ``But on several occasions members of Congress have
given us names of individuals or groups and asked us to
investigate.''
   He said the IRS does not audit a taxpayer just because a member
of Congress makes the request, and the agency ``would scream
loudly'' if the White House made such a demand.
   The legislation is considerably weaker than when it was
introduced early last year. Dropped from the original were a
requirement that the IRS carry the burden of proving that its tax
assessments were wrong; a directive that taxpayers be given
Miranda-type readings of their legal rights anytime they are called
before the IRS; and a vast increase in the value of income and
property that would be exempt from IRS seizure.
   Key provisions of the committee-approved bill would:
   _Prohibit the IRS from judging employees on the basis of how
much tax they collect. This would write into law an IRS policy that
agents say is violated in some areas of the country.
   _Require the IRS to waive any penalty imposed because of a tax
underpayment that was caused by erroneous written IRS advice. The
IRS generally follows such a rule. This change would not affect a
taxpayer who asks IRS for advice by telephone; neither would it
allow the waiver of interest charges on any late payment.
   _Increase from 10 days to 30 days the advance written notice the
IRS generally must give a taxpayer before seizing property.
   _Allow the IRS ombudsman, or consumer advocate, to issue orders
stopping the agency from acting against a taxpayer about to suffer
unnecessary and significant loss if the IRS failed to carry out its
duties under the law.
   _Require the IRS to explain in detail how any interest or
penalties attached to a notice of tax deficiency were arrived at.
   _Allow a taxpayer to sue the IRS and recover litigation costs
and at least $100 for each day the agency wrongfully fails to
remove a claim from the taxpayer's property.
   _Permit a taxpayer who defeats the IRS to recover attorneys'
fees unless the IRS could prove it had substantial justification
for its position.
</TEXT>
