<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 0809EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ArmsTreaty     03-19 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arms Treaty,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senators Propose Amendment On Interpreting INF</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd and three
influential committee chairmen are pushing for an amendment to the
Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces Treaty that would limit future
administration interpretations of the accord.
   The amendment, which the administration says would be
unconstitutional, was sparked by Senate Democrats' wrath over
President Reagan's interpretation of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic
Missile Treaty. They have charged that he interpreted the pact too
broadly so he could justify development of the ``Star Wars''
missile defense system.
   Under their proposed attachment to the INF treaty, future
interpretations would be based not just on the text of the treaty,
but also on the voluminous testimony given during weeks of
ratification hearings since Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev signed the pact in December.
   A congressional source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
the decision to tack the amendment on was made at a luncheon Friday
attended by Byrd, Foreign Relations Committee chairman Claiborne
Pell of Rhode Island, Armed Services Committee chairman Sam Nunn of
Georgia and Intelligence Committee co-chairman David Boren of
Oklahoma.
   The original author of the proposal was Sen. Joseph Biden Jr.,
D-Del.
   Their condition will be presented to the foreign relations panel
during consideration of the treaty next week, the source said.
   In a commentary attached to the proposed amendment, the senators
have said their purpose was not to resolve the dispute over the ABM
Treaty.
   ``Rather the provision is intended to reaffirm certain
constitutional principles which have been brought into question
during the `reinterpretation' debate,'' the commentary said.
   Many Democrats have argued that the ABM treaty, as outlined
during the ratification hearings in 1972, prevents certain Star
Wars testing and development. The administration has asserted that
its interpretation _ based on the text and the record of
negotiations with the Soviets _ permits the development.
   The Democratic chairmen already have expressed their support for
the INF treaty provisions, which would eliminate all land-based
missiles with ranges between 300 and 3,125 miles.
   Ratification by the required two-thirds of the Senate is
expected, but the attachments of conditions opposed by the
administration would be a complicating factor that could require
renegotiations with the Soviets.
   In a letter to Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., a member of the
foreign relations panel, the White House reiterated its fears about
the amendment and said its views were endorsed by the State,
Defense and Justice departments and the Arms Control and
Disarmament Agency.
   The letter, signed by Arthur B. Culvahouse, counsel to the
president and made public Friday, said the resolution is
``seriously flawed.''
   He acknowledged that for domestic purposes a president would
adhere to an interpretation generally agreed to by the Senate, but
he said the proposed amendment would go too far, by binding an
administration to ``all statements made by officials of the
executive branch during ratification proceedings.''
   These would include ``answers to over 1,000 questions submitted
by members of the Senate, no matter how trivial or how unimportant
the issue addressed may be to the Senate's advice and consent
deliberations.''
   ``The result might be two INF treaties, one binding domestically
against the president and a second one binding internationally
between the United States and the Soviet Union,'' Culvahouse said.
   That would favor Moscow ``because the Soviet Union is not and
cannot be bound by our domestic processes.''
   The proposal ``only serves the interests of confusion,
ambiguity, confrontation and uncertainty,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
