<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 0013EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MortonThiokol-Fire 1stLd-Writethru a0887essursulaandressis
03-19 0689</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Morton Thiokol-Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0887,0702</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Force Finds Fault With Morton Thiokol MX Assembly</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to CLARIY that Air Force accuses
Morton Thiokol of failure to implement safety measures; PICKS UP
4th graf pvs, `The plant's ...'; SUBS 14th graf pvs, `Rocky Raab
...' to UPDATE with comment.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VERN ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Air Force report Friday on a fatal fire
at an MX missile assembly plant said Morton Thiokol Inc. failed to
provide an adequate remote-control system or fully implement other
safety measures recommended after a ``near miss'' six months
earlier.
   The fire Dec. 29 killed five workmen who were manually removing
the steel core from the first stage of an MX motor into which
propellant had been poured and hardened.
   The Air Force concluded the fire was caused either by friction
or static electricity. In the accident, 100,000 pounds of solid
rocket fuel ignited in a fireball at the company's Wasatch
Operations plant 90 miles northwest of here.
   The plant's remote control system includes a video monitor to
allow workers to perform the procedure from a bunker a quarter-mile
away, but ``design deficiencies'' prevented them from using it as
specified, the Air Force said.
   ``The video system ... did not provide the required visibility.
Thus, remote operation requirements were circumvented,'' according
to the report, which said it was common practice among workers not
to use the camera.
   Morton Thiokol officials have said such deviations were only
occasional and were not known to management.
   Installation of a video camera for remote-control use was among
the Air Force's recommendations after a ``near miss'' on May 20,
1987, consisting of ``a flash, followed by a loud report, smoke and
fumes,'' the Air Force said.
   Later inspection indicated a small piece of the solid propellant
had ignited, possibly from friction caused by grit, said the report
issued by the Air Force Inspection and Safety Center at Norton Air
Force Base in California.
   ``In both cases, the operators were raising the core, and the
probable causes were similar,'' the Air Force said. ``Many of the
recommended changes resulting from (the May incident) had not been
fully implemented at the time of the (December) mishap.''
   Other Air Force recommendations stemming from the ``near miss''
included grounding and other measures to reduce static.
   When the Dec. 29 fire broke out, the recommended grounding was
incomplete, and operators didn't understand the requirements or
follow them properly, the report said.
   The manual used by the workers to remove the core ``was vague,
written at a reading level well above that of the average operator,
confusing, hard to follow (sometimes impossible), contradictory and
incomplete,'' the report said.
   The findings were released a day after Morton Thiokol officials
released the results of their own investigation and vowed to appeal
state citations, alleging willful and serious violations, that
carry $30,000 in penalties.
   Rocky Raab, Morton Thiokol spokesman, denied Air Force
allegations company routinely failed to follow written procedures.
``We would take issue with the word routinely,'' he said. ``We
would say sometimes, or occasionally.''
   The company said Thursday that its procedures were clear and
that it did not know why the five men failed to follow them by
entering the assembly building during an operation that should have
been handled by remote control.
   The rocket motors are filled with fuel in a semi-liquid state.
The core is raised from the rocket motor by a hydraulic lift after
the fuel has hardened.
   The Air Force recommended among other thigns that operating
procedures be rewritten, remote operations be properly designed and
enforced and that the company ensure compliance with procedures.
   Since the accident, Morton Thiokol and the Air Force have been
studying ways to reduce the risks of ignition by friction or static.
   The accident has held up MX missile production until the cause
and corrective measures could be determined. The fire caused $6.2
million damage to the assembly building.
   Ed Garrison, president of the company's aerospace group, said
Morton Thiokol hopes to reach an agreement on corrective measures
with the Air Force within two weeks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
