<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Britain-Bacon,0151</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Briton to Display his Art Work in Moscow</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Francis Bacon, whose paintings of hideously
distorted human figures have made him the highest-paid living
British artist, will show his works in the Soviet Union, the
British Council said.
   The council, which promotes Britain abroad, said Friday that 43
Bacon canvases will be displayed in a two-month exhibition opening
in Moscow in September.
   The show, requested by the Union of Soviet Artists, will be the
first in Moscow by a contemporary British artist.
   ``Bacon himself was delighted to hear that Soviet artists admire
him, and he will go to Moscow with his paintings,'' said council
spokesman John Nickson.
   A record $1.7 million for a work of the 78-year-old artist was
offered last May. The offer was for his 1953 picture, ``Study for
Portrait 1-8,'' one of eight paintings of Pope Innocent X.
</TEXT>
