<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 0355EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalRdp Bjt   03-19 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, Bjt,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Hoping To Gain Ground On One Another In Kansas, Puerto
Rico</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Kansas and Puerto Rico claimed political center stage for the
weekend as Democratic presidential candidates sought to gain ground
on one another and George Bush expected to bolster his already
commanding lead by adding a few offshore delegates.
   On the Democratic side, 39 delegates were at stake in Kansas
caucuses today and another 51 were up for grabs in Sunday's primary
in Puerto Rico.
   Among Republicans, the vice president was expected to dominate
the winner-take-all vote in Puerto Rico and pick up all 14 GOP
delegates. Kansas Republicans already have made their wishes known,
favoring home-state contender Bob Dole.
   Michael Dukakis, Albert Gore Jr. and Jesse Jackson all
campaigned in Kansas during the week, while Richard Gephardt
instead focused his energies on Michigan's March 26 caucuses and
Paul Simon straggled along behind.
   Dukakis, his prospects enhanced by a strong organizing effort,
had a slight edge heading into today's Kansas caucuses.
   ``We've been organized in Kansas for eight months,'' said
Dukakis' state campaign chairman, state Sen. Paul Feleciano. ``...
I think we'll get 20 to 24 of the 39 delegates still to be picked.''
   Gore's state campaign chairman, state Sen. Joe Norvell, was
hoping the Tennessee senator's late forays into Kansas ``could
minimize what I would consider an early lead for Gov. Dukakis.''
   Jackson had out-organized Gore, but supporters conceded that not
enough counties were organized to claim a majority of the delegates.
   Gephardt, struggling to recover from the thrashings he took on
Super Tuesday and again in Illinois, was hoping Michigan would
revive his flagging campaign.
   Eighteen members of Congress flew to Michigan on Friday to
campaign for the Missouri congressman but a poll showed him
trailing well behind Dukakis and Jackson.
   ``We're going to make political history in Michigan, just as we
did in Iowa,'' said Gephardt, who had his best showing to date in
Iowa's leadoff caucus.
   Cash-poor Simon was in Pennsylvania on Friday for a series of
fund-raisers. He continue to predict none of the Democrats would
lock up the nomination before the national convention in July.
   ``If you're talking about buying the nomination, I can't do
that,'' he said. ``If you're talking about winning the nomination,
I can do that.''
   Gore spent Friday vote-hunting in Puerto Rico, where he said
that he would consider allowing the territory to be exempt from the
federal minimum wage and that he favored letting the territory
decide itself whether to become a U.S. state.
   Dukakis released a videotaped address in Spanish in which he
pledged to work to increase payments to Puerto Ricans under the
Medicaid, Aid to Families with Dependent Children and Supplemental
Social Security programs.
   Bush was the only Republican to mount an organizing campaign in
Puerto Rico.
   Dole's weakened campaign, meanwhile, continued to shrink, with
only about 10 to 12 aides left on the payroll, according to
spokeswoman Dale Tate.
   Pat Robertson, campaigning in California, conceded Bush had an
overwhelming delegate lead but pledged to stay in the race because
``there has to be a rallying point for conservatives.''
   Other political activity on tap today: Gephardt hoped to turn
his victory in last month's South Dakota primary into delegates at
today's state convention, and Dukakis and Jackson, the
front-runners in the Texas primary on March 8, were expected to
divvy up most of the 64 delegates at that state's caucuses.
</TEXT>
