<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Salvador-ElectionMonitoring     03-19 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador-Election Monitoring,455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Lawmakers To Monitor Salvadoran Elections, Rebels Warn Of
Disruption</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional delegation was bound for El
Salvador today to monitor legislative and municipal elections that
leftist forces have threatened to disrupt.
   President Reagan selected the group of Republicans and mostly
conservative Democrats to watch Sunday's election and report back
to him, officials said Friday.
   ``Our presence there is mainly one to deter any fraud (by the
participating political parties) and to objectively and fairly
report what we see happening,'' said Rep. John G. Rowland, R-Conn.,
a delegation member.
   Andy Fisher, an aide to Sen. Richard G. Lugar, R-Ind., said the
lawmakers will visit polling places in San Salvador and the
countryside despite the pinpointing of the polls as military
targets by the leftist forces.
   But Rowland said the threats may keep the delegation away from
the polls. The delegation's presence at the polls would ``show the
voters we're not afraid,'' he said, but added ``I'm not sure if
we're doing that.''
   ``We cannot stop violence,'' Rowland said.
   The delegation, headed by Lugar and Rep. John P. Murtha, D-Pa.,
was scheduled to leave Andrews Air Force Base today and return late
Sunday night or early Monday morning.
   The U.S.-backed Salvadoran government headed by President Jose
Napoleon Duarte is holding elections Sunday for mayors and councils
in the country's 262 municipalities and for all 60 seats in the
Legislative Assembly.
   Leftist groups have vowed to ban road transportation during the
elections to disrupt voting, and said polling places will be
``military objectives.'' The rebels maintain that peace must be
achieved before any election is held.
   The main electoral opposition to the ruling Christian Democratic
Party is Arena, a rightist group.
   ``This particular election is a test for democracy, not only
because of the hazards proposed by the rebels, but perhaps because
many citizens of El Salvador, after five elections, have lost some
of their enthusiasm for democracy,'' Lugar said in a statement.
   Rowland said the election, which has not gained widespread
attention because it does not include a presidential race, is
important because Duarte's party could lose its slim majority in
the assembly.
   ``There could be a definite change in the makeup of the
Assembly,'' the congressman said in a telephone interview from
Connecticut.
   The congressional group will be briefed by State Department
officials in San Salvador before monitoring the elections.
   The House members include Reps. Rowland; Murtha; Beverly B.
Byron, D-Md.; John R. Kasich, R-Ohio; Mickey Edwards, R-Okla.; and
Alan B. Mollohan, D-W.Va., according to Rowland aide Harry Phillips.
   Senators include Lugar, Frank H. Murkowski, R-Ala.; Christopher
S. Bond, R-Mo.; said Fisher.
   The Salvadoran Defense Ministry said about 53,000 troops will be
deployed to provide election security.
</TEXT>
