<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AntarcticRow     03-19 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Antarctic Row,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Adventurers Recount Unprecedented Row To Antarctica</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ned Gillette's first thought after being knocked
into the treacherous waters off Cape Horn was not about his fate,
but whether the ``Sea Tomato'' would survive the wintry gale in its
quest to sail to Antarctica.
   Moments later, Gillette was pulled back aboard the high-tech
rowboat _ never fully tested in open ocean _ to join three other
adventurers who hoped it was possible to row 600 miles across the
treacherous Drake Passage from South America.
   On March 7, after suffering three knockdowns in heavy seas and
skirting icebergs, the four waddled about Nelson Island off
Antarctica like the penguins that greeted them at the end of the
voyage.
   ``You should see what it's like to try to walk on land after
being thrown around at sea for 12 days,'' said Gillette, whose
arrival in Antarctica ended a 4{-year quest that included an
unsuccessful expedition last year.
   ``Until we made it, we weren't really sure it could be done,''
Gillette, 42, a native of Stowe, Vt., said Friday.
   While the crew bailed out flooded cabins and rowed their 28-foot
boat through 100-foot swells, a Massachusetts weather station each
day fed them with sophisticated forecasts and the boat's location
was tracked by satellite.
   The ``Sea Tomato,'' so-called because of its red color, was
built for $17,000 and equipped with state-of-the-art navigational
and survival equipment. After waiting for nearly a month for proper
weather conditions, the expedition almost ended in disaster Feb. 22
off the Chilean coast. Twelve hours after leaving under sail, a
heavy squall erupted and tipped the craft, sending Gillette
overboard. Gillette, an experienced moutaineer, was saved by a line
fastened to the boat.
   In the next several days, the boat took two more spills, casting
crew members Jay Morrison, 34, and Fred Trombly, 32, into the sea.
   Three days out, the crew took down the sails and began to row in
shifts, sometimes all night. They creeped southward at an average
rate of 2.3 knots, about walking speed.
   Crew member Mark Eichenberger, 35, said the raging Drake Passage
seas and variable weather made the expedition more challenging than
other rowing voyages across the Atlantic and Pacific.
   ``Why did we do it?'' said Morrison. ``Because nobody had ever
done it before. That's a pretty good reason.''
</TEXT>
