<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Czechoslovak-Maneuvers,0147</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Observers to Be Allowed to Use Cameras at War Games</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign observers of
Czechoslovak-Soviet military exercises will be allowed for the
first time to use cameras and tape recorders, Lt. Gen. Jiri Brychta
told a news conference.
   He said 22 countries have applied to send a total of 43
observers to the maneuvers to be held by 17,400 Soviet and
Czechoslovak military personnel in western Czechoslovakia March
22-28.
   Brychta, first deputy chief of the general staff, said Friday
that the use of cameras and recorders by the observers ``should
make their work easier and goes beyond the framework of conditions
provided for by the Stockholm document.''
   Under the Stockholm agreement on security and cooperation in
Europe, the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact and North Atlantic Treaty
Organization are to allow foreign observers to view large military
maneuvers.
</TEXT>
