<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Biaggi-Wedtech     03-19 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biaggi-Wedtech,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witness: Meese Interceded With Pentagon For Wedtech</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Wedtech Corp. executive says a friend
of Attorney General Edwin Meese III told him that Meese intervened
with the Pentagon to help get a $24 million Navy contract awarded
to the Bronx contractor.
   Mario Moreno made the revelation Friday in his fourth day of
testimony in the racketeering trial of Rep. Mario Biaggi and six
others accused of bribery and influence peddling involving Wedtech.
   Moreno said he met Meese's friend, San Francisco lawyer E.
Robert Wallach, in December 1983. He said he asked Wallach to get
Meese ``to change the Navy's mind'' about awarding Wedtech only the
less lucrative part of a contract to build bridge pontoons. Meese
was presidential counselor at the time.
   Meese said he would ask then-Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger
to call then-Navy Secretary John Lehman, Wallach told Moreno.
   In January 1984, a month after Wallach told Moreno of Meese's
alleged intercession, Wedtech received the approval making it
eligible for the entire pontoon contract, which it signed in April
1984.
   Moreno testified previously that Wallach told him Meese also had
interceded on Wedtech's behalf with the Commerce Department over
another defense contract.
   Moreno had described Meese's alleged intervention for the
pontoon contract in an affidavit disclosed last October at a Senate
hearing in Washington. At that time, both Meese and Weinberger said
they did not remember the incident.
   The contract was to build floating bridge units to link supply
ships with U.S. rapid deployment forces.
   Wedtech, a $100 million-a-year defense contractor before it
filed for bankruptcy in 1986, grew from a small Bronx machine shop
through a series of no-bid defense contracts.
   The company was able to obtain those contracts through a Small
Business Administration program for minority-controlled businesses,
but federal prosecutors claim that Wedtech falsely portrayed itself
as being eligible.
   Wallach, Meese's former personal lawyer, is under indictment for
allegedly taking bribes from Wedtech officials in exchange for
trying to influence Meese and others.
   Last December, a special prosecutor in Washington said there was
insufficient evidence to charge Meese with wrongdoing in the
Wedtech case.
   Moreno, one of four ex-Wedtech officials who have pleaded guilty
to bribing public officials and other crimes, also testified that
the company paid former Bronx Borough President Stanley Simon and
Biaggi's law firm $50,000 each for their help in a real estate deal
with the city.
   Moreno said Wedtech did not have the proper facilities to
assemble and test the pontoons and wanted to lease city-owned land
in the Bronx.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880319-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 0448EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Mideast     03-19 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Mideast,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Envoy Goes to Mideast To Discuss U.S. Peace Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration, looking for an
``early response'' to its Mideast peace plan, is sending special
envoy Philip Habib to Jordan, Egypt, Saudi Arabia and Morocco to
discuss the proposal.
   The State Department said Habib will consult next week with
officials in the Arab countries and brief them on the discussions
held this week in Washington with Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir.
   He also is expected to ask Jordan for its response to the
proposal formulated by Secretary of State George P. Shultz for
Israeli-Arab talks about Palestinian self-rule in the occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip.
   ``We're looking for an early response to our proposals from the
parties in the region,'' department spokesman Charles Redman said
Friday.
   Shultz's plan envisions that talks on self-rule would begin May
1 between Jordan, Israel, Palestinians and any other Arabs wishing
to take part, under the auspices of the United States, the Soviet
Union, China, England and France. The plan also calls for talks to
start Dec. 1 about the future of the West Bank and Gaza Strip that
Israel captured from the Arabs in the 1967 Mideast war.
   ``We have an ambitious timetable,'' Redman said. ``This is an
active process. ... We're intensively engaged in it.''
   Shamir already has rejected the idea of an international peace
conference, fearing it would bring pressure on Israel to cede
occupied lands, but he promised to bring up the plan next week for
a vote by his divided cabinet.
   ``We continue to be encouraged by the active and serious
consideration being given to this proposal by all the parties
concerned,'' Redman said.
   Habib, a retired ambassador who negotiated between Israel and
the Arabs in the early 1980s, undertook a one-day trip to Jordan at
the end of January to sound out King Hussein about the Shultz plan.
This time he will spend less than a week on his mission, Redman
said.
   The United States also is consulting with Syria on the Shultz
plan, but this is being done through the embassies in Washington
and Damascus, according to a State Department official who spoke
only on condition of anonymity.
   Habib's stop in Morocco is designed to bring that country into
the process as a moderating influence. Morocco, a former French
colony, enjoys good standing with both the Arabs and Israel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
