<DOCNO> AP880319-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 0818EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CocaineConspiracy     03-19 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cocaine Conspiracy,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airline Employees Convicted Of Cocain Smuggling At Kennedy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five former passenger service agents for
airlines have been convicted of participating in an eight-year
conspiracy to smuggle $1.5 billion worth of cocaine through Kennedy
International Airport.
   After five days of deliberations, a jury in U.S. District Court
in Brooklyn returned guilty verdicts Friday against the five men
and another defendant on all counts of the nine-count indictment.
   The defendants were among 56 people arrested last year in
connection with the drug smuggling operation. Of those arrested,
most have either pleaded guilty or been convicted in state and
federal courts. Six others remain fugitives.
   All six defendants were convicted of the most serious charge of
conspiracy, which carries a possible life sentence. Sentencing is
expected to take place within six weeks.
   Federal prosecutors charged during the six-week trial that four
of the airline employees used their positions to circumvent customs
in the United States and Brazil to bring several tons of cocaine
into the country between 1979 and 1987.
   The two lead defendants _ Jean Marie Chapoteau, 50, of Queens, a
former passenger service agent for Pan American World Airways, and
Pedro DaSilva, 49, of Miami, who held a similar position at Varig
Airlines _ were charged with running separate smuggling operations
at their respective airlines.
   Two other Pan Am service agents _ Vincent Cicali, 29, of Queens,
and Bruce Duignan, 31, of Massapequa _ were accused of working for
a third smuggling operation at Kennedy run by another former Pan Am
employee, Aart Vanwort.
   Vanwort pleaded guilty to a conspiracy charge earlier this year
and was one of the prosecution's key witnesses during the trial. He
is awaiting sentencing.
   The other defendants were also convicted of purchasing portions
of the cocaine smuggled into the country. They are Michael Crown,
34, of Queens, a former passenger service agent for Pan Am, and
Steven Finn, 33, an auctioneer from Boston.
   The case stemmed from an investigation by the federal Drug
Enforcement Agency, the U.S. Customs Service, the Internal Revenue
Service and the Port Authority police.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
