<HEAD>Warning to Congress from Palau Lawmakers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of senators from the Pacific Island
chain of Palau says problems with drugs there have been ``permitted
to develop unchecked'' during 40 years of U.S. rule and could best
be solved by a new sovereign government.
   The seven Palau lawmakers on Friday accused a House subcommittee
of unreasonably delaying their country's independence with
unfounded charges of corruption and narcotics trafficking.
   The Palau senators raised the issues in a letter to Ron de Lugo,
the Virgin Islands delegate, who is chairman of a House
subcommittee on insular and international affairs.
   The senators admitted the islands had drug and other problems
but said they had been ``permitted to develop unchecked'' during 40
years of U.S. rule, and could be attacked more effectively now by
the new government with financing promised under the
recently-approved compact of free association with the United
States.
