<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Salvador     03-19 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Try to Enforce Traffic Ban on Eve of Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taxi driver Alfonso Valdez
stopped at a red light, and four young men jumped in the car. The
one in the front seat and the one directly behind him pulled
pistols.
   ```We're a guerrilla urban commando cell, and you should know
better than to take your cab out when we've called a transport
ban,''' Valdez quoted one of the men as telling him. They ordered
him out of the cab, set it afire and fled.
   The cab was one of several vehicles burned Friday by guerrillas
trying to enforce the indefinite traffic ban they called to
dissuade voters from participating in Sunday's elections.
   Even so, the government and small-time entrepreneurs with pickup
trucks kept a lot of urban traffic moving.
   Salvadorans cast ballots Sunday to elect all the members of the
60-seat National Assembly and municipal officials nationwide.
Leftist guerrillas fighting the U.S.-backed government since 1979
say the people's will cannot be expressed by voting in wartime.
   Intercity bus transport was reduced by about 80 percent
nationwide, according to dispatchers quoted in telephone and radio
reports.
   The privately owned radio station YSU, with correspondents in
almost all of El Salvador's 14 provinces, said guerrillas burned
eight vehicles in the eastern province of Usulutan.
   The station said two buses, two tractor-trailers, two pickups,
one jeep and one taxi were burned there. No injuries were reported.
   One person died in the capital when an extremely overcrowded
pickup truck overturned. Eighteen people were reported injured in
the accident.
   Scores of pickups with up to 40 people packed in truckbeds and
standing on bumpers circulated in the capital, partially taking the
place of privately owned buses, few of which were seen on the road.
   Rides in the trucks cost up to 60 cents, or five times the
normal bus fare.
   The government put several dozen blue and white state-owned
buses on the streets, and they too were overcrowded, with people
riding on roof luggage racks, hanging from the doors and standing
on the bumpers. Army trucks also were used for passenger transport.
   But many _ probably most _ people simply walked to work.
   Ten yards from where Valdez recounted the Friday evening
hijacking, in a middle class neighborhood of this capital, what was
left of the yellow Toyota smoldered. The guerrillas had run down
the road about a half hour before, and firemen had just
extinguished the blaze.
   ``What could I do?'' said Valdez, 49. ``They were armed.''
   He said his only remaining fear was informing the woman who
owned the taxi that it was now a black hulk.
   Dozens of children stood around, enthralled by the spectacle.
Their parents, who also had gathered to watch the flames consume
the car, criticized the guerrillas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880319-0031 </DOCNO>
