<HEAD>Poll Finds California Delegates Like Dukakis, Cuomo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIVERSIDE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Potential delegates to California's
state Democratic convention favor Michael Dukakis over his
presidential rivals, but they still prefer non-candidate Mario
Cuomo, according to poll results published today.
   The poll of 217 of 1,200 potential delegates to the convention
this weekend in Palm Springs was conducted by the Riverside
Press-Enterprise.
   Asked to rank their favorites among the declared candidates, the
party regulars lined up 38 percent for Dukakis, 22 percent for
Jesse Jackson, 10 percent for Paul Simon, 8 percent for Albert Gore
Jr. and 3 percent for Richard Gephardt. Eighteen percent were
undecided.
   That changed dramatically when the list was expanded to include
New York Gov. Mario Cuomo. Cuomo was the favorite of 34 percent,
Dukakis 20 percent, Jackson 16 percent, Simon 7 percent, Gore 6
percent and Gephardt 3 percent, with 15 percent undecided.
   On Sunday, Monday and Tuesday, the paper interviewed potential
delegates picked at random from a list provided by the party. Max
Neiman, a University of California, Riverside, political science
professor with polling experience, reviewed the methods and
calculated the sample had a 5.5 percentage point margin of error.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fewer New York Democrats Think Cuomo Will Run</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While the number of New York Democrats who
think Gov. Mario Cuomo should run for president keeps edging up,
the number who think he will run is declining, a poll indicates.
   Results of a poll released Friday by the Marist College
Institute for Public Opinion found that while 59 percent of the
Democrats surveyed said Cuomo should run, only 24 percent said they
thought he would. In a January poll by Marist, 58 percent of the
Democrats said Cuomo should run and 36 percent said they thought
Cuomo would run.
   ``He's pleased that the people are taking him at his word,''
Cuomo spokeswoman Anne Crowley said of the governor's reaction to
the poll results.
   The poll also indicated that Michael Dukakis and Jesse Jackson
appear to be in a two-man race among likely New York Democratic
primary voters with the crucial April 19 presidential primary just
a month away.
   The poll found that 37 percent of the 459 likely Democratic
voters surveyed said they would vote for Dukakis while 28 percent
said they would back Jackson. The other Democratic candidates
trailed far behind.
   The poll had a margin of error of plus or minus 5 percentage
points.
</TEXT>
