<HEAD>Ex-Terrorist Gains Readmission To The Bar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A co-founder of the notorious Red Army Faction
leftist gang, having renounced terrorism, can now practice law
again in West Berlin.
   Horst Mahler, 52, who spent six years in prison on a terrorism
conviction, regained his license Friday after a November ruling by
the West German Supreme Court, said West Berlin Justice Department
spokesman Cornel Christoffel.
   The court endorsed an appeal by Mahler against an earlier
refusal by West Berlin's judicial authorities to allow him to work
again as a lawyer.
   The high court pointed out that Mahler distanced himself from
his earlier actions and denounced terrorism.
   Mahler was arrested in West Berlin in 1970 and was convicted
four years later on bank robbery charges and for helping notorious
terrorist Andreas Baader escape from jail.
   He was sentenced to 14 years in prison but was released in 1980
after several public statements condemning terrorism and Red Army
Faction methods.
