<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Sikhs     03-19 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Sikhs,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sectarian Violence Kills 10 in Punjab in Two Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspected Sikh extremists today shot to
death five members of a Sikh family, including a two-year old girl,
in a raid on the family's farmhouse in Punjab state, police said.
   Police also recovered the bodies of five other people killed
Friday in attacks blamed on Sikh radicals, including three Sikhs
shot to death in the village of Manda in Amritsar District and an
unidentified man killed in nearby Janti village.
   A Sikh farmer, identified as Amrik Singh, was shot to death
Friday night in Jalandhar District, police said.
   The killings raised to at least 480 the number of people who
have died in attacks blamed on the militants since Jan. 1. Last
year, more than 1,000 people were killed in Punjab by the
extremists, who have been waging a guerrilla war since 1982 for an
independent Sikh homeland in Punjab.
   The latest attack came at 12:30 a.m. in the village of Butt,
about 17 miles north of the Sikh holy city of Amritsar, police said.
   They said four gunmen shot farmer Balbir Singh and his family as
they slept. The other victims were his wife, a son, a
daughter-in-law and his granddaughter, Amandeep, who was 2.
   After the shootings, the extremists set fire to the farmhouse
and fled, police said.
   The motive for the attack was not known, but the militants have
killed a number of moderate Sikhs who disagree with their
separatist goals. The extremists also have accused some Sikhs of
being ``police informers'' and have killed others who refused to
pay extortion money.
   Sikhs, whose sect was founded about 500 years ago as an
alternative to Hinduism and Islam, claim they are discriminated
against by India's majority Hindus. Although a minority of about 2
percent in India, Sikhs are a majority in Punjab.
</TEXT>
