<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SriLanka-Village     03-19 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka-Village,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Villagers Fear Return of Tamil Rebel Attackers</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GALMETIYAWA, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When dusk settles in this
seemingly tranquil eastern Sri Lankan village, people carrying
straw mats, pillows and blankets leave their huts and trek to a
Buddhist temple to spend the night.
   Galmetiyawa, inhabited mostly by members of the majority
Sinhalese community, was attacked by separatist Tamil rebels at
dusk Monday. Fifteen villagers were killed.
   Now, residents sleep in the temple, fearing the attackers will
come again.
   The rebels, dressed in military uniforms, came out of nearby
jungle. In 30 minutes, they shot and killed four children, five
women and six men.
   Villagers said the rebels threw some of the victims' bodies into
a hut and set it on fire. A Sri Lankan army lieutenant and two
soldiers, who came to the village after hearing gunfire, chased the
rebels away.
   Marasinghe Ratnasiri, a member of a home guard that once
protected the village, complained that a peace accord with the
Tamils had taken away the local men's weapons.
   ``When we had guns, the rebels did not attack our village,''
said Marasinghe, 28, a farmer with two children. ``Now, they know
we are defenseless.''
   The rebels have been blamed for the killings of more than 110
people, most of them Sinhalese, in Sri Lanka's Eastern Province
this month as part of their bloody four-year campaign for a
separate homeland.
   Colonel Lakshman Wijayaratne, a Sri Lankan army officer, said
the spate of killings aims to halt a government resettlement
program aimed at encouraging Sinhalese to migrate to the north and
east.
   He predicted there would be more rebel attacks in reaction to
the settling of Sinhalese in what Tamils view as their traditional
homeland, saying it was not possible to protect every village in
the area.
   Many rebels fled to this part of the Indian Ocean island in
October, when Indian troops attacked the Tamil stronghold of Jaffna
in the north.
   India deployed soldiers in Sri Lanka to disarm the rebels after
they denounced a New Delhi-sponsored peace accord with Sri Lanka's
government aimed at ending the fighting by creating some measure of
autonomy in the north and east where Tamils are most numerous.
   Under the India-Sri Lanka peace accord signed in July, Sri
Lankan soldiers in the north and east are to keep to their barracks
while Indian troops take on the rebels.
   There are more than 50,000 Indian troops in Sri Lanka, but the
number in the Eastern Province is uncertain.
   Galmetiyawa is 30 miles west of the coastal city of Trincomalee.
Most of the recent killings have taken place around Trincomalee,
and 2,000 Sri Lankan soldiers are posted there along with Indian
soldiers.
   About 1,000 Tamil rebels are believed to be in the district.
   Tamils, who make up about 18 percent of the country's 16 million
people, claim they are discriminated against by the majority
Sinhalese, who control the government and military.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
