<1ST_LINE>r i PM-People-Grebenshchikov     03-19 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Grebenshchikov,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Rock Star to Record Album With U.S. Musicians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock star Boris Grebenshchikov has signed a
contract to cut an album of his songs with American musicians.
Soviet officials said it would be the first American-produced
Soviet rock album released in the United States.
   Grebenshchikov told a news conference Friday that his songs,
some in Russian and others in English, will be performed by his
group Aquarium and American musicians who are to be chosen later.
   Sporting a pony tail, blue jeans and six rings, Grebenshchikov
seemed ill at ease alongside American and Soviet officials in suits
who announced the deal. An earlier record on which he performed was
released in the United States without the Soviet government's
consent.
   Grebenshchikov is to record the album in New York and Los
Angeles this summer for CBS Records, which plans distribution in
the United States and Europe, said his American lawyer, Ina
Meibach. The record also will be released in the Soviet Union,
Soviet officials said.
   Kenneth Schaffer, vice president of New York-based Belka
International which helped put together the deal, said he was
confident Grebenshchikov will become popular in the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
