<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 0642EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WritersAwards     03-19 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Awards,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strikebound Writers Guild Awards Its Members</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romantic comedies swept the top
movie-writing honors as the strikebound Writers Guild of America
handed out its 40th annual awards at a ceremony largely shunned by
studio executives.
   Steve Martin took best screenplay for ``Roxanne,'' an adaptation
of ``Cyrano de Bergerac'' by Edmund Rostand, while John Patrick
Shanley won best original screenwriting for ``Moonstruck.''
   CBS came away as the night's big winner, taking top honors in
seven categories, including best TV spot-news script.
   NBC and ABC each took four awards. The Public Broadcasting
System had three and Home Box Office won one for best
variety-music, award tribute or special event for ``Will Rogers:
Look Back in Laughter.''
   Neither Shanley nor Martin was on hand to accept the awards from
presenter Sylvester Stallone, who wore his ``Rambo''-length hair in
a ponytail.
   Martin's acceptance speech was read by an associate. In it, he
called Rostand ``a great first-draft guy.''
   Martin also provided an ``If-I-Lose'' speech. ``You pigs, you
idiots. You wouldn't know a good script if it walked up to you and
vomited on your shoes,'' his associate read as the audience rocked
with laughter.
   In addition to writing the script, Martin starred in
``Roxanne,'' a summer hit from Columbia Pictures, along with Daryl
Hannah.
   In ``Moonstruck,'' a darkly romantic film nominated for six
Academy Awards, Cher stars as an Italian widow in New York who
finds herself engaged to one man but in love with his brother.
   The dinner extravaganza came on the 11th day of a strike by the
9,000-member guild against the Alliance of Motion Picture and
Television Producers.
   References to the strike flavored the evening, despite guild
Executive Director Brian Walton's admonition, ``This is a night to
celebrate writers and writing.''
   But WGA President George Kirgo told the black-tie audience:
``The Writers Guild of America is stronger, more powerful, more
cohesive, more unified than at any other time in our history.''
   Studios were conspicuously absent from the banquet tables. Only
Columbia and 20th Century Fox were represented.
   Before the dinner, the WGA announced winners of special awards
from its Board of Directors.
   The husband-and-wife screenwriting team of Irving Ravetch and
Harriet Frank won the prized Screen Laurel Award honoring them for
their body of work, which includes such movies as ``Norma Rae,''
``Hud'' and ``Murphy's Romance.''
   Longtime television writing team Bob Schiller and Bob Weiskopf,
who wrote over the past 35 years for such series as ``I Love
Lucy,'' ``All In The Family,'' ``Maude'' and ``The Red Skelton
Show,'' were named co-winners of the Paddy Chayevsky Laurel Award
for Television.
   The award goes to a writer who has advanced the literature of
television and made outstanding contributions as a television
writer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
