<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 0647EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Jane's-SriLanka     03-19 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jane's-Sri Lanka,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jane's Says India Has Control of Sri Lanka But With Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India may have to maintain a military presence in
Sri Lanka ``for many months, if not years to come,'' according to
Jane's Defense Weekly.
   The authoritative magazine said in this week's issue that India
has an armed force of 65,000 in Sri Lanka under an accord to disarm
Tamil separatists, and almost total control of the island country
off India's southern coast.
   It added the Indian army has suffered considerable casualties
and a host of problems in trying to keep peace, and its mission is
far from over.
   The magazine said ``India's influence on Sri Lanka is now total
and even in matters of foreign policy, Sri Lanka is controlled from
New Delhi.''
   But ``in spite of having considerable numbers of troops, the
Indian peacekeeping force has problems in neutralizing the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Elam.'' The Tigers are the main Tamil
guerrilla group waging a four-year war for creation of a separate
state in northern and eastern Sri Lanka.
   India, which has a politically powerful Tamil population of 60
million in its southern regions, sent a military force to Sri Lanka
last July under a peace agreement signed with the Sri Lankan
government.
   Under the accord, limited autonomy would be given to the Tamils
in exchange for an arms surrender by the guerrillas.
   The Sri Lankan army, mistrusted by Tamils because most officers
come from the majority Sinhalese population, was to stop fighting
the rebels. The Tamils, however, denounced the accord and have been
fighting the Indian troops.
   Tamils, most of whom are Hindus, make up 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people and the Buddhist Sinhalese 75 percent.
   Jane's said India has six divisional headquarters, at least 15
brigades, and paramilitary, parachute, police and other forces in
Sri Lanka.
   It said 500 Indian soldiers have been killed and an estimated
2,500 wounded. India has said 400 soldiers and at least 1,100
rebels have been killed died in the fighting.
   Jane's said the Indians' high casualty rate could be attributed
to the army's desire to avoid civilian casualties, its lack of
experience in fighting guerrillas and its ``politically motivated''
orders to move as quickly as possible.
   ``This resulted in troops being committed to operations within
hours of landing in unfamiliar territory,'' the article said.
</TEXT>
