<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MissingBoy     03-19 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Missing Boy,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Boys Held Captive By Drug Dealers; Two Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drug dealers shot two of three boys they had
abducted to work for them after the boys apparently failed to pay
them for crack, police said.
   Joseph Jones, 12, told police he managed to escape from the
kidnappers early Friday. The boy said he was abducted last Saturday
by two young men from New York who forced him and his friends to
sell crack, a derivative of cocaine.
   The body of Cornell Williams, 15, was found Friday afternoon
near Philadelphia International Airport with two gunshot wounds in
the head, according to the city medical examiner's office.
   Williams' brother, Anthony Williams, 13, was found Tuesday along
railroad tracks near downtown Philadelphia with a bullet wound in
the head, police said. He died the next day.
   Joseph told police the boys owed their captors $500 for crack,
but the people to whom they delivered the crack in their housing
project never paid for it.
   When the boys returned with little crack left and what neighbors
said was just $68, the enraged dealers held the boys hostage,
police said.
   The dealers decided to kill Anthony Williams, who was classified
as socially and emotionally disturbed, when the boy filched drugs
while in captivity, detectives said.
   Joseph said he did not know what happened to Cornell after he
escaped, according to Detective Edward Tenuto.
   Police said they were searching for the two men they believed to
be the killers and a third man they believe aided in the abduction.
Police said two of the suspects are thought to be Jamaican.
</TEXT>
