<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 0655EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-Violence     03-19 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Violence,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Policemen Killed in Shootout, Four Arrests in Transvaal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three black policemen were
killed when two men opened fire with automatic rifles on a group of
people in the yard of a township west of Pretoria, police said
today.
   The attack Friday night in Atteridgeville was so sudden none of
the police fired back at their black attackers, who fled on foot,
said Police Lt. Col. Johan Labuschagne.
   He said it had not yet been established whether the policemen
were off-duty during the attack.
   Police said in a statement that two men who wore blue overalls
killed two officers at the scene, and wounded three other people,
one of them a police officer who died later at Kalafong Hospital.
   Meanwhile, police said they had captured two alleged terrorists
and two collaborators and seized some arms in roadblocks set up
Friday in central Transvaal province in an attempt to find those
responsible for a Krugersdorp car bomb that killed three black
people and injured 20 people on Thursday.
   Police refused to give details about the roadblock arrests, but
said none of those arrested were wanted in connection with the car
bomb.
   Meanwhile, Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu issued a statement
in Cape Town condemning the car-bombing.
   He said: ``I deplore without equivocation acts such as this
week's car bombing, since all violence is evil, whether it is that
of a vicious system such as apartheid or the violence employed by
people who wish to overthrow apartheid ... I desperately hope the
day will come when the authorities realize that the only way to end
violence is to eradicate apartheid.''
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
