<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0488 03-19 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0488,0664</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran and Iraq Launch More Attacks On Each Other's Cities</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with Iran firing missile into
Baghdad and launching artillery attacks; Iraqi air raids. Pickup
5th graf pvs ``Tikrit, on...''; ADDS byline</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran fired a long-range missile into
Baghdad and said it pounded more than a dozen other Iraqi targets
with artillery after Iraq launched new air raids on cities in
western Iran.
   The attacks followed a day in which the warring countries
reported blasting each other's cities with more than 40 missiles
and attacking other targets on land and in the Persian Gulf.
   Iraq, acknowledging today's attack on Baghdad, said the missile
crashed in a ``purely residential'' neighborhood. Baghdad Radio
said several civilians were killed in the blast shortly after
midnight but gave no casualty figures.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency said the missile
was fired at the Iraqi Army's ``command headquarters in response to
their mischiefs.''
   IRNA reported 12 missiles fired into the southeastern Iraqi Umm
Qasr port, and one into Al-Amarah, a city 200 miles southeast of
Baghdad.
   It said Revolutionary Guards artillery units hammered a string
of cities and towns along the 730-mile war front, including Basra,
Iraq's already devastated southern port city.
   The attacks came after renewed Iraqi air raids today on the
western cities of Bakhtaran and Hamadan, as well as southwestern
Dezful, IRNA said. It gave no exact casualty count, but said ``many
civilians were martyred.''
   Bakhtaran also was hit at 11:30 p.m. Friday, IRNA said.
   Iran claimed its gunners fired a long-range missile into Tikrit
on Friday in the first attack on Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's
hometown since the resurgence of the war of the cities Feb. 29.
Iraq did not report any attack on Tikrit.
   Reports from both sides were monitored in Nicosia.
   Tikrit, on the Tigris river about 100 miles north of Baghdad, is
home to ``most members of the ruling clique in Baghdad,'' an IRNA
dispatch said.
   Other missiles on Friday hit the northern Iraqi cities of Mosul
and Kirkuk, the latter an important oil center.
   Six missiles pounded Basra, Iraq's second largest city, while 24
other projectiles were lobbed into the southern towns of Haretha,
Shubair, an industrial center just south of Basra.
   The official Iraqi News Agency reported seven missiles fired
into Tehran Friday, raising to 30 the number of such attacks on the
Iranian capital since Sunday. In all, Baghdad says it has fired 101
missiles into Tehran since the intercity dueling began Feb. 29.
   The Iranians also claimed they captured two towns Friday in a
five-day-old land offensive into northeast Iraq in which they said
9,200 Iraqis have been killed or wounded and 4,000 captured.
   They also said they recaptured the Iranian border town of
Nowsud, held by the Iraqis since the early days of the 7{-year-old
war.
   The Iraqi news agency, also monitored in Nicosia, has denied
there was combat in that region, where most of Iraq's 3.5 million
Kurds live.
   IRNA reported five Iraqi warplanes were shot down Thursday and
Friday, but Iraq confirmed only one jet downed.
   Iraq claimed two Iranian jets were shot down. IRNA denied the
report.
   The Iraqi agency said Iraqi warplanes hit two ``large maritime
targets,'' which usually means tankers, off Iran's coast on
Thursday and Friday.
   London-based Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit confirmed only
one _ on the 80,137-ton Cypriot tanker Kyrenicos.
   Iranian gunboats attacked three neutral ships in the southern
gulf Friday.
   In one attack, a Japanese seaman was killed aboard the
Panamanian liquified gas carrier Maria II in the first raid around
midnight Thursday, shipping officials said on condition of
anonymity.
   Gunboats later attacked the 284,494-ton Norwegian tanker Berge
Lord, starting a small fire, and the 87,768-ton Singapore-flag
tanker Neptune Saburu. No casualties were reported in either attack.
</TEXT>
