<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines     03-19 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldiers Kill Suspected Communist Hit Man; Ambushes Kill Four
Officers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers gunned down a suspected
communist assassin during a shootout in the capital today, military
authorities said.
   The incident came a day after gunmen wounded a national police
major and three troopers in two attacks and a rebel chief
proclaimed an autonomous Moslem region in the southern Philippines.
   Lt. Pedro Vergara, investigation chief of the Philippine
Constabulary capital command, said the shootout occurred in
Manila's residential district of Santa Mesa.
   He said soldiers arrested the suspect, Miguel Jardin, 26, in the
nearby suburb of San Juan and confiscated a .45-caliber pistol from
him.
   Vergara said that while being transported to a military camp,
Jardin jumped out of the military jeep and drew another gun
concealed on his back, prompting the officers to shoot him.
   Vergara said Jardin is a suspected member of an urban-based
communist hit squad and has been under close watch by the military.
   On Friday, police said gunmen in a car fired on a vehicle
carrying Maj. Pepito Campos and his driver in suburban Quezon City.
Both were wounded but doctors said they were recovering.
   A captain of the paramilitary national police, the Philippine
Constabulary, was arrested for questioning, according to the
police. Campos is chief of the Special Investigations Division of
Manila's northern police district.
   In the other attack Friday, gunmen believed to be communist
rebels fired on a military car in suburban Taguig, wounding two
Constabulary troopers.
   Thousands of Moslems in the southern Philippines held marches
and rallies Friday celebrating the 20th anniversary of the Moro
National Liberation Front, largest of three rebel groups seeking an
independent Islamic state in the region.
   At a rally of about 100 Moslems in Taguig organizers broadcast a
taped statement by the Front's leader, Nur Misuari, who lives in
Saudi Arabia.
   He accused President Corazon Aquino of reneging on self-rule for
the 5 million Moslems and said the archipelago's central and
southern regions were under the ``unlawful and immoral hegemony''
of Luzon, the main Philippine island.
   Misuari declared the establishment of 20 federated states in
Mindanao and other southern islands as the homeland of the Moslem
minority.
   He claimed the foreign ministers of the 46-member Organization
of Islamic Conference, a worldwide Moslem federation, were
preparing to recommend full membership for the front at a meeting
next week in Amman, Jordan. It now has observer status.
   Phillipine officials have called full membership tantamount to
secession and said it could start a new war in the south.
</TEXT>
