<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mecham     03-19 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governor Backtracks On Stealing Allegation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Evan Mecham has recanted an
accusation, made under oath while he testified at his impeachment
trial, that his former chief bodyguard stole a report from his
office.
   Moments after the Republican governor admitted Friday that he
lacked the proof he earlier claimed he had, a state official
testified the report had in fact been taken by one of Mecham's own
men, former state official Lee Watkins.
   ``I did not have the proof then and I do not have the proof
now'' that the missing report was taken by Department of Public
Safety Lt. Beau Johnson, the former head of the governor's security
detail, Mecham acknowledged in his third day of testimony before
the Senate.
   The governor did not apologize, but said he did not want to
leave senators with the wrong impression.
   In sworn testimony Thursday, the governor said he had ``had
complete confirmation that he (Johnson) was the one'' who took a
report on the DPS from then-chief of staff Jim Colter's desk and
turned it over to the DPS. Mecham testified that he had an
``informer'' within DPS.
   Johnson denied taking the report, and the DPS deputy director,
Lt. Col. Gary Phelps, told senators Friday it actually was taken by
Watkins, the former state prison construction chief.
   Watkins is accused of making a death threat against a former top
Mecham aide. One of the three impeachment articles against Mecham
charges the governor with trying to obstruct an investigation of
the alleged threat.
   Watkins, reached by telephone, denied that he took the report.
   Mecham fired Johnson from his security detail after the police
officer reported the alleged threat to his superiors.
   Republican Sen. Tony West, who had demanded that Mecham reveal
who accused Johnson of taking the report, admonished the governor.
``When you have careers, reputations at stake ... we have an
obligation to protect each and every ... reputation and career.''
   Mecham again insisted Friday that he did not know the alleged
death threat against former top aide Donna Carlson was a serious
matter. At the time, Ms. Carlson was about to testify before the
state grand jury about Mecham's failure to report a $350,000
campaign loan.
   The governor is accused of ordering DPS Director Ralph Milstead
not to cooperate with the attorney general's investigation of the
alleged threat.
   Testimony is expected to begin next week on the second
allegation against Mecham: that he misused $80,000 from the
governor's protocol fund by loaning it to his auto dealership. The
third impeachment article accuses him of concealing the $350,000
campaign loan.
   The governor also faces an April 21 criminal trial on charges of
hiding the campaign loan, and a May 17 recall election.
   A two-thirds vote of the 30-member Senate is required to convict
Mecham, and lawmakers also could decide to bar him from holding any
future office. Mecham is the first U.S. governor to be impeached in
six decades and the first ever in Arizona.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
