<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Angola-US     03-19 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Angola-US,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Negotiators Wrap Up Southern African Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK REYNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUANDA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuba has presented the United States with
a proposed timetable for the withdrawal of its 40,000 troops
stationed in Angola, Angola said.
   U.S. negotiators left the Angolan capital Friday after 10 days
of talks with government authorities on efforts to secure peace in
southern Africa. American officials refused to comment on the
progress of the negotiations or on the timetable.
   In Lisbon, Portugal, a statement Friday by Cuba's Armed Forces
Ministry said 39 Cuban soldiers have been killed or wounded over
the past two months defending a key southern Angola town.
Anti-Marxist Angolan rebels also announced they had shot down a
Soviet-built Mi-17 helicopter in the region.
   The Foreign Ministry said Angola and a Cuban delegation
presented the United States with a proposed timetable for the
withdrawal of the 40,000 Cuban troops stationed in Angola.
   Officials in Luanda, speaking on condition of anonymity, said a
U.S. assistant secretary of state, Chester Crocker, was expected to
pursue negotiations in Angola next week.
   The United States, which has been negotiating since 1981 for a
peace accord in the region, wants Cuba to pull out of Angola in
return for a South African withdrawal from neighboring South-West
Africa, also known as Namibia.
   Angola says it will not send the Cubans home until South African
troops withdraw from Angolan territory and cease all military
incursions. In addition, Angola wants an end to U.S. and South
African aid to Angolan rebels and the implementation of a U.N. plan
for Namibian independence.
   South Africa says the Cubans must leave Angola first.
   The Cuban statement, distributed to reporters in Lisbon, said
Cuba had sent infantry units, tanks and artillery to help defend
the garrison town of Cuito Cuanavale from South African attack.
   The town is a staging post for Angolan government offensives
against strongholds of the anti-Marxist National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola, or UNITA.
   Hundreds of Angolan troops were killed or wounded, the statement
said. Enemy forces also suffered heavy casualties, including
hundreds of South African and South-West African soldiers, it added.
   Angola estimates 9,000 South African troops are fighting in
Angola. UNITA, which also receives U.S. support, has been fighting
to share power in Angola's government since 1975, when it gained
independence from Portugal.
   UNITA claimed Friday that its guerrillas shot down a government
helicopter ferrying wounded Angolan army officers from Cuito
Cuanavale.
   The rebel statement said the helicopter crashed and killed all
aboard when it was hit by anti-aircraft fire Wednesday between
Cuito Cuanavale and Menongue, 100 miles to the west.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
