<HEAD>Former President's Brother, Accused in Scandals, Leaves Country</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with government considering
summoning brother, probing allegations after request by Chun.
Pickup 7th graf, ``We strongly...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A younger brother of former President
Chun Doo-hwan flew to Japan, airport officials said today, as
controversy raged about his alleged involvement in financial and
political scandals.
   Opposition leaders charged the government allowed Chun
Kyung-hwan to leave South Korea. A presidential official announced
that the government was considering summoning Chun back and
investigating the allegations.
   That announcement followed a request by the ex-president today
for a formal investigation into the scandals involving his younger
brother, said officials who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Chun, 46, left for Osaka Friday afternoon after booking a seat
under a false name, airport officials said.
   Under the former president, the younger Chun headed the New
Community Movement, a non-political campaign started in the 1970's
to modernize rural and urban areas.
   The younger Chun was allegedly involved in large-scale land
speculation and the abuse of power to exact money from businessmen
and force government agencies to divert funds to help his
organization.
   One report estimated the total amount of money involved at
between $60 million and $100 million.
   In an apparent move to defuse the controversy before next
month's legislative elections, government officials said they would
consider summoning Chun from abroad.
   ``The government may start a full-scale investigation into the
scandals, along with summoning Mr. Chun Kyung-hwan,'' a
high-ranking official at President Roh Tae-woo's presidential
office said.
   The younger Chun's sudden departure quickly became a political
issue as opposition parties charged that the Roh government helped
him out of the country to escape possible criminal prosecution.
   ``We strongly demand that the government immediately arrest the
criminal, put him to trial and get him due punishment,'' the major
opposition Reunfication Democratic Party said in a statement.
   The other major opposition Party for Peace and Democracy said
the case would test the morality of the newly inaugurated Roh
government.
   The younger Chun has never held a political office, but was
considered one of the most powerful figures in South Korean
politics.
   The scandals were not reported under the old government, which
put a tight lid on the news media. Local newspapers, which enjoy
more freedom with Roh's inauguration last month, began to report
details of the scandals.
   Roh, Chun Doo-hwan's chosen successor, defeated rival opposition
candidates Kim Young-sam and Kim Dae-jung in December's
presidential election. Roh did not win a majority of the vote,
winning because the opposition vote was split.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
