<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     03-19 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talk about room service.
   When George M. Harris Jr. made his first visit to the Hotel
Pennsylvania in New York in March 1933, he was an unexpected but
welcome guest, coming into the world in Room 1032 with the
assistance of a hotel doctor.
   On Friday, it was Harris' turn to be surprised.
   The staff of the hotel, now the New York Penta across from Penn
Station, marked his 55th birthday by giving Harris and his family a
party, complete with cake and champagne, and by putting them up in
the hotel's Presidential Suite for the weekend.
   ``I was born in this hotel and after this weekend I may die in
this hotel,'' Harris joked during the festivities.
   Edward W. Moles, the hotel's director of advertising and public
relations, said the hotel had hosted presidents, band leader Glenn
Miller and other notables, but Harris was the only guest born
there. He said employees had decided to go all out with a
celebration when they learned that Harris and his wife were coming
to the Big Apple for a visit.
   Harris and his wife, Shirley, were scheduled to go to New York
next week with a band from a Rocky Mount High School. Mrs. Harris
called for reservations and thought the story of her husband's
birth might get them a discount.
   Harris became a New Yorker when his mother, Winifred, gave birth
earlier than expected while traveling to Rocky Mount, 53 miles
northeast of Raleigh, with his father. Harris said his father, a
tobacco buyer, worked in Turkey most of the time but was returning
to Rocky Mount.
   ``It was a surprise to her,'' he said. ``They thought sure they
had plenty of time to get to Rocky Mount.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was only appropriate that Kelly give
birth on St. Patrick's Day, but it still came as a surprise to
officials of the Oklahoma City zoo. They had no idea that the
16-year-old dolphin was pregnant.
   Kelly's been a real trouper with the Aquaticus performing
Atlantic Bottlenose Dolphin troupe since she came to the zoo in
October, and no one knew she was well along into her year-long
pregnancy, said zoo spokeswoman Emily Hopkins.
   But on Thursday, Kelly went into labor and her 3-foot-long,
45-pound daughter was born 45 minutes later at 4:20 p.m. Zoo
officials and trainers said the calf, as yet unnamed, appeared
healthy and normal.
   She swam immediately to the surface of the water to breathe and
then began swimming near her mother. The calf, which will nurse for
about 3 to 5 months, will grow to an adult size of about 350
pounds, Ms. Hopkins said.
   The dolphin birth was the first for landlocked Oklahoma, Ms.
Hopkins added.
</TEXT>
