<HEAD>Released Dutch Ship Had No Treasure Hunters, Official Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Dutch embassy official has denied
reports that a ship released Friday by Venezuela carried a team
looking for sunken Nazi treasure.
   The vessel ``is simply a cruise ship and has nothing to do with
any treasure-hunting whatsoever,'' embassy spokesman Harry
Trouerbach said in a telephone interview.
   Earlier reports in Europe said the ship was carrying treasure
hunters in search of a World War II wreck.
   ``That is a fantastic story. It surely comes from a very
imaginative mind,'' Trouerbach said.
   The Plancius was released Friday afternoon and was bound for the
neighboring Netherlands Antilles island of Curacao, Trouerbach said
late Friday.
   The Venezuelan coast guard detained the ship a week agp off La
Blanquilla island, 170 miles northeast of Caracas. Venezuela
claimed it had illegaly entered its territorial waters.
   Trouerbach said it was allowed to leave La Guaira port at
Caracas once authorities determined it never actually entered
Venezuelan waters.
   The Plancius was taking its 40 passengers to Willemstad,
Curacao's main city, where they were scheduled to board a KLM plane
for the Netherlands, Trouerbach said.
   ``Most of the passengers are biologists, not treasure-hunters,''
he said.
</TEXT>
