<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country singer Tammy Wynette will
perform and be master of ceremonies for a talent show Monday to
benefit the troubled Nashville Symphony, promoters say.
   Sixty singers are to perform in the first round Sunday in the
``Mr. and Ms. Country Music America'' talent contest, sponsored by
Music City News, a monthly country music publication, and Memphis,
Tenn.-based Holiday Inc.
   Ms. Wynette will preside over the finals and perform Monday
night at the Grand Ole Opry, officials said Thursday. The winners
of the best male and female vocalist categories win $10,000 and a
recording contract.
   During Monday night's show, organizers plan to pass the hat for
the symphony, which folded in mid-season this year because of
financial difficulties, said Music City News General Manager John
Sturdivant.
   ``If people have a good time, we don't think they'd mind
dropping some money into a goldfish bowl,'' Sturdivant said. ``We
might raise a couple of thousand dollars that way.''
