<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfRdp.2ndLd-Writethru a0494   03-19 0725</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp. 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0494,0744</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran and Iraq Launch More Attacks On Each Other's Cities</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with oil terminal attack; picks
up 9th graf, `Iran claimed ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said its warplanes blasted Iran's
vital oil center at Kharg island today, setting oil installations
and tankers ablaze. Iran fired long-range missiles into Baghdad and
other Iraqi cities.
   Iraq, acknowledging the attack on Baghdad, said the missile
crashed in a ``purely residential'' neighborhood of the capital.
Baghdad Radio said several civilians were killed in the missile
blast, but gave no figures.
   Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency said the missile was fired
at the Iraqi Army's ``command headquarters in response to their
mischief.''
   The Iranian news agency, monitored in Nicosia, also reported 12
missiles fired into the southeastern Iraqi Umm Qasr port, and one
into Al-Amarah, a city 200 miles southeast of Baghdad.
   An urgent dispatch, carried by the Iraqi News Agency, said large
formations of fighter-bombers attacked Kharg Island, on the
northern edge of the Persian Gulf, and a tanker holding area east
of the facility, in a ``daring'' raid.
   The agency, monitored in Nicosia, quoted a mlitary spokesman as
saying: ``Our pilots ... devastated their targets, setting
facilities on the island and several tankers nearby on fire.''
   The unnamed spokesman did not say whether all attacking planes
returned safely from the raid, and IRNA reported that Iranian jets
shot down an Iraqi aircraft in a dogfight over the Persian Gulf.
   Iran did not confirm the attack on Kharg.
   Kharg accounts for about 90 percent of Iran's oil exports. It
has been hit frequently in Iraqi air raids.
   The Iranian news agency said Revolutionary Guards artillery
units hammered a string of cities and towns along the 730-mile war
front, including Basra, Iraq's already devastated southern port
city.
   The attacks came after renewed Iraqi air raids today on the
western cities of Bakhtaran and Hamadan, as well as southwestern
Dezful, the Iranian news agency said. It gave no exact casualty
count, but said ``many civilians were martyred.''
   Iran claimed its gunners fired a long-range missile into Tikrit
on Friday in the first attack on Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's
hometown since the resurgence of the war of the cities Feb. 29.
Iraq did not report any attack on Tikrit.
   Tikrit, on the Tigris river about 100 miles north of Baghdad, is
home to ``most members of the ruling clique in Baghdad,'' an
Islamic Republic News Agency dispatch said.
   Other missiles on Friday hit the northern Iraqi cities of Mosul
and Kirkuk, the latter an important oil center.
   Six missiles pounded Basra, Iraq's second-largest city, while 24
other projectiles were lobbed into the southern towns of Haretha,
Shubair, an industrial center just south of Basra.
   The Iraqi News Agency reported seven missiles fired into Tehran
Friday, raising to 30 the number of such attacks on the Iranian
capital since Sunday. In all, Baghdad says it has fired 101
missiles into Tehran since the intercity dueling began Feb. 29.
   The Iranians also claimed they captured two towns Friday in a
five-day-old land offensive into northeast Iraq in which they said
9,200 Iraqis have been killed or wounded and 4,000 captured.
   They also said they recaptured the Iranian border town of
Nowsud, held by the Iraqis since the early days of the 7{-year-old
war.
   The Iraqi news agency has denied there was combat in that
region, where most of Iraq's 3.5 million Kurds live.
   The Iranian news agency reported five Iraqi warplanes were shot
down Thursday and Friday, but Iraq confirmed only one jet downed.
   Iraq claimed two Iranian jets were shot down. Iran denied the
report.
   The Iraqi agency said Iraqi warplanes hit two ``large maritime
targets,'' which usually means tankers, off Iran's coast on
Thursday and Friday.
   London-based Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit confirmed only
one _ on the 80,137-ton Cypriot tanker Kyrenicos.
   Iranian gunboats attacked three neutral ships in the southern
gulf Friday.
   In one attack, a Japanese seaman was killed aboard the
Panamanian liquified gas carrier Maria II in the first raid around
midnight Thursday, shipping officials said on condition of
anonymity.
   Gunboats later attacked the 284,494-ton Norwegian tanker Berge
Lord, starting a small fire, and the 87,768-ton Singapore-flag
tanker Neptune Saburu. No casualties were reported in either attack.
</TEXT>
