<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Shamir     03-19 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shamir,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Leader Says Peace Should Follow Approach of Camp David
Accords</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir,
winding up his six-day U.S. visit, said the best course for
bringing peace to the Middle East was charted in the 1978 Camp
David accords.
   In a speech Friday to the Los Angeles World Affairs Council,
Shamir praised the accords signed by Israel and Egypt under U.S.
auspices, although he opposed them 10 years ago as a member of
Israel's Parliament, the Knesset.
   As at Camp David, Shamir said, peace talks between Israel and
her Arab neighbors must be conducted directly and on an equal
footing.
   ``This approach is enshrined in the Camp David accords, to which
we remain committed,'' he said. ``They still provide a workable
blueprint for resolving issues between us and our Arab neighbors,
including the Palestinian Arabs.''
   During his visit, prime minister rebuffed a U.S. proposal for
peace negotiations in the region, saying the proposal for an
international conference would allow the Soviet Union ``to push a
settlement favorable to themselves and their Syrian clients.''
   The U.S. proposal was an attempt to accommodate Jordan's King
Hussein, who has refused to enter peace taks with Israel except at
an international conference.
   Shamir, whose Likud Bloc is opposed to the notion of trading
territory for peace because it feels this would leave the Jewish
state vulnerable to the Arab goal of destroying the Jewish state
altogether, also dismissed criticism about Israel's crackdown on
Palestinian rioting in the West Bank and Gaza. The violence in the
territories captured by Israel in the 1967 Six-Day War has left 101
people dead.
   Despite the recent differences of opinion, Shamir said, ``the
basic relationship between Israel and the United States is as close
as ever, as strong as ever and as good as ever.''
   During Shamir's speech, about 250 Arab-Americans and their
supporters waved Palestinian flags and chanted slogans as they
demonstrated outside the Century Plaza Hotel. About 20 members of
the militant Jewish Defense League staged a counter-demonstration
outside the posh hotel, but there were no confrontations, violence
or arrests, said police Sgt. Larry McKinley.
   Shamir has sought to blunt criticism of his country's action in
the territories by some American Jews.
   He reiterated his view that the picture presented of the
Palestinian riots in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip has been
distorted by the media, and said Americans shouldn't confuse the
violence with U.S.-style civil rights activism.
   ``It is war. It is an extension of urban terrorism,'' he said,
defending his troops' use of rubber bullets, beatings and live
ammunition.
   Shamir returns to Israel tonight.
</TEXT>
