<DOCNO> AP880319-0060 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 0859EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AmishControversy     03-19 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amish Controversy,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Controversy Over Sign Color Causes Rift in Amish Community</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dispute within the Amish community over
whether their horse-drawn vehicles should carry orange safety
reflectors has divided the normally close-knit society.
   Some who object to the orange, saying displays of such bright
colors are against their religion, are only willing to use a
hand-cut black metal triangle outlined with white reflective tape
to warn drivers of other vehicles.
   The sign rift runs so deeply that the so-called ``orange-sign''
and ``black-sign'' Amish now maintain separate churches.
Orange-sign Amish also have opened their homes and farms to tour
groups; the black-sign Amish have refused.
   The rift has led two families to leave the 60-family community
in southeastern Minnesota's Fillmore County and move to Michigan.
   ``They want their freedom,'' said Jacob Hershberger, a community
elder whose daughter and son-in-law moved to Michigan. ``I feel
really bad some of our group broke away. But they were making
trouble. If they hadn't made trouble with the orange signs, there
wouldn't be this other trouble.''
   State law requires the Amish to display orange reflectors on the
backs of their horse-drawn buggies and wagons at night and in fog,
and to carry it in the vehicle at all other times.
   But Hershberger and others object to the orange on religious
grounds. Those Amish, if they use any sign at all, use the
white-bordered black triangle, a device permissible only in the
daytime, and not in fog.
   ``I look at it this way,'' said Menno Mast, 24, an Amish
furniture maker from Mabel who has orange reflectors on his
vehicles. ``If the black sign was legal, I'd be willing to use it.
But instead of making trouble with you folks, I'd rather use red
(orange).
   ``I don't feel it's hard on my religion. I look at this: We have
red barns, and red stuff in the house. I don't have much difficulty
with that.''
   A bill that would have allowed the Amish to use their black
signs at night failed to clear a legislative committee this week.
   Hershberger said he'll refuse to pay any fines for violating the
sign law, risking a jail sentence.
   One Amish man spent a day in the Fillmore County jail last fall
for not paying his $22 fine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880319-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 0904EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Egypt-US     03-19 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Egypt-US,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Envoy Seeks Backing for American Peace Plan in Egypt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Special U.S. presidential envoy Philip Habib
arrived in the Egyptian capital today to seek Arab backing for an
American plan for peace in the Middle East.
   Habib met for an hour with Foreign Minister Esmat Abdel-Meguid.
He told reporters afterward that he had briefed the Egyptian about
the status of the peace process but refused to give details.
   Abdel-Meguid said that Cairo's position ``has been to encourage
the United States to move for the peace process because we all in
this region are in need of peace.''
   An Egyptian government source, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Habib was to meet with President Hosni Mubarak on
Sunday before continuing his swing.
   Mubarak has called the American plan ``encouraging'' but
suggested, without specifics, that some of its provisions be
elaborated.
   Habib's tour will take him to Jordan, Saudi Arabia and Morocco,
according to a Washington announcement Friday by State Department
spokesman Charles Redman.
   Redman said one aim of Habib's mission was to get views of
leaders in the four countries about the peace plan presented this
month by U.S. Secretary of State George Shultz during a regional
tour. Syria and Palestinian leaders rejected the plan and Jordan
criticized it.
   Redman said Habib also will brief Arab leaders on talks this
week in Washington between administration officials and Israeli
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, who rejected key elements of the
plan.
   ``We are looking for an early response to our proposals from the
parties in the region,'' Redman said.
   The U.S. peace plan calls for a United Nations-sponsored
international conference. That meeting would give way by May 1 to
direct Arab-Israeli talks on a three-year transition period of
self-rule for 1.5 million Palestinians in the Israeli-occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Negotiations on the final status of the two territories,
occupied by the Israelis since the 1967 war, would be held in
December.
   Meanwhile, Egyptian Defense Minister Abdel-Halim Abu-Ghazala
flew to Washington today for a 10-day visit to discuss Egypt's arms
requirements under a 9-year-old aid program. U.S. military aid to
Egypt averages $1.3 billion a year in a program that began after
Egypt signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1979.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
