<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GorillaDies     03-19 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gorilla Dies,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oldest Breeding Gorilla In Captivity Dies At Chicago Zoo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BROOKFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A massive brain tumor killed a
30-year-old western lowland gorilla believed to be the oldest
breeding male gorilla in captivity, say officials at the Brookfield
Zoo.
   Samson died Thursday at the zoo in suburban Chicago and an
autopsy later revealed the presence of the brain tumor, said
Brookfield spokeswoman Linda Elbert.
   He had sired four offspring at Brookfield, including an infant
born a week ago. A fifth is expected from a recent mating, Ms.
Elbert said.
   Samson, star of Brookfield's ``Tropic World'' exhibit, had been
in failing health for some time before an apparent stroke felled
him Tuesday, said Dr. Anne Baker, curator of primates. She said the
30005-pound gorilla regained consciousness only twice before his
death.
   ``We were a bit taken aback by his apparent stroke,'' Ms. Baker
said. ``After Tuesday we knew he was in a life-threatening
situation, but we had not expected that we would lose him as soon
as we did.''
   She said Samson had suffered from rheumatoid arthritis since
1980, and had been blind for about a month before his death.
   Samson came to Brookfield in 1980 from the Buffalo Zoological
Gardens in Buffalo, N.Y. Ms. Baker said he was captured in Africa
and arrived at the Buffalo zoo in 1962.
   ``Samson has left a lot of offspring here to continue the
genetic pool of these creatures,'' Ms. Elbert said. ``He was a
really, really beautiful animal.''
   Gorillas usually live 30 years to 40 years in captivity, she
said, and the record in captivity is 53 years.
</TEXT>
