<HEAD>Freeway Gunman Sentenced To Maximum 10 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gunman whose bullet paralyzed a
marathon runner in a freeway shooting last July has been sentenced
to the maximum 10-year prison term.
   A rash of similar confrontations, including several in which
victims were killed or injured, plagued Southern California last
summer. Incidents have been reported sporadically since then.
   Albert Carroll Morgan, 33, of Huntington Beach, who apologized
for shooting Paul Gary Nussbaum, was sentenced Friday to seven
years for shooting at an occupied vehicle and an additional three
years for infliction of great bodily injury.
   Morgan also was ordered to pay a maximum $10,000 to the victim
restitution fund by Orange County Superior Court Judge Jean
Rheinheimer.
   Morgan shot Nussbaum on July 18, 1987, while Nussbaum was
driving on the southbound Costa Mesa Freeway during rush-hour
traffic.
   Nussbaum, 29, confined to a wheelchair, said he was satisfied
with Morgan's sentence.
   ``I feel that he should spend the rest of his life in prison,''
said Nussbaum. ``But the judge did what she had to do. I'm really
glad he got the maximum.''
   A jury convicted Morgan in February of the felony charges of
voluntary manslaughter, assault with a firearm and shooting at an
inhabited vehicle.
   In another case, jurors began deliberations Friday in Compton in
the case of Ronald Elam, 28, who is charged with first-degree
murder, two counts of attempted murder and two counts of assault
with a deadly weapon in connection with an Aug. 17, 1987, roadway
shooting.
