<2ND_LINE>PM-IRA Funeral, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0515,0567</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Two Dead In New Attack On IRA Funeral</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs with police confirming that the men were
British soldiers, details. PICKS up 5th graf, `Officials at ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A funeral crowd mourning the
death of an IRA guerrilla dragged two British soldiers from a car,
beat them with crowbars and stripped them naked, witnesses said.
Minutes later they were shot to death.
   Initial reports said the crowd believed the men were
plainclothes detectives who were spying on the funeral for Irish
Republican Army member Kevin Brady, who was killed earlier in the
week during another IRA funeral.
   Police later confirmed that the two men were plainclothes
British soldiers.
   Witnesses said the victims fired shots in the air in an
unsuccessful attempt to extricate themselves from the crowd, but it
overwelmed them.
   Some witnesses said the soldiers were beaten and driven away in
a taxi and their bodies, stripped naked, were found later at an
abandoned lot.
   Others said the soldiers were not driven away but stripped naked
by the crowd, bundled unconscious onto a wall surrounding a soccer
field and then dragged behind a building and shot.
   It was not clear whether the men were shot by mourners or by
other assailants.
   Officials of Sinn Fein, the legal political wing of the IRA,
said papers were found on the men identifying them as British army
personnel. They said the men were killed with their own pistols.
   There were reports that a priest was seen trying to give one of
the victims mouth-to-mouth resuscitation and being ordered away by
the gunmen who then pumped more shots into the men.
   After the men were killed, witnesses said the cortege continued
toward Milltown Cemetery with some people weeping and trembling as
they walked.
   It was the second time in three days that funerals of IRA
members have been disrupted by violence. On Thursday, a Protestant
gunman fired shots and tossed grenades into a crowd of mourners,
killing three and wounding 68.
   Brady was shot as he and other mourners chased the attacker. The
enraged crowd finally grabbed 33-year-old Michael Stone when his
gun jammed. They severely beat him before police caught up and took
him into custody.
   Stone is under armed guard in a hospital, being treated for the
injuries he received at the hands of his pursuers. Police have
arrested a second person believed linked to the shooting.
   Police said Friday that Stone will be formally charged next week
with murder in connection with the cemetery attack and other
unrelated serious crimes.
   Press Association said Stone was being questioned about 10
sectarian killings unrelated to Wednesday's attack.
   On Friday, West Belfast Catholics buried two other victims of
sectarian violence. One was 20-year-old Thomas McErlean, another of
the three people killed in Wednesday's attack at Milltown cemetery.
   The other buried Friday was Charles McGrillen, who was shot
Monday outside a Belfast supermarket. The Ulster Freedom Fighters,
an outlawed Protestant extremist group, claimed responsibility for
killing him in a statement Friday.
   The outlawed IRA is fighting to drive the British from Northern
Ireland. The mainly Catholic guerrilla group wants to unite the
predominantly Protestant province with the overwhelmingly Catholic
Irish Republic under socialist rule.
   Protestant militants reject unity with the Irish Republic.
</TEXT>
