<HEAD>Israel Detains Four TV Crews: Shamir Overhaul Government</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with U.S. TV crews detained.</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   PICKS up 5th graf, `In Cyprus ... EDITS to tighten
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JOCELYN NOVECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Israeli army detained two American
television crews for an hour today after they refused to leave the
West Bank city of Ramallah when protests broke out, a crew member
and a military spokesman said.
   Scattered protests were reported in the West Bank and Gaza Strip
but there were no reports of shootings. Hospital officials in Gaza
City said nine Palestinians were admitted with beating injuries.
   Prime Mimister Yitzhak Shamir said he may let Israel's coalition
government collapse because of the rift over how to make peace with
the Arabs. Shamir said he was thinking about calling for early
elections.
   In an unusual move, soldiers in the West Bank City of Ramallah
detained four foreign TV crews, including crews from the CBS and
CNN networks, who refused to obey orders to leave the area.
   Eli Fastman, a cameraman for the London-based Visnews, said the
four crews had entered Ramallah in violation of an army order and
had stayed there ``to challenge this crazy system of closing us out
of the territories.''
   When protests broke out in Ramallah's central square, Fastman
said, the cameramen were approached by troops and told to leave,
but they refused.
   Fastman said he and the two-man crews from CBS, CNN and the
London-based Worldwide Television News were taken to a military
police station in Ramallah where they ``discussed the situation
with army officials.'' The army filed no charges and released the
crews an hour later, he said.
   An army spokesman confirmed the detentions but could provide no
details. Local area commanders in the West Bank and Gaza Strip are
empowered to close areas under their command at will.
   Shamir, meanwhile, revealed Friday that he was considering
supporting early electons.
   ``The internal situation in the government could be the main
reason for early elections,'' Shamir told Israel Television's
Washington correspondent. ``I am thinking about it ... I do not
rule out such a thing.''
   Troops killed two Palestinians in the Israeli-occupied
territories on Friday. The shootings brought to 102 the number of
Palestinians killed by U.N. count in anti-occupation violence since
it began Dec. 8. Hospital officials said at least 25 protesters
were wounded in scattered clashes.
   In Cyprus, U.N. officials announced that more than 400
Palestinian refugees had been injured in the occupied Gaza Strip
this week, bringing the casualty toll for March to more than 900.
   Troops killed a protester at the Shati refugee camp in Gaza
during a clash with hundreds of worshipers after noon prayers at
the camp's Al-Gharbi mosque, the army said.
   Officials at Gaza City's Shifa hospital identified the victim as
24-year-old Hani Abu Hamam. Witnesses said his family smuggled the
body out of the hospital for a burial service attended by about 100
angry mourners.
   In the occupied West Bank, a soldier shot and killed a
19-year-old protester who attacked him at the Ein Beit Ilmah camp
near Nablus, the army said. A spokeswoman said the protester had
assaulted the soldier with ``a dangerous object,'' but she would
not elaborate.
   Officials at Nablus' Ittihad hospital identified the victim as
Muhamed Mahmud Suleiman Khaled. Jehad Alawni, a nurse, said Khaled
bled to death from a bullet wound in the left thigh.
   Also Friday, two Israeli civilians were detained for allegedly
stockpiling an arsenal of weapons intended for anti-Arab attacks,
police said. Investigators determined the two had acted alone and
were not part of a larger ring, the daily Haaretz said.
</TEXT>
