<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FCA 1stLd-Writethru   03-19 0648</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FCA, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0448,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Regulators Assure Depositors In Second-Largest Thrift</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 2nd graf, bgng: The Federal, to CORRECT name of S&L</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators are reassuring nervous
depositors in the California-based Financial Corp. of America that
they won't lose money in any government action against the troubled
holding company.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board said Friday it would protect
all depositors and general creditors of American Savings & Loan
Association, FCA's main subsidiary. Normally deposit accounts are
only insured up to $100,000.
   The Irvine-based FCA, with $33.7 billion in assets, is the
nation's second-largest thrift holding company and the biggest
problem for the bank board, which regulates 3,150 savings
institutions.
   The pledge of support came after the company, in a report filed
with the Securities and Exchange Commission, said for the first
time that American, based in Stockton, was insolvent under
generally accepted accounting principles.
   Karl Hoyle, a bank board spokesman, said the statement was made
in part to stem the drain of deposits at American. The bank board
also reaffirmed its support for the management of both the S&L and
its parent.
   FCA said American's net worth _ the difference between assets
and liabilities _ had fallen to negative $106 million at the end of
the year, compared with positive $244.4 million on Sept. 30.
   Under less stringent regulatory accounting guidelines,
American's net worth was plus $69 million at the end of 1987,
compared with $357.8 million at the end of the third quarter.
   FCA had previously revealed that its net worth had fallen into
the red, but this is the first disclosure that net worth at
American has fallen below the zero mark. That happened when
American concluded that repayment of debts due from its parent
company were not assured.
   FCA's annual report, filed with the SEC, also revealed that
depositors withdrew $493 million during the first two months of
this year. Deposits had totaled $17.1 billion at the end of 1987.
   The company attributed the drain to publicity about the bank's
problems and said it eased during the first 10 days of March.
   The drain was milder than the severe run at American in August
and September of 1984, when the bank lost about $6.8 billion of its
$25 billion in deposits.
   The bank board's sister agency for commercial banks, the Federal
Deposit Insurance Corp., issued a similar promise on Thursday
protecting all depositors and general creditors of First
RepublicBank Corp. of Dallas, a bank holding company of about the
same size as FCA.
   However, the FDIC went a step further than the bank board by
pumping $1 billion into First RepublicBank.
   FCA on Feb. 23 asked for $1.5 billion in assistance as soon as
possible from the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., the bank board
unit that guarantees deposits. Hoyle said the request is under
review.
   The largest-ever government bailout of a banking company was the
$4.5 billion rescue in 1984 of Continental Illinois Corp.
   The bank board has tried unsuccessfully for nearly a year to
find another institution willing to take over all or part of FCA on
terms that wouldn't be too costly. On-again, off-again talks with
the thrift unit of Ford Motor Co. broke down early in January.
   On Jan. 27, FCA reported a loss of $224.6 million in the last
three months of last year, bringing its 1987 loss to $468 million.
   Two weeks later, the bank board ordered it to sell $2.5 billion
in mortgage-backed securities to reduce its vulnerability to
interest rate fluctuations.
   On March 9, the bank board passed a resolution reassuring
nervous Wall Street firms, which had lent more than $12 billion to
American in the form of reverse repurchase agreements.
   Ranked by assets, FCA is second among thrift holding companies
to H.F. Ahmanson & Co., the Los Angeles-based parent of Home
Savings of America.
</TEXT>
