<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SchoolRumble     03-19 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School Rumble,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High School Calm After 2 Days of Fights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLYMOUTH, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Calm has settled over Plymouth-Canton
High School following two days of fights between ``jocks'' and
``burnouts'' in a turf battle that some students say has overtones
of discrimination.
   Louise Gates, a spokeswoman at the suburban Detroit school, said
there was one minor scuffle Friday lasting about 10 minutes, but
order was restored quickly. Large-scale fist fights rocked the
school Wednesday and Thursday.
   ``Everything was pretty calm, maybe we've seen the end of the
disturbances,'' said a public safety officer, who declined to give
her name.
   Fights between the student-athletes and the so-called burnouts,
who students say are distinguished by their leather jackets and
concert T-shirts, erupted around noon Wednesday.
   Administrators said the fighting began over the use of a popular
hallway gathering place known as ``the Pit.''
   There were no injuries, but at least 12 students were suspended
and school officials sealed off the hallway, officials said.
   About 20 police officers were called to restore order Thursday.
Police declined to say how many officers were at the school Friday.
   Some students said administrators over-reacted to the fights.
   ``The amount of police that they brought in was outrageous. It
gave the kids a reason to keep going,'' said student Reeder Singler.
   ``The fighting is not really over turf, ... it's over
discrimination of one group over another,'' Singler said. The
burnouts feel the jocks receive preferential treatment by some
administrators and faculty, he said.
   On Thursday, the burnouts sent school Principal Thomas Tattan a
note that said: ``We feel we should be treated with the same
courtesy as other peer and social groups. We believe you're taking
the jocks' side over the Pit issue.''
   The burnouts and the jocks met Friday among themselves but the
meeting broke up when administrators tried to join in the
discussions, Singler said.
   Gates said administrators talked to both sides, but declined to
reveal what was discussed.
</TEXT>
