<DOCNO> AP880319-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 1039EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-FerryStrike     03-19 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ferry Strike,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike By Ferry Workers Halts Channel Crossings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOVER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strikes by ferry workers crippled weekend
travel between Britain and France on Saturday, jamming ports on
both sides of the English Channel with long lines of cars, buses
and trucks.
   The Dover Port Authority said separate strikes had reduced
sailings to the European continent by 75 percent. It advised casual
travelers to stay away.
   Ferries staffed by Belgian crews and traveling from Dover to
Belgium were departing normally, but only one passenger ferry still
was sailing to France, the port authority said.
   Early Saturday, there were about 250 cars and 100 buses waiting
inside the docks at Dover, but the pressure was relieved when some
of the cars were ferried to nearby Folkestone to cross the English
Channel to Boulogne, France.
   About 400 freight trucks also were jammed inside the Dover dock,
and 240 others lined up along a cordoned section of the expressway
leading into the port city.
   ``It's a pretty desperate situation,'' said a port official,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The Dover Harbor Board said travelers to the continent might
have to wait up 36 hours to make the crossing.
   About 2,200 employees of P and O European Ferries went on strike
six weeks ago to protest the company's plan to cut 400 jobs and
change work conditions.
   On Thursday, French crews of the British-French consortium
Sealink-SNCF walked off the job on both sides of the channel in a
separate protest over work practices.
   French workers are striking against a reduction in wages and an
increase in working hours.
   Port officials in France, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said some truck drivers who had been waiting for more than 72 hours
to cross temporarily abandoned their vehicles at Calais.
   Crews of three French ferries were on strike in Calais. The only
ferry making the crossing to Dover, England, was the Saint Anselm,
run by British Sealink.
   Departures continued from Cherbourg to Poole, England and from
Ouistreham.
   In Dieppe, the car-ferry Le Chartre had blocked the vehicle
access ramp to all ferries since Thursday, according to port
authorities. Ferry captain Gerard Delaunay has refused to allow
another ferry, the Versailles, to take on cars for the crossing to
Newhaven, England.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
