<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 1057EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Candidates-Panama     03-19 0764</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Candidates-Panama,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Presidential Candidates Support Pushing Noriega Out Of Power</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush says it is too
early to discuss dropping the drug indictments against Panamanian
strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega. Jesse Jackson says he favors
a guarantee of no extradition if that will speed up his departure.
   Other presidential candidates, in reponse to a survey by The
Associated Press, voiced support for U.S. efforts to force Noriega
to step down and end the crisis in Panama.
   Several Democrats faulted the Reagan administration for not
acting sooner.
   Pat Robertson, a Republican hopeful and former television
evangelist, said, ``Under no circumstances should a deal be made
whereby drug charges are dropped.''
   The AP asked the candidates last Tuesday if the United States
should impose a trade embargo on Panama to force Noriega out, if it
should drop drug charges against Noriega if that would hurry his
departure, and if there were conditions under which they would
annul the treaty giving Panama eventual control of the canal.
   All the candidates except Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., responded by
Friday.
   Only Robertson suggested the crisis was grounds for changing the
treaty.
   ``In light of the uncertainties and volatility of the situation
in Panama, I believe the U.S. should reconsider transferring
control of the canal,'' Robertson said.
   However, Bush said: ``we signed the treaty in good faith. The
canal is operating smoothly and we expect it to continue to operate
smoothly. We fully expect Panama to live up to its treaty
commitments.''
   Bush called the U.S. drug charges against Noriega ``a matter for
the judiciary and it is premature to discuss dropping indictments.''
   On a trade embargo, the vice president said: ``Noriega should go
and will go and the United States government is listening to the
Panamanian people and the legitimate government of Panama. We hope
this internal problem will soon be resolved.''
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis said he supports sanctions,
``but I don't believe that a trade embargo is necessary or
appropriate at this time.''
   ``Before we consider any action that would affect the criminal
proceedings against Noriega, it is essential that the American
people be given a full accounting of the past relationship between
Gen. Noriega and agencies and officials of the U.S. government,''
Dukakis said.
   Jackson said, ``Drugs are our No. 1 national security issue.
Apparently, Gen. Noriega is deeply involved in the international
drug trade. Therefore it is justified to use diplomatic and
economic pressure to push him out.''
   But Jackson added the United States should be acting in concert
``with our friends in the region'' and the Organization of American
States. ``When we act unilaterally, we fan the flame of nationalism
and undermine our effectiveness,'' he said.
   ``The administration's recent moves are to be supported, but we
lack moral authority, which undermines our diplomatic and economic
actions, because the administration failed to respond quickly and
forcefully when it first learned of Noriega's involvement in drug
traffic,'' Jackson said. ``Our weak policy has put the U.S. in
another crisis in Central America.''
   ``It is in our interest and that of the Panamanians to settle
the crisis with Noriega as quickly as possible. If that means
granting Noriega a guarantee of no-extradition, then it should be
granted,'' Jackson said.
   Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., said, ``I support the economic steps
taken last week against Noriega. The pressure must be kept on
Noriega so that he quickly steps aside and allows President
Delvalle to take over. If that happens, the U.S.-Panama
relationship will greatly improve, barring other revelations about
Panamanian drug dealings.''
   Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., said, ``Supporting dictators does
not serve our interests. The lesson of the Shah and Somoza, and
before them Batista, and Diem, is that by sticking with dictators,
the United States sets the stage for the outcome we fear the most.''
   ``The days of the United States deciding who governs Panama are
over. We are not going back to the days before the Panama Canal
Treaty,'' Gephardt said. ``The days of military dictatorship in
Panama are also over. Gen. Noriega does not understand that history
has passed him by.''
   Gephardt ruled out dropping the drug indictments, saying, ``The
United States is a nation of laws. The rule of law cannot be
subordinated to political expediency.''
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr., D-Tenn., said through spokesman Arlie
Schardt that he supports a trade embargo and the possibility of
dropping the drug charges if that would speed up Noriega's
departure.
   Gore's spokesman added that it was hard to envision
circumstances that would justify annuling the treaty.
</TEXT>
