<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-NicaraguaVisit     03-19 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Nicaragua Visit,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Observer Mission Heading To Nicaragua</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of U.N. observers will visit
Nicaragua as soon as possible to investigate the tense border
situation with Honduras, a U.N. spokesman said Saturday.
   Mahbub Ahmad said Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
decided to send the team at Nicaragua's request. He said it would
include one poliitical officer from U.N. headquarters and a
still-undecided number of military observers.
   Diplomatic sources said the team was likely to inclkude two
military observers and probably would leave Tuesday. The observers
have not been named.
   The announcement followed a Security Council meeting Friday
night during which Nicaragua, Honduras and the United States traded
allegations over whether Sandinista troops are in Honduran
territory and who is responsible for the current conflict.
   Several Latin American speakers endorsed Nicaragua's call for a
neutral U.N. observer mission to visit the site of the border
clashes.
   Ahmad said there are no immediate plans to visit the Honduran
side of the border. Sources said no request had come from Honduras.
   Nicaragua has requested a joint mission by the U.N. and the
Organization of American States to investigate the border situation
and make recommendasntions on preventing further conflict.
   Honduras and the United States contend that Nicarguan troops
have attacked Contra bases in Honduras. Nicaragua has denied the
claim.
   Honduras has responded by attacking Nicaraguan forces around the
border area.
</TEXT>
