<1ST_LINE>u a PM-ChemicalFire 1stLd-Writethru a0481 03-19 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chemical Fire, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0481,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Evacuate 2,000 In Area Around Chemical Plant Explosion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf, ```It's just ...,'' with
situation unchanged this morning.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY HEIGHTS, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities evacuated 2,000 people
after firefighters were unable to extinguish a burning gas
container that threatened surrounding cylinders in a plant rocked
by a fatal blast the day before.
   The cylinder was found earlier Friday amid the ruins of the
Gollob Analytical Services chemical plant, where the explosion and
fire Thursday killed three men.
   ``It's just a waiting game right now,'' James Staples, a
spokesman for the state Department of Environmental Protection,
said Friday night. ``The slightest vibration could cause that
cylinder to turn into a fireball.''
   The cylinder was still a threat this morning, he said, and
people remained away from their homes.
   Authorities ordered the evacuation in a half-mile area
surrounding the plant out of concern that the flames would ignite
surrounding cylinders containing unknown gases.
   Nursing home patients were evacuated from the nearby Berkeley
Heights Convalescence Center on stretchers at about 8 p.m. and
residents from some 400 nearby homes also were ordered to leave as
a precaution, said Deputy Mayor Albert Boyance.
   Officials said some of the residents were staying with relatives
while others went to a nearby high school.
   The New Jersey Transit Authority discontinued passenger rail
service near the plant until at least Sunday. Passengers were to be
shuttled by bus.
   Staples said the flaming cylinder contained phosphine and
hydrogen. Authorities were planning to wait until all the gas
burned before attempting to move the cylinder.
   Investigators said the plant burst into flames Thursday after
another cylinder exploded outside the plant and became a
projectile, shooting into the building. Authorities were
investigating whether mislabeling or a contaminated gas may have
been the cause.
   A delivery man who was severely injured remained hospitalized in
fair condition Friday. He had a leg amputated and suffered shrapnel
wounds in the blast, said Doris Ortiz, a spokeswoman for University
Hospital in Newark.
   The evacuation followed a smaller evacuation earlier Friday of
an industrial area around the plant, said police Capt. Michael
Borsos.
   State environmental officials said authorities cleared the area
at lunchtime as a precaution since workers were preparing to remove
gas cylinders from the building and were not sure what they
contained.
</TEXT>
