<1ST_LINE>u w PM-TaintedBlood 2ndLd-Writethru a0461 03-19 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tainted Blood, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0461,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Red Cross Says No Danger in Blood Screening Slip Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: NEW throughout with Red Cross denial of danger, additional
detail.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Red Cross said today that blood that
slipped through procedures against AIDS contamination was not
actually contaminated with the virus or posed no known health
hazard.
   Twenty-four questionable units of blood were erroneously shipped
last month from Red Cross centers in Washington and Nashville,
Tenn., to hospitals for use but were never given to any patients,
according to the Food and Drug Administration.
   ``While it should not have been shipped, it actually proved to
be HIV (AIDS virus) free, and a number of units underwent
processing that would inactivate the virus,'' said Gene Jeffers,
American Red Cross spokesman.
   He said there was ``no known health hazard associated with the
24 units of blood. We were very fortunate and lucked out in that
there was no human risk at all involved here.''
   However, he conceded when questioned that five of the units
tested positive for hepatitis B antigens and would have posed a
health risk had they been used in transfusions. However, they were
not used, he said.
   Ten of the units initially tested positive for HIV antibodies
but they underwent fractionation, which eliminated the danger of
any contamination, Jeffers said. Fractionation breaks the blood
down into components for specific uses.
   The remaining nine units were from donors who were unacceptable
because they previously tested ``false positive,'' but all the
actual units were tested safe, he said.
   The Washington Post reported today that federal officials
recovered the 24 units, each consisting of one pint, and were
``virtually certain'' all the questionable blood had been destroyed
or quarantined.
   ``None of the blood was transfused, and we were out of the gate
in a hurry, but of course it's a worrisome event,'' Dr. Frank E.
Young, commissioner of the Food and Drug Administration, told the
Post.
   Two senior officials of the Washington regional office of the
American Red Cross _ John McGraw and Frederick Darr _ have been
suspended with pay for 30 days pending an investigation of their
actions.
   ``The purpose of the suspension is to permit us to assign
someone to make recommendations'' said Richard Schubert, president
of the American Red Cross. ``Then we will decide what to do. We are
not in a position yet to take disciplinary action.''
   Schubert said no officials in the Nashville center had been
disciplined, but that the investigation there was continuing.
   Six of the questionable units of blood were from the Washington
center and the other 18 were from Nashville.
   The mistakes in Washington were detected after the chapter found
discrepancies during a routine audit and then contacted the FDA,
which conducted a more complete investigation. The Tennessee errors
were detected when the FDA began an audit after a woman sued local
blood bank officials because she became infected with the AIDS
virus through a previous blood transfusion.
   As a result of the errors, the FDA said it has increased its
periodic audits of the blood supply and instituted new training
procedures for blood bank employees.
   ``An ongoing investigation by FDA at the two blood centers has
revealed that standard operating procedures were not followed in
handling these blood products,'' the Public Health Service said in
a statement.
   ``The FDA and the Red Cross are continuing to investigate the
issue and monitor the recall to ensure that all suspect units of
blood products are identified and that appropriate follow-up action
taken,'' the service said.
   Dr. S. Gerald Sandler, associate vice president of the American
Red Cross, said that in 1987, more than 37 million tests were
conducted on the 6 million units of blood donated, which placed
increased demands on laboratory workers.
   ``We are seriously concerned about this, and we are implementing
additional efforts to help reduce potential human errors,'' Sandler
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
