<DOCNO> AP880319-0080 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 1110EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NorthProsecution Bjt   03-19 0862</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-North Prosecution, Bjt,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Greed' Charges In Iran-Contra Case Seen As Gamble</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Independent Counsel Lawrence E. Walsh took a
riverboat gamble by steering a federal grand jury to a catch-all
indictment which includes charges that connote greed by the four
major Iran-Contra principals, legal experts say.
   Former prosecutors, interviewed by The Associated Press, said
the strategy may open a line of testimony that could draw out
sympathy for the defendants _ especially Lt. Col. Oliver L. North.
   For instance, North was accused of accepting an illegal gratuity
_ a $13,800 home security system _ from his key operative in the
Iran-Contra affair, Richard V. Secord.
   By including that particular charge, the experts said, the door
is open for North to repeat congressional testimony that he was
threatened by international terrorists including Abu Nidal.
   Defendants in the broad conspiracy indictment handed down last
week are North, a former National Security Council aide; his
onetime boss, former National Security Adviser John M. Poindexter;
Secord, a retired Air Force major general; and his business
partner, Albert Hakim.
   Most of the 23 counts focus on the broad conspiracy to aid the
Nicaraguan Contras when such assistance was banned, and attempts to
cover up the activities.
   But several counts allege motives of personal gain by North and
the Secord-Hakim enterprise _ which carried out the logistics of
aiding the Nicaraguan Contras and secret sale of U.S. arms to Iran.
   There are charges that North received the illegal gratuity of a
death benefit education fund for his children; that he used Contra
traveler's checks for personal purchases, and that the Secord-Hakim
enterprise made enormous profits.
   North has already testified under congressional immunity that he
made a bad mistake when he accepted the home security system as a
gift, then tried to cover up the gratuity. But he said he was
motivated by fears for his family in the wake of threats against
him by terrorists, including Nidal. His explanation before the
Iran-Contra congressional committees won sympathy from many
Americans who watched the proceedings live on television.
   ``That charge opened up the ability of North to admit all kinds
of evidence on terrorist groups around the world,'' said Joseph
diGenova, until recently the U.S. attorney for the District of
Columbia and now a private attorney.
   He said it would open ``a Pandora's Box of national security
information. It may not show venality, but instead a legitimate
concern for North and his family.''
   At the congressional hearings, North also disavowed knowledge of
the $200,000 death benefit fund set up for his family with money
from the U.S. arms sales to Iran.
   He apologized for trying to cover up acceptance of the security
system, saying, it ``was probably the grossest misjudgment I have
made in my life.'' In cashing the traveler's checks for personal
items, North said he was reimbursing himself for money he paid out
of his own pocket for covert activities when a special fund ran dry.
   The experts said Walsh likely has anticipated that the
defendants will wrap themselves in a cloak of patriotism, and
contend they were following legitimate orders from top government
officials. They speculated Walsh used the allegations of greedy
motives in an attempt to overcome that defense.
   ``It's much easier to persuade a jury to convict somebody who
has been advancing his personal interest, which could mean
political interest, at the expense of other people or the national
treasury,'' said Philip Hyman, a Harvard professor and former chief
of the Justice Department's criminal division.
   ``You can show you're not dealing simply with misguided
patriots, that these are also men now receiving some personal
benefits along the way, wheeling and dealing in a way that gives
them a great deal of pleasure.''
   But Philip Lacovara, a former Watergate prosecutor, agreed that
``Some of these charges give a very clear platform for North in
particular to emphasize the sympathetic role he will portray to the
jury as one of leaders in America's fight against world terrorism.
   ``He will explain the security fence as a wholly justifiable
attempt to protect his family while he was on the front line
protecting America against forces of evil,'' Lacovara said.
   Lacovara said ``one of issues I'm sure the defense will raise
will be demands for production of highly classified information.
This is the age-old question of `graymail' _ a demand for
classified information to prevent the prosecution from proceeding
with the case because risks to national security might be unwise.''
   A federal law establishes courtroom procedures that look for
alternative ways of conveying the information, but a judge could
order it released in open court if he deems it essential to protect
a defendant's rights. This leaves the prosecution with the dilemma
of whether to proceed, and can tie the case in knots.
   Another former Watergate prosecutor, Richard Ben-Veniste, said
the 101-page indictment _ combining charges of personal gain with
difficult issues like separation of powers _ could be too
complicated for jurors.
   ``My own philosophy was to be as streamlined and direct as
possible,'' he said. ``This indictment looks to me a little more of
the kitchen sink philosophy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
