<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 1112EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nepal     03-19 0688</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nepal,0710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dissent Remains Rare As Nepal Grapples With Social Problems</HEAD>
<HEAD>AN AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LABELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It is a directive for discipline from
Nepal's monarch, one of the many edicts written on red-and-yellow
signs and sprinkled throughout Katmandu. ``Speak the truth, perform
your dharma, do not fall from self-studies,'' it says.
   The dharma _ or cosmic order _ remains largely undisturbed in
Nepal. Tourists still spend money, foreign aid rolls in, and
criticism of King Birendra remains taboo.
   Rarely is the harmony upset. In the past few months, the only
public dissent has been an unsuccessful call for a general strike
and criticism from a handful of outspoken officials who later were
suspended from their jobs.
   But something is amiss amid the majesty of Nepal's mountains.
Half the 17 million residents live in poverty, only 2 percent have
sanitary sewage disposal and more than 70 percent are without safe
drinking water.
   A Nepalese born today has an average life expectancy of 47 years.
   Some blame lack of progress on meager resources. Some blame the
country's unusual government, under which political parties are
banned.
   But not even massive foreign aid _ $500 million this year _
makes much dent in Nepal's troubles.
   Not all the statistics are depressing. Life expectancy at birth
is up from 38 years in 1960. Some 70,000 Nepalese students are in
college. Tourism grew 23 percent last year, to 223,000 visitors.
   But the population is expected to jump to 24 million by the year
2000, and food production can't match it. World Bank figures show
Nepal's farms met all demands for food in 1960 but now meet only 86
percent of the nation's needs.
   Despite efforts to add jobs, one-fifth of the people have 60
percent of the private income. The bottom fifth has less than 5
percent. Per capita annual income is $160.
   Harkha Gurung, a former cabinet minister, said only about 60
percent of foreign aid that is offered can actually be used because
much of the population lives in the so-called middle hills, which
are largely inaccessible.
   ``Shortage of food and surplus of population has always been a
problem in the middle hills,'' Gurung said. ``Now they have reached
a saturation point. They can't support any more people.''
   Gurung, educated as a geographer, said Nepal's landlocked
position between India and China also blocks development. The
country's best untapped resource is hydroelectricity from its
rivers, but the only possible customer is its huge southern
neighbor, India.
   India also has come to dominate Nepal's two growth industries,
tourism and garment making. One foreign observer said Indians
``either own or control much of the cash economy'' of the country.
   But no one doubts the authority of the king.
   In Nepal, the king is advised by the Rastriya Panchayat, or
non-partisan parliament. Political parties were outlawed in 1961.
The parliament has 112 elected members and 28 appointed by the
king, with the prime minister chosen by the members.
   Nav Raj Subedi, the Panchayat chairman, noted no king has found
it necessary to veto a law passed by parliament. He insisted
dissent was welcome, but added that criticizing the partyless
system was not allowed.
   Of the dozen officials suspended last year, one was a member of
parliament who demanded a return of political parties and 11 others
were local officials who boycotted National Day ceremonies last
December.
   A strike against the suspensions was called in January by the
outlawed Nepalese Congress Party, but party officials say the
action flopped when 250 organizers were arrested. They were later
freed.
   The punishment can be more severe. A report last November by the
human rights organization Amnesty International said up to 100
political prisoners are in jail at any given time, with some kept
tied or caged as a means of torture.
   Even more staunchly forbidden is criticism of the king. One
leader in an outlawed party railed against Nepal's political
system, but turned suddenly thoughtful when asked about the monarch.
   ``Our law says we can't speak anything against the king, so we
don't say anything against the king,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
