<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Violence     03-19 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Violence,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Members Of Sikh Family Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh militants Saturday sneaked into an
Indian farmhouse and killed five members of a Sikh family as they
slept, including a 2-year-old girl, police said.
   The killings brought to 16 the number of people believed killed
by Sikh extremists during the past two days in India's northern
Punjab state, police and news reports said.
   At least 13 of the victims were Sikhs. This year, 486 killings
have been blamed on Sikh militants fighting for a separate homeland
in Punjab.
   Balbir Singh, a farmer, and four members of his family were shot
and killed early Saturday at Butt village 17 miles north of the
Sikh holy city of Amritsar, police said.
   The other victims were his wife, son, daughter-in-law and
2-year-old granddaughter. Izhar Alam, Amritsar district police
chief, said the victims were killed as they slept.
   The motive for the killings was not known, but the militants
have in the past killed fellow Sikhs who do not support their
separatist campaign.
   The United News of India said at least six other Sikhs were
killed in the district on Friday night. Three farmers were shot and
killed in separate attacks and the bodies of three Sikhs were found
at Manda village.
   Two unidentified bodies were found in nearby Janti village, the
news agency said.
   The body of a factory guard was found at Bawa village, also in
Amritsar district.
   In neighboring Jalandhar district, a farmer, Amrik Singh, was
shot and killed Friday night, UNI said. A Sikh woman, identified as
Gurdial Kaur, was killed Friday when militants opened fire at a
gathering in Ludhiana district in central Punjab, the news agency
said.
   At least 1,000 people were killed last year in the separatist
camapign, which has gone on four years. Sikhs form just 2 percent
of India's 800 million people but comprise a majority in Punjab
state.
   The militants claim that Sikhs are discriminated against by the
majority Hindu community, who form 80 percent of India's population.
</TEXT>
