<DOCNO> AP880319-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 1127EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SizingUpYazov Bjt   03-19 0801</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sizing Up Yazov, Bjt,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Americans Get a Rare Glimpse into Soviet Military Minds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At their first encounter, Soviet
Defense Minister Dmitri Yazov reminded the senior Pentagon
officials he met last week of a giant Kodiak bear _ big, rough and
gruff, with distinctive Russian features.
   ``He's a real ground-thumper, a real Soviet infantry officer,''
one senior U.S. official said after Defense Secretary Frank
Carlucci and his aides dined with Yazov. ``He seemed a little ill
at ease, not exactly cut out for this type of diplomacy.''
   But that view of Yazov changed Wednesday, during the first
business meeting ever conducted between the defense secretaries of
the superpowers. It was held in a small conference room at the U.S.
Embassy in the Swiss capital of Bern.
   Yazov, 64, showed the Americans why Kremlin leader Mikhail
Gorbachev summoned the four-star general back from his command
assignment in the Far East last May and appointed him defense
minister him over the heads of more senior candidates.
   Yazov appears committed to the task of convincing a skeptical
Soviet officer corps of the need for economic reforms. Soviet
advocates argue reforms may cut defense spending at first, but
could lead to technological progress that will ultimately benefit
the Red Army.
   ``They are desperate for `Detente 2,''' said a U.S. official,
explaining the Soviet rationale for the Yazov-Carlucci meeting.
``So they they trotted out their big, burly defense minister and
said, `Look. He's a teddy bear.' They wanted to convince us that
they are benign.''
   Yazov, wearing a business suit instead of his uniform, broke the
ice by noting how small the room was and recalling a Russian saying
that, ``although we have close quarters, we shouldn't quarrel.''
   ``Everyone got a laugh out of that,'' said Pentagon spokesman
Dan Howard. And although the talks weaved through a minefield of
explosive East-West issues, they remained, in Carlucci's words,
``cordial and businesslike.''
   Yazov delivered major statements from notes, but for the most
part spoke off the cuff, competently arguing the Kremlin position
on doctrine, force levels and tricky regional issues such as
Afghanistan and Nicaragua. He had the ability to defuse tense
moments with humor, when it suited him. Or start an argument, when
he wanted.
   On Wednesday afternoon, said a U.S. offical, Yazov ``pulled out
a map showing U.S. bases and fleets, and said, `You see how the
United States has us surrounded.'''
   Carlucci responded by ``referring to Cuba and Nicaragua, and
said, `You have got a beachhead yourselves,'' said a senior
Pentagon official, who like others interviewed, spoke on condition
of anonymity.
   The three-day session was valuable for U.S. analysts. American
policymakers had already gotten a picture of Yazov based on his
meetings with the U.S. ambassador to Moscow, Jack Matlock. The
Americans who met Yazov were particularly interested in the aides
he brought with him.
   ``We have never seen most of these guys before,'' except for
Col. Gen. Nikolai Chervov, the top Soviet military spokesmen on
arms control, said a veteran American on the team.
   The Americans included Defense and State Department
Kremlin-watchers as well as the top White House adviser on Soviet
affairs, former senior CIA analyst Fritz Ermath.
   Carlucci and Yazov did 90 percent of the talking, but they
appeared to make little headway in resolving such fundamental
disputes as who has the larger military.
   To settle the argument, Carlucci said at one point, ``the simple
thing would be to publish your military budget.''
   ``Yazov said, `well, it isn't all in one piece. It's as
difficult for us as for you''' to determine the exact level of
Soviet defense spending, recounted a senior U.S. official.
   The Americans pursued the point in less formal moments, and were
convinced that the Soviets ``really didn't know the size of the
budget or everything that was going on in their military
establishment,'' said another U.S. official.
   And Yazov didn't know everything his forces are doing.
   ``At one point, he complained about our ships collecting
electronic intelligence off their coast,'' said a senior U.S.
official.
   Carlucci responded that ``your spy ships are three miles off our
coast,'' just beyond the territorial limit, ``and they are welcome
there.''
   ``Yazov turned to an admiral (in the Soviet delegation), and
said, `Is that right?' And the admiral said, `Yeah, they're
there,''' said the U.S. official.
   Yazov kept his cool during tense moments, and showed no offense
when Carlucci demanded an apology for the fatal shooting, by a
Soviet soldier, of U.S. Army Major Arthur D. Nicholson in East
Germany three years ago. Yazov did not apologize, but promised to
re-examine the event.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Bryan Brumley, who was an Associated Press
correspondent in Moscow during the eras of Leonid Brezhnev and Yuri
Andropov, covered the Carlucci-Yazov talks in Bern.
</TEXT>
