<2ND_LINE>AM-Noriega-Asylum,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega Could Get Asylum In France Or Spain, Spanish Prime
Minister Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COTO DE DONANA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega could
be granted political asylum in France or Spain if he is forced to
relinquish his power in Panama, Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez said
Saturday.
   Gonzalez spoke to reporters just before beginning a meeting with
French President Francois Mitterrand at this national park on
Spain's southern Atlantic coast.
   Gonzalez didn't elaborate on his statement, and Mitterrand did
not speak to reporters.
   In Paris, the French Foreign Ministry said it had no comment on
whether France was prepared to offer asylum to Noriega.
   Gonzalez reiterated an offer made last week. Spain said it would
be willing to admit Noriega, chief of the Panamanian military and
the country's de facto leader, provided he requested asylum and the
United States agreed not to seek his extradition on drug
trafficking charges.
   Noriega has denied the charges.
   The Noriega-dominated National Assembly ousted Panama's civilian
president, Eric Arturo Delvalle, on Feb. 25 after Delvalle ordered
Noriega to step down from his post.
