<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Chambers 1stLd-Writethru a0470 03-19 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chambers, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0470,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deliberations Continue in Chambers Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with jury deliberations resuming
this morning, picking up 5th graf pvs, ``The jurors ....''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors deliberating the fate of murder defendant
Robert Chambers Jr. for a second day asked to hear and see again
some of the evidence and testimony presented at the 11-week trial,
but did not reach a verdict.
   Chambers, 21, is charged with second-degree murder in the
strangulation of Jennifer Levin, 18, during an early morning tryst
in Central Park on Aug. 26, 1986.
   On Friday, forewoman Debra Cavanaugh sent Justice Howard Bell a
note from jurors at 2 p.m., expressing the desire to deliberate
until 8 p.m. However, the judge cut deliberations off at 6:30 p.m.,
and a few of the jurors seemed surprised by Bell's move.
   The jurors, who resumed deliberations nearly an hour late today,
at 11:20 a.m., have spent 15{ hours discussing the case. Chambers,
his family and lawyers were in the courtroom this morning awaiting
any word.
   The jurors also asked the judge for the transcript of a taped
telephone conversation between defense lawyer Jack Litman and Dr.
Werner Spitz, the chief medical examiner of Detroit who was the
prosecution's chief witness.
   However, the transcript had not been put into evidence and was
therefore not available to jurors. In the discussion, Litman sought
to recruit Spitz as a defense witness and Spitz declined. Litman
taped the call.
   Spitz testified for the prosecution that he believed Chambers
killed Miss Levin by using her blouse to strangle her. Chambers has
contended he killed her accidentally during sex. He said he was
reacting to the pain caused when she squeezed his genitals.
   During the afternoon Friday, jurors also asked for the
following: an enlarged picture of the crime scene; an X-ray of
Chambers' right hand, showing a fractured fifth metacarpal; and a
reading of the testimony of Dr. Allan Garber, a resident physician
at Bronx Lebanon Hospital.
   Garber, who jogged by while Chambers and Levin were under a tree
in Central Park, testified that he saw a white male sitting astride
another person under a tree 30 to 40 feet off the park's East
Drive. He testified that he encountered the same scene 15 to 20
minutes later, and assumed the people he saw were having sex.
   Jurors also asked Friday to see evidence they had seen on
Thursday _ Miss Levin's clothing and lipstick case, smaller
pictures of the crime scene, photos of Miss Levin at the bar she
left with Chambers and Chambers' written statement to the police.
   The jurors, who can also convict Chambers of manslaughter or
criminally negligent homicide, were given all the material they
requested, with the exception of the transcript not entered into
evidence.
</TEXT>
