<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Kenya-Election Bjt   03-19 0582</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kenya-Election, Bjt,0602</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Candidates Turn to Brew and Lucky Charms in Search for Votes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHEGE MBITIRU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strange and bizarre things, from
witchdoctor consultants to a beer shortage brought on by frantic
politicking, have marked the whirlwind campaign leading to Monday's
nationwide elections.
   Candidates plied voters with everything from roasted goat to
dancing troupes and gallons of brew. Plenty of hopefuls turned to
that old political standby: the fists of their supporters.
   One candidate reportedly hired a witchdoctor to help him win,
but the medicine man died while preparing his lucky charms.
   This eastern African nation's traditially rowdy politicking took
an especially raucous turn this year with scrapping of secret
ballots in preliminary voting and only six weeks to campaign.
   The 200-member Parliament is a rubber-stamp body, but candidates
campaign zealously anyway. Though subservient to the president,
parliamentarians have clout in their home constituencies. They're
also courted by merchants and enjoy benefits like free housing and
cars.
   At stake are 128 parliamentary seats and hundreds of municipal
jobs. It will be the fifth general election since Kenya gained
independence from Britain in 1963. Elections are generally held
every five years.
   Candidates were pared down in a Feb. 22 primary election. For
the first time, votes were tallied as voters stood in line behind
the candidate of their choice, or a picture of the candidate.
   The government adopted the system last year, saying it would end
voting abuses such as stuffing ballot boxes. But religious leaders
and legal groups argued it would lead to intimidation of voters.
   The general election is by secret ballot. It's open to all 5.6
million registered voters among Kenya's population of 22 million.
   Under Kenyan law, the president must be a member of Parliament,
and President Daniel arap Moi returned unopposed to Parliament and
his job as head of state after preliminary voting. He announced the
election dates Feb. 5.
   Since the campaigning began, Nairobi's three English-language
newspapers have carried daily accounts of fist fights, heckling,
alleged kidnappings of candidates and riot police quelling battles
between stone-throwing supporters of rival candidates.
   The Kenya Times said one unidentified parliamentary contender
resorted to a witchdoctor.
   ``The candidate is alleged to have taken the witchdoctor to his
home ... where he prepared some charms that would bring the
candidate good luck,'' said Kenya Times. ``However the witchdoctor,
known as Madego Mwarojo, died in the process of preparing the
charms.''
   Most parliamentary hopefuls instead charm voters with piles of
promises, gobs of roasted goat or beef and a flood of beer.
   Kenya Breweries credited a sales increase of more than 10
percent over a year ago and a chronic beer shortage to the
campaigning. Working overtime, the brewery one recent weekend
distributed 12 million bottles of beer, and it wasn't enough.
   Election law sets a campaign budget ceiling of $2,400, but the
law has gone unenforced.
   Rallies are the most popular form of talking to voters, but
candidates sometimes take advantage of any gathering to win support.
   In some districts, local administrators have been forced to ban
weddings, discos and politicking in bars until after polling. In
other areas, candidates and their agents have been barred from
addressing church services, including funerals.
   Officials censor candidates' speeches for exaggerated promises
or insinuations that anyone is anti-government. Troupes of dancers
normally accompany candidates, along with busloads of
placard-carrying supporters.
   But even signs were banned at some rallies this year after
supporters used them to club rivals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
