<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Dissident     03-19 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Dissident,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Dissident Flies To London</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet dissident Herman Obukhov flew from the
Soviet Union to London on Saturday where he was greeted at Heathrow
Airport by British students who campaigned on his behalf.
   Students from Lancing College near the southern England seaside
resort of Brighton bombarded Soviet authorities with more than
2,000 letters, telexes and postcards on behalf of the 38-year-old
medical engineer from Leningrad.
   The students, members of Amnesty International, the worldwide
human rights group, also wrote letters of support to Obukhov and
his family.
   Obukhov was sentenced in 1981 to four years hard labor in a
Siberian prison camp, followed by two years of internal exile in
eastern Siberia.
   He was arrested in 1980 while trying to give a Western
journalist the manuscript of his book, ``Extinguished Dawn,'' which
criticized Soviet medical policy, particularly the use of drugs to
subdue political prisoners.
   ``My first emotion is that a sweet dream has come true,'' he
told reporters at Heathrow. ``I have waited for this moment nearly
half my life. When I finished my military service 16 years ago I
knew somehow I must get out.''
   Obukhov was forced to leave his wife Irina behind in the Soviet
Union. The couple were married while he was in prison but according
to Soviet law, the marriage has been annulled because Obukhov gave
up his Soviet citizenship to obtain an exit visa.
   During his exile, Obukhov taught himself English by reading a
novel by Evelyn Waugh, unaware the author once attended Lancing
College.
   Obukhov said he will stay at Lancing College while he decides
his future plans.
</TEXT>
