<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BritonsDetained     03-19 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britons Detained,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British TV Crew Detained after Filming Near Arms Factory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swedish police detained a British
television crew for three hours and seized film they said might
contain pictures of classified areas at a weapons factory, police
said Saturday.
   The three Britons were detained Friday night after workers saw
them filming outside Sweden's arms manufacturing Bofors' plant at
Karlskoga, 180 miles northwest of here.
   A police spokesman at Karlskoga, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said the men worked for Yorkshire Television, an
independent production company. He declined to give their names.
   ``We do not suspect that they were spying. They are well-behaved
fellows ... and they are allowed to leave the country any time.''
   ``But they may have violated a law which forbids filming such
installations as an arms factory,'' he said. ``We will know when we
have developed their film.''
   The Swedish government has been investigating Bofors Ordinance
company because it allegedly exported weapons to countries in
volatile areas, an act forbidden under neutral Sweden's arms export
laws.
   The company, a subsidiary of Nobel Sweden Industries, also has
drawn attention after allegations of extensive bribing in
connection with a major artillery deal with India.
