<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AirportShooting     03-19 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airport Shooting,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspect In Policemen Killing Arrested In Amsterdam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KARLSRUHE, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A West German music student
sought in the shooting deaths of two policemen at Frankfurt Airport
has been arrested in the Netherlands, West German authorities said
Saturday.
   Hans-Juergen Foerster, spokesman for the federal prosecutor's
office in Karlsruhe, said Frank Hoffmann, 24, was arrested in
Amsterdam on Friday.
   Foerster declined to give details and it was not known if
Hoffmann had been brought to West Germany. West German authorities
had offered a $62,500 award for information leading to his capture.
   Hoffmann was sought in connection with the killing of two
policemen during an environmentalist demonstration near Frankfurt
Airport last November. Two other officers were injured.
   The shooting of the two officers prompted authorities to seek
tougher demonstration laws, and the government later adopted
regulations that ban protesters from wearing masks.
   Authorities said the shots at the airport protest came from a
group of masked demonstrators.
   A suspect, Andreas Eichler, was arrested shortly after the
killings with the murder weapon in his possession. He has denied
firing the fatal shots and claimed that Hoffmann gave him the gun
after the shooting.
   Authorities say both men belonged to a leftist group that
frequently took part in demonstrations at the airport by
environmentalists protesting the use of a new runway.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
