<DOCNO> AP880319-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 1332EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i BC-NIreland-Chronology     03-19 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-NIreland-Chronology,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Incident Piles Upon Incident to Inflame Ulster Anew</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Northern Ireland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of diplomatic incidents and
outbreaks of violence this year that have turned Northern Ireland
into a flashpoint and soured Anglo-Irish relations after two years
of relative harmony.
   Jan. 25: The British government admits attempts were made to
obstruct justice in the case of Northern Ireland policemen involved
in the 1982 killing of six Catholics, five of them unarmed IRA
guerrillas. Nonetheless, the government says, there will be no
prosecutions. Ireland says Britain's attorney general ought to be
fired.
   Jan. 28: A British court rejects an appeal by six Irishmen
serving life sentences for planting bombs that killed 21 people in
1974 in the worst terrorist attack ever in mainland Britain. The
Irish government says the evidence suggests they are innocent.
   Feb. 16: Britain announces its tough Prevention of Terrorism
Act, hitherto renewable annually, will be made permanent. Ireland,
which regards the law as discriminatory toward Irish nationals,
protests.
   Feb. 21: A British soldier shoots and kills an unarmed Irish
Republican Army supporter as he walks through a checkpoint on the
Ireland-Northern Ireland border. The soldier claims it was an
accident and is charged with manslaughter. Ireland, in a calculated
slight to Britain, announces it will conduct its own investigation.
   Feb. 23: The army discloses that the only soldier ever sentenced
to life imprisonment for killing a Catholic civilian in Northern
Ireland has been freed and returned to his regiment, having served
less than three years of his sentence. Catholic leaders protest.
   March 6: A British anti-terrorist unit in Gibraltar kills three
IRA guerrillas who allegedly plotted to bomb a military ceremony in
the British colony. Ireland protests that the three were unarmed
and could have been captured alive.
   March 13: The cortege carrying the three Gibraltar dead from
Dublin to Belfast is stoned and jeered by Protestants along the
road.
   March 16: A Protestant extremist fires shots and lobs grenades
at mourners burying the Gibraltar dead, killing three and wounding
68.
   March 19: Mourners in the cortege of an IRA man killed at the
March 16 funeral drag two British plainclothes soldiers from their
car, beat them unconscious and strip them naked. The two are hauled
away and later found shot dead.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
