<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Talks     03-19 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Talks,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras Spokesman Say Cease-Fire Talks Are Still On</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With AM-Nicaragua-Sandinistas, Bjt
^By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaragua's Contra rebels are
willing to hold cease-fire talks as scheduled this week with the
Sandinista government, despite threatening earlier to boycott them,
a Contra spokesman said Saturday.
   The U.S.-backed rebels last week accused Sandinista troops of
invading Honduras in pursuit of Contras and said they would boycott
the talks unless the Sandinistas withdrew.
   But Carlos Hurtado, an adviser to the six-member directorate of
the Contra umbrella organization, Nicaraguan Resistance, said his
side was ready for Monday's talks.
   In Managua, the Nicaraguan capital, President Daniel Ortega said
Friday his government was also ``ready and willing'' to hold the
talks.
   For the first time, the talks are scheduled to take place inside
Nicaraguan territory, in the southern town of Sapoa near the Costa
Rican border.
   The cease-fire talks, which are part of a peace plan the five
Central American presidents signed last night, were almost called
off by both the Contras and the Sandinistas because of the fighting
that flared up along the Nicaragua-Honduras border during the past
two weeks.
   Claiming that Sandinista troops had entered Honduran territory
while chasing Contra troops, the Reagan administration last week
sent 3,200 American troops to Honduras as both a warning to the
Sandinistas and a show of support for Honduras.
   ``But after several days of talks with Costa Rican President
Oscar Arias and former Venezuelan President Carlos Andres Perez,
the Nicaraguan Resistance decided to go to the meeting,'' Hurtado
said in an interview. He did not elaborate.
   ``Even though the fighting continues, mostly in northern
Nicaragua and our fighters have been scattered towards the Atlantic
coast of the country without suffering great damage, we have
decided to attend the meeting,'' Hurtado said.
   ``We want to show we are willing to seek a peaceful solution to
the problem afflicting our country,'' he added.
   The regional peace plan, devised by Arias, calls for
negotiations to end the war in Nicaragua and leftist guerrilla wars
in El Salvador and Guatemala.
   Arias was awarded the 1987 Nobel Peace Prize for the plan which
also calls for cease-fires, an end to outside intervention in
Central America, removal of all foreign military from the area,
negotiations for national reconciliations between governments and
opposition and reforms to bring greater democracy to the region.
   Defense Minister Gen. Humberto Ortega, the Nicaraguan
president's brother, will head the Sandinista delegation _ the
Contras have been insisting the Sandinistas be represented ``at the
highest level.''
   The rebel delegation will be represented by all six members of
the Nicaraguan Resistance directorate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
