<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DemocraticText     03-19 0731</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democratic Text,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Reagan-Radio Text</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of the Democratic Party's
response, delivered by Rep. Pat Williams of Montana, to President
Reagan's radio address on Saturday:
   Hello, this is Congressman Pat Williams. I represent Western
Montana in the United States Congress.
   This week, much of the news at home and abroad was discouraging.
The economy remains particularly fragile, the trade deficit is
still dangerously high and, of course, American troops are in
Central America. But, nonetheless, there is particularly good news
to announce from the House of Representatives.
   For the first time in the history of the House Budget Committee,
the federal budget was passed bipartisanly without a single
objection. The agreement, of course, took much work, but the
members of the House Budget Committee completed our blueprint for
federal efforts for the coming year.
   It is a responsible, lean, bipartisan federal budget.
   Most Americans probably missed the news about our budget. That
ought not to be surprising. Controversy routinely creates the
biggest headlines. That's been especially true of the big budget
battles Congress too often has fought in these last several years.
   This time, there was no fight to report. Members of the Budget
Committee have cooperated to approve our new federal budget without
objection.
   As you may remember, the foundation for our budget was laid this
past December at the economic summit between the Congress and the
president.
   Those summit talks, of course, followed last fall's stock market
drop, and they came with the recognition that delay in putting this
nation's fiscal affairs in order could no longer be tolerated.
   Our country began this decade with a national debt of $914
billion. In seven years, that debt exploded to $2.8 trillion _ a
three-fold increase, bigger than any in our 200-year history.
   When this session of the 100th Congress convened in January,
House Speaker Jim Wright fashioned an agenda for our work this
year. Cooperation on the budget between Democrats and Republicans
was the paramount goal of the speaker.
   This budget achieves that goal and complies with the spending
limits set by the economic summit.
   Importantly, this budget _ provided the economy suffers no
serious downturn _ will avoid the automatic, across-the-board
Gramm-Rudman cuts.
   That, by the way, is the way the American people have a right to
expect their Congress to work _ for elected officials to make the
hard choices instead of abandoning them to faceless computers.
   This budget meets a high national responsibility. It fulfills
the right and proper obligation of government to extend a hand to
those citizens among us, those who live in poverty or near to it,
those inflicted by misfortune, those citizens both young and old
who need just a little help to live decent lives and realize the
American promise of a good life.
   This budget provides full protection for those folks and
stitches the numerous holes in our government's so-called ``safety
net.''
   This year, despite his periodic calls in the past for
reductions, the president properly asked Congress for increased
funding for education. We wholeheartedly agree _ so much so that
our budget provides 4 percent more than the White House recommended
for America's schools.
   Our budget does this as well: It adds new revenues to assist
those tragically swelling the ranks of homeless Americans. It
provides funds to fight our nation's war against drugs. It calls
for $1 billion in new appropriations to keep the United States on
the cutting edge of space exploration. We also provide the funds
the president agreed to at the economic summit to keep our national
defense forces strong.
   Every budget must comply with the deficit limits. This year that
deficit target is $136 billion and our budget comes in a full $2
billion below that target.
   This year, the budget is on time. Both House Speaker Wright and
the president, and especially the American people, are correctly
insistent that Congress not fall behind on its budget and
appropriations schedule and not rely on a mammoth year-end spending
bill.
   With this budget, the Congress is not only on time _ we are
ahead of time and we intend to remain on time and move our budget
proposal to the floor of the House next week for debate and passage
and then on to the Senate for its prompt consideration.
   This is Congressman Pat Williams. Thank's for listening.
</TEXT>
