<DOCNO> AP880319-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 1422EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DeathRow     03-19 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Death Row,0599</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Darden Death Leaves Several Visible Killers Awaiting Execution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BIRK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The execution of Willie Jasper Darden
has focused attention on the nation's largest death row, where some
well-known killers, including serial killers Theodore Bundy and
Gerald Stano, await their fate.
   Darden's execution left 287 convicted murderers in the death row
wings of the Florida State Prison near Starke.
   Darden avoided execution for 14{ years after being placed on
death row in January 1974, earlier than any of his surviving
inmates except one. While pursuing his appeals, he survived an
unprecedented six death warrants, until his appeals ran out on No.
7 last Tuesday.
   Bundy, linked to more than 20 sex slayings in Washington, Utah,
Colorado and Florida, is under separate death sentences for the
1978 bludgeoning murders of Florida State University sorority
sisters Lisa Levy and Margaret Bowman and for the murder of
12-year-old Kimberly Leach in Lake City.
   Bundy, subject of at least four books and a television
miniseries, has been on death row since August 1979 and has
survived three death warrants.
   Stano, a former short-order cook from Daytona Beach, has
confessed to dozens of killings and is under three death sentences
for the murders of Susan Bickrest and Cathy Muldoon in Volusia
County and Cathy Lee Scharf.
   He also has been sentenced six times to life in prison for other
Florida killings. He has been on death row since January 1984 and
has survived three warrants.
   Capital punishment supporters urge the state to press Bundy's,
Stano's and other cases.
   But while their appeals may seem to linger, some 50 death row
cases are older than Bundy's and some 140 are older than Stano's,
according to Department of Corrections records.
   The governor's office can push the cases forward only as quickly
as legal roadblocks to execution fall. That's up to the courts.
   ``It's counter-productive to sign a warrant if they're not at an
appropriate stage to sign one when you know they have an automatic
appeal,'' said Andrea Hillyer, an attorney for Gov. Bob Martinez
who handles death cases.
   ``You just have to wait until courts are through with different
stages,'' she said. ``It's hard to predict, we just monitor their
cases.''
   On April 7, mass murderer Robert Dale Henderson is scheduled to
to be executed for three of 12 slayings he is believed responsible
for during a spree that started in Ohio and continued through South
Carolina, Mississippi, Louisiana and Florida.
   However, Henderson's case dates back only six years, and it's
generally expected that his attorneys still have plenty of room for
appeals that would gain a stay of execution.
   Martinez, who has signed 33 death warrants since taking office
Jan. 6, 1987, and seen only two inmates put to death, broke a
record with Darden's final death warrant by allowing Darden's
attorneys only seven days to appeal.
   All the other 17 men executed since Florida returned to the
death penalty in 1979 had three or fewer death warrants.
   Martinez, noting that Darden, condemned for the slaying of a
furniture store owner, had a career criminal record and that he had
14-plus years of appeals, felt no remorse about the hurried
execution schedule.
   ``I think of the whole case, not just the person whose name is
on the death warrant,'' the governor said after Darden's death. ``I
think of the person who died years ago because of the killing. I
think of the family that was left behind.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880319-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 1428EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CatalogTax Bjt   03-19 0713</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Catalog Tax, Bjt,0729</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyers Say $44,000 Case Could Have Billion-Dollar Ramifications</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET McCONNAUGHEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. businesses might have to pay billions of
dollars in new taxes if the U.S. Supreme Court agrees that
Louisiana may tax a New Orleans store for catalogs it had printed
in and mailed from other states, the store's lawyer says.
   The case involves $43,937.03 in use taxes assessed against the
D.H. Holmes Co. department store chain, but lawyers for both sides
agree that the ramifications go far beyond that.
   ``I threw out the figure of $800 million at a meeting of the Tax
Executive Institute in New York. ... People said that was a half or
a quarter of the taxes it would raise,'' William F. Grace Jr., an
attorney for Holmes, said in an interview.
   Use taxes are imposed on property brought in from another state
for use, consumption, distribution or storage. Louisiana, like most
states, sets the use tax equal to its sales tax minus any sales
taxes charged to the purchaser.
   The catalogs in question were designed in New York, printed in
three other states and mailed from those states to customers in
Louisiana with Holmes charge accounts.
   The case to be heard Tuesday by the high court is probably the
most significant in interstate commerce since the L.L. Bean sales
tax case 15 years ago, say both Grace and William Pugh, who is
arguing for Louisiana.
   In the Bean case, the court ruled that mail-order companies
don't have to collect sales taxes from customers in states where
they have no employees or property.
   If the high court upholds state court rulings against Holmes,
Grace said, states could tax such things as flyers sent with credit
card bills, catalogs from national chains with stores in their
states and even telephone directories.
   ``We think it would be a tremendous burden on business and could
be crippling to ... retailers who send tons of their advertising
and catalog materials across state lines,'' said Lee Williams of
the American Retail Federation, which filed one of seven
friend-of-the-court briefs in the case, said in a telephone
interview from Washington.
   ``All of the states are starved for revenues. They're going to
look wherever they can. ... It could turn into big bucks,'' said
Williams, the legislative counsel and a vice president of the
federation.
   ``We contend ... that Holmes did not use these catalogs in
Louisiana. There was no use by Holmes because when the taxes were
imposed, the catalogs were being transmitted in the U.S. mails,''
Grace said. ``At that time, they were not subject to tax.''
   Pugh, a Shreveport attorney retained to represent the Department
of Revenue and Taxation, said the case hinges on ownership.
   ``I would contend and did contend and shall contend that Holmes
owned the catalogs when they were designed, Holmes owned the
catalogs when they were printed, Holmes owned the catalogs when
they were mailed, and Holmes owned the catalogs when they arrived
at the post office boxes,'' he said.
   That argument could mean trouble for catalog companies, said Bob
Levering, legislative counsel for the Direct Marketing Association
in Washington, D.C.
   If the Supreme Court agrees that a company possesses and is
using something while it is being sent through the mail, he said,
it could open the way for taxes on all kinds of mailings, he said.
   Courts in Tennessee, Illinois, New York, Ohio, South Dakota,
Wisconsin and the District of Columbia have reached rulings
opposite to Louisiana's, said Andrew Rinker Jr., another lawyer for
Holmes. But he said Missouri's case was decided the other way.
   One of two legal briefs supporting Louisiana was filed on behalf
of the National Governors Association, National Association of
Counties, Council of State Governments, International City
Management Association, National Conference of State Legislatures,
National League of Cities and U.S. Conference of Mayors. The other
was from the Multistate Tax Commission.
   In addition to the retail federation, the Direct Marketing
Association, the National Association of Catalog Showroom
Merchandisers and the Committee of State Taxation of the Council of
State Chambers of Commerce have filed individual
friend-of-the-court briefs. Magazine Publishers of America Inc.,
Printing Industries of America and R.R. Donnelly & Sons Co., a
catalog publisher, joined forces for another.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880319-0111 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 1449EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Panama-Crisis     03-19 0663</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Crisis,0691</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Panamanians Rely On Ingenuity, Family to Weather Cash Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With banks closed and cash scarce
because of a U.S. financial embargo against the military regime,
Panamanians are resorting to family ties and ingenuity to survive.
Life isn't as easy as it used to be.
   Until recently, Panamanians were used to the good life. The
Panama Canal, a major oil pipeline, and offshore banking propelled
an economy envied by other Central American nations.
   Prosperity ended when the United States applied pressure to oust
the military strongman, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, after a
federal grand jury indicted him on drug trafficking charges and
Noriega supporters ousted Panama's civilian president, Eric Arturo
Delvalle.
   ``We have had it so easy, that we are really suffering now with
this crisis,'' said an Education Ministry employee who identified
himself only as Joaquin. ``We are not a warring type of people. We
are used to the good life.''
   A government worker, who identified herself only as Isabel,
warned of dire consequences if things don't change.
   ``Many families are getting together and sharing everything,''
she said.
   ``My husband works. We can survive. I do not know how other
people who make less can make it. If this keeps up, people will be
on the streets looting, looking for food,'' she said.
   Some Panamanians have adapted with aplomb. Companies have
bartered goods among themselves and supplemented employees' pay
with food coupons redeemable at local stores.
   ``We have better credit than the government,'' said a
businessman who paid his workers each with $20 cash and the rest in
food coupons.
   The cash crisis has hit government workers the hardest.
   First, their paychecks were late when the government, which uses
the U.S. dollar and thus can't just print new bills, lost its
credit.
   When the government finally paid workers, those making up to
$1,000 a month received only $75, including $30 in commemorative
coins issued in 1978 to mark the ratification of the treaties
turning control of the canal over to Panama at the end of the
century.
   To many teachers, the big, round commemorative coins were a
strange sight. ``What is this: some sort of token?'' asked one
teacher, a middle-aged woman.
   The money not only looked strange but fell far short of most
people's needs. ``The landlord is going to have to wait,'' said one
teacher.
   Meanwhile, food is foremost in everyone's mind.
   ``I had nothing to eat yesterday,'' said a mother of two who
identified herself only as Carmen. ``I wish I had known about this
a few months ago, I would not have separated from my husband.''
   She said she was going to stock up on milk for her youngest
child. ``I am going to buy enough for two weeks because you never
know what is going to happen,'' she said. ``I can stand hunger; the
baby cannot.''
   Other families began to ration for their own needs.
   High school teacher Hugo Lloyd said he cannot pay his rent or
utility bills. Lloyd said he and his wife are staying home with
their children because schools are closed.
   ``We ration everything,'' he said. ``You know, we used to say
that we would never see rationing in Panama like you see in other
countries.''
   Technician Arturo Gonzalez was worried about feeding his
household of 11. ``The problem is that kids always want what
they've always had _ candies and stuff,'' he said. ``We had to
eliminate luxuries like fancy deodorants and shaving lotions and
some food spices.''
   Even some opponents of Noriega wondered why Panama's people
should bear the brunt of the crisis.
   ``I do not agree with these military rulers that have a false
civilian government up front,'' said the Education Ministry worker
Joaquin. ``The U.S. even supported this government _ practically
created it. Now it does not want it, and the people of Panama are
paying a high price.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880319-0112 </DOCNO>
