<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 1503EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Armenia     03-19 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Armenia,0613</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leaders Of Caucasus Region Again Call For Union With Armenia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist leaders in a disputed region of the
Caucasus have called again for union with Armenia, repeating an
earlier demand that helped spark bloody riots which left at least
32 people dead.
   The decisions of the party committee in the Nagorno-Karabakh
Autonomous Region, part of Soviet Azerbaijan since 1923, were
reported in the area's newspaper Friday. A copy of the paper was
obtained Saturday.
   The actions showed that despite complaints from national
officials about their handling of the dispute, leaders of the
Delaware-sized region were unshaken in their desire to unite the
territorial enclave inside Azerbaijan with Armenia, a neighboring
Soviet republic.
   Sovietsky Karabakh, the party and government newspaper in
Nagorno-Karabakh, said the region's party committee held a plenary
meeting Thursday in the region's capital, Stepanakert, that focused
on the territorial quarrel.
   The paper said the committee ``expressing the aspirations of the
Armenian population of the autonomous region, the will of the
overwhelming majority of Communists of Nagorno-Karabakh, asks the
Politburo'' to allow it to become part of Armenia.
   It would be highly unusual for a local party committee to go on
record with a demand that had not been previously been cleared by
Moscow.
   Conflict over the region's affiliation led to huge street
protests in the Armenian capital of Yerevan last month and ethnic
rioting in the Azerbaijan city of Sumgait on Feb. 28. At least 32
people were killed in Sumgait.
   On Friday, top Soviet officials, including No. 2 Kremlin leader
Yegor K. Ligachev, met with leading Armenians and Azerbaijanis
living in Moscow to express concern about the turmoil.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev appealed Feb. 26 for ``civic
maturity and restraint'' in Armenia and Azerbaijan and pledged that
the policy-making Central Committee would soon review relations
among the Soviet Union's more than 100 nationalities.
   Armenian nationalist Paruyr Ayrikyan told a news conference
Saturday that his countrymen are divided about whether to proceed
with a plan to demonstrate March 26 to underscore demands that
Nagorno-Karabakh, whose population is more than three-quarters
Armenian, be made part of Armenia.
   Ayrikyan said rumors spread in Armenia that the Central
Committee will meet March 28 for the plenary meeting Gorbachev
promised. ``People are being told, `Don't have the rally on March
26, so as not to hinder the plenum on the 28th,''' Ayrikyan said.
   There has been no official word of when a plenum will be held.
The meetings of the 300-plus member body take place behind closed
doors and are rarely announced in advance.
   In addition to renewing its annexation demand, the regional
plenum also sent Second Secretary V.A. Bogoslovsky into retirement,
and replaced him with B.A. Malkov, who previously worked as an
instructor in the Moscow-based Central Committee's department of
party organization and work, Sovietsky Karabakh reported.
   Western Sovietologists say local party second secretaries are
usually Russians or other Slavs, and that they act as a separate
conduit of information to Moscow.
   Malkov's previous post indicates he is known to top party
officials in the capital.
   The plenum's call echoed one made Feb. 20 by the
Nagorno-Karabakh Soviet, or legislature, which asked central
authorities to shift the territory to Armenian control.
   It was the refusal of the party's national Central Committee to
accede to that demand that sparked protests.
   Since unrest began in the Caucasus, Western reporters have not
been allowed to visit the region to gather information, and have
been unable independently to confirm or deny numerous reports of
ethnic strife and violence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
