<DOCNO> AP880319-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 1511EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FiscalWoes     03-19 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fiscal Woes,0667</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Roemer Runs Headlong Into Fiscal Crisis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Buddy Roemer originally thought
Louisiana's problem was a $150 million budget shortfall, but Monday
he'll give the Legislature his initial ideas on dealing with a $2
billion crisis.
   Roemer is the first to admit that his ambitious plans for
economic development and changes in education, the state's tax
system and environmental protection will have to take a back seat
to the budget crisis.
   ``We are in a position this fiscal year where the numbers drive
the policy and not the policy driving the numbers,'' the governor
said. ``When this state is busted, broke, when the deficit is
approaching a number too large to comprehend, the numbers are
driving this now.''
   The special legislative session convenes Monday for a maximum
10-day run to deal with problems caused largely by the slump in the
oil and gas industry.
   In addition to searching for short-term budget relief, lawmakers
will be asked to split the giant Department of Health and Human
Resources into two agencies and dissolve the Department of Urban
and Community Affairs.
   The governor also has promised proposals to do away with certain
boards and commissions.
   During Roemer's first week in office, there was talk about the
need to ``scrub the budget,'' but the overview expanded into
long-term financing of an estimated $1.3 billion in accumulated
debt and expenses that will be pushed into the next fiscal year.
   Roemer says the state also faces a $750 million shortfall
between anticipated revenues for the 1988-89 budget year and
current expenditures.
   Roemer said that when he first took office, he thought about
$150 million in spending reductions would produce a balanced budget.
   Although Commissioner of Administration Brian Kendrick said he
plans to slash spending to produce a balanced budget proposal,
Roemer said about $300 million in additional taxes may be needed.
   Roemer said taxes would not be considered during the special
session, but Kendrick said the administration will ask for a $90
million increase in fees for certain state services.
   Two ideas are being explored to pay off the $1.3 billion in
accumulated debt and delayed expenditures _ issuance of short-term
notes against projected tax revenues or of long-term bonds that
would be financed through a dedicated source of revenue.
   The first order of business, according to administration
officials, will be to stumble through the rest of the 1987-88
fiscal year through budget cuts and delayed expenditures.
   Already on tap are plans to push one state payday beyond June
30, delay state contributions to retirement systems and vendor
payments and hold up state income tax refund checks.
   The state also will try to take advantage of the depressed real
estate market by renegotiating leases for government office space,
said Kendrick. Some agencies already have been ordered to vacate
leased space and move back into state-owned buildings.
   On Friday, Kendrick met with representatives of major Louisiana
cities to discuss the possibility of withholding such state
payments as revenue sharing and supplemental pay for police and
firefighters.
   ``As we all know, the news is bad. This state is broke. It's
going to take a lot of pain to get us out,'' said Alexandria Mayor
Ned Randolph. ``It's going to take some real curative work.''
   The administration is scheduled to go to court Tuesday to answer
a suit filed by 14 state employees challenging the legality of the
delay of the payday and retirement contributions.
   Roemer said that without the pay plan, there will be layoffs.
   ``If you look at the options, I don't have any, that's it. OK?''
he said. ``And I don't like it. I'm not enthusastic about it. But
that's between $38 million and $45 million we don't have. One
option is to shut this baby (government) down about the 12th of
May. I don't find that very interesting to anybody.''
</TEXT>
