<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     03-19 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MACOMB, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An emergency drive through McDonough County
ended when a police officer named McBride delivered a baby for a
couple named McGrew in Macomb (or should it be McComb?) _ all on
St. Patrick's Day.
   Jason Patrick McGrew was born late Thursday in the driveway of
the Illinois State Police District 14 headquarters.
   Melody McGrew said she and her husband got a late start for the
hospital 20 miles away because she had already had one false alarm.
   ``I guess I wanted to be sure I was ready,'' she said.
   Mrs. McGrew and her husband, Dave, of rural Walnut Grove, were
en route when it became clear the baby's arrival was imminent, and
they stopped at the police station.
   McGrew went in seeking help, and Patrolman Vern McBride, a
former ambulance worker with training in delivering babies, ran out
just in time.
   ``My husband is a farmer and he has delivered many animals, so I
have confidence in him,'' said Mrs. McGrew. ``I think he was a
little nervous, though, when he ran into the police station. That's
the fastest I'd seen him run all day.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   By the time Reinhold Holtkamp is
finished, he hopes to see purple, pink and white violets decorating
the window sills of most American homes.
   Holtkamp brought his family from West Germany to the United
States some 10 years ago with a mission of spreading the violet
craze to this relatively pioneer territory.
   ``If you walk through the streets in Germany, I don't know of a
window sill that doesn't have a violet on it. It's considered a
necessity there,'' said Reinhold Holtkamp Jr., who helps his father
run Holtkamp Greenhouses.
   ``It's not that way in the States at all. But it wasn't that way
in Germany 20 years ago either,'' said the younger Holtkamp, whose
grandfather is considered the Johnny Appleseed of the violet
industry.
   Holtkamp Greenhouses this year will produce more than 12 million
violets in Nashville, making it the largest grower of violets in
the country.
   Worldwide, its operations in Germany, Japan, Spain and Nashville
will nurture some 65 million of the dainty plants, making the
family business the largest producer of violets on the planet.
   ``If a person is successful at growing violets, they're not
going to stop at growing just one. They become very committed. .. .
Our business is 30 percent above last year,'' Holtkamp said.
</TEXT>
