<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Jordan     03-19 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Jordan,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tass Indicates that Jordanian Prime Minister, Soviets Mideast
Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tass news agency indicated that Jordan's prime
minister and Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze agreed
Saturday that the U.S. plan for a Middle East peace conference
merits further examination
   The government agency said Jordanian Prime Minister Zaid
Al-Rifai and Shevardnadze discussed the plan and ``noted the
expediency of continuing a substantive talk with the U.S.
administration on issues of a Middle East settlement.''
   U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz submitted his plan for
negotiations two weeks ago to Israel, Jordan and Syria and asked
for replies by mid-March.
   He proposed that the United States, Soviet Union, China, Britain
and France hold a conference on the Middle East next month to
prepare for negotiations May 1. He also called on Israel to cede
part of the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip in exchange for Arab
recognition.
   Jordan's King Hussein has refused to enter peace talks with
Israel except at an international conference.
   But Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir rejects such a forum
because he believes it would allow the Soviet Union ``to push a
settlement favorable to themselves and their Syrian clients.''
   Shamir prefers direct negotiations with Jordan and Palestinians
under limited U.S. and Soviet auspices.
   The Tass dispatch said Al-Rifai and Shevardnadze ``pointed out
that the only realistic way leading to a just and all-embracing
settlement of the conflict ... is convocation of an international
conference with the participation of all directly interested
parties, including the PLO.''
   Shultz's plan excludes the Palestine Liberation Organization
from the negotiations. Palestinians approved by the PLO would be in
a delegation with Jordan.
   The Soviet news agency said Shevardnadze and Al-Rifai, in a
Moscow meeting, ``pointed to the danger and inadmissibility of
partial, separate understandings which interfere with settling the
Arab-Israeli conflict and lead to a split between Arab countries.''
It was not clear which understandings Tass referred to.
   Shevardnadze is scheduled to discuss the Middle East peace
efforts with Shultz and other U.S. officials in Washington this
week.
</TEXT>
