<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Nicaragua     03-19 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Nicaragua,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Accuse U.S. In Nicaragua Dispute</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Honduras, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The official Tass news agency accused the United
States on Saturday of using military threats to impose its will on
Nicaragua and spoil peace efforts in Central America.
   The Tass dispatch, the most extensive Soviet comment on the
dispatch of 3,200 U.S. troops to Honduras last week, did not
mention the Kremlin's support of Nicaragua's Sandinista government.
   ``Washington is actually doing its utmost for preventing a just
peaceful settlement in Central America, for procrastinating and
aggravating the conflict despite its eloquent statements in favor
of the termination of regional conflicts,'' Tass said.
   The dispatch, read on the national television evening news
program and on Soviet radio, was billed as a ``Tass statement,''
one step short of a government statement but still clearly carrying
the Kremlin's endorsement.
   President Reagan sent the troops after Nicaragua allegedly
crossed the border into Honduras in pursuit of Contra rebels.
   The United States has been supplying the Contras with weapons
and other aid for years, but Congress last month ordered an end to
the assistance.
   The Soviet Union and its allies gave Nicaragua $500 million in
economic assistance and $600 million in military aid in 1986,
according to the Pentagon.
   Tass accused the U.S. government of sending the troops to
Honduras to destroy the Central American peace plan signed in
Guatemala last summer.
   The statement listed Washington's harmful actions as
``opposition to the implementation of the Guatemala Accords, the
desire to keep other Latin American countries away from the
political process, and the continuing attempts to legalize the
military assistance to the mercenaries who invaded the Nicaraguan
territory and are using methods of terror against the Nicaraguan
people.''
   It accused the United States of attempting to ``impose its will
on peoples of sovereign countries.''
   The statement made no mention of the Soviet Union's military aid
and other close ties to Nicaragua or say whether the Kremlin would
be willing to end its support of the Sandinista government to help
foster peace. It said only that the Soviet Union ``is ready to
constructively promote'' implementation of the Guatemala Accords.
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze was to leave for
Washington on Sunday to discuss the Central American tensions and
other issues with U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz.
</TEXT>
