<HEAD>U.N. Observer Mission Heading To Nicaragua</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Honduras, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of U.N. observers will visit
Nicaragua as soon as possible to investigate the border conflict
with Honduras, a U.N. spokesman said Saturday.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar decided to send the
team at Nicaragua's request. He said it would include one political
officer from U.N. headquarters and an undecided number of military
observers, U.N. spokesman Mahbub Ahmad said.
   Diplomatic sources said the team was likely to include two
military observers and probably would leave on Tuesday. The
observers have not been named.
   The announcement followed a Security Council meeting Friday
night during which Nicaragua, Honduras and the United States traded
allegations over whether Sandinista troops are in Honduran
territory and who is responsible for the current conflict.
   Several Latin American speakers endorsed Nicaragua's call for a
neutral U.N. observer mission to visit the site of the border
clashes.
   Ahmad said there are no immediate plans to visit the Honduran
side of the border. Sources said no request had come from Honduras.
   Nicaragua has requested a joint mission by the U.N. and the
Organization of American States to investigate the border situation
and make recommendations on preventing further conflict.
