<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SovietFiance     03-19 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Fiance,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teacher's Soviet Fiance Arriving After 21-Year-Courtship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LYNN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American teacher who first met her Soviet
fiance 21 years ago and hasn't seen him in eight years says she's
excited and nervous at the prospect of being reunited with him this
week.
   Victor Novikov, 56, a research chemist in Moscow, is scheduled
to arrive Saturday from the Soviet Union on a three-month
immigration visa, said Elizabeth Condon, 45, a Russian and French
teacher in Woburn public schools.
   The couple have been unable to see each other since Oct. 28,
1979, when they tried to marry in the Soviet Union but were blocked
by Soviet officials.
   Over the intervening years, Ms. Condon's requests for visas to
visit the Soviet Union were turned down repeatedly, as were
Novikov's attempts to come to the United States.
   The couple met in 1967 when Ms. Condon had a temporary job in
Moscow. Over the years, she has visited the Soviet Union 10 times.
   ``The efforts of the Reagan administration in the last two years
in working with the Soviets to resolve cases like ours created a
little bit of hope,'' she said.
   The two finally learned in December that Novikov was among 15
Soviet residents who would be allowed to emigrate after years of
being rebuffed.
   ``We're both very excited, and nervous,'' said Ms. Condon.
``After all, we haven't seen each other for 8{ years. We may need
name tags.''
   She said that if they marry within the three months of his visa,
there will be nothing to keep Novikov from staying in the United
States.
   As for their immediate plans, ``we first have to get
reacquainted and I hope to get Victor into an English class,'' Ms.
Condon said.
</TEXT>
