<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 1637EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CancerPrize     03-19 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cancer Prize,0598</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cancer Researcher First Woman, Fourth American, To Win Saudi Award</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIO FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A University of Chicago researcher is a little
worried about fitting in when she goes to Saudi Arabia to accept
the King Faisal International Prize on Tuesday for her breakthrough
in cancer research.
   ``I don't want to do anything offensive. I want to follow their
dress code,'' said Dr. Janet Davison Rowley, the first woman and
fourth American to receive the prestigious award in that Middle
Eastern nation with strict rules on how women may act and dress in
public.
   But she said she knows there have been many changes in the
Islamic country. And she doesn't plan to pack a veil in her
suitcase.
   ``In the 1960s, girls weren't even going to schools and young
women now are in medical school,'' said the University of Chicago
researcher, who discovered a link between genes and leukemia.
   Mrs. Rowley, 62, is being honored by the King Faisal Foundation
for ``service to humanity.''
   Mrs. Rowley is the only woman among the 45 prizewinners chosen
since 1976, when the foundation was established by the late
monarch's U.S.-educated sons to honor work in a variety of fields,
said spokeswoman Karen Strickholm in Los Angeles.
   She plans to spoil herself a bit with the $47,000 cash prize.
   ``This sounds self-indulgent. I have a nice garden where my
husband and I live and I'm tired of lugging garden hoses around. So
I'm going to buy a sprinkling system,'' she said. ``If there's any
money left over, then I'll think of something else.''
   Mrs. Rowley's scientific breakthrough came in 1972 while she
studied chromosomes from leukemia victims. Chromosomes carry the
genes that convey hereditary characteristics. There are 46
chromosomes in a normal human cell.
   Mrs. Rowley noticed one day that in nearly all leukemia
patients, a piece of chromosome No. 9 had broken off and switched
places with a piece of chromosome No. 22.
   She raced to the library to see if anyone else had observed this
phenomenon.
   ``They hadn't,'' she recalled. ``It was one of the greatest
moments of my life.''
   Mrs. Rowley has received other honors for her work, but her path
wasn't easy. The discovery came after she'd spent 10 years bent
over a microscope in a small corner of laboratory space.
   But if she'd started later, it might never have happened at all.
   ``I'm convinced that there would be less chance of it today,''
Mrs. Rowley said. ``A lot of the money is diverted to defense, and
there's more researchers. I had no research background and had to
find someone to take me in.''
   Dr. Leon O. Jacobson gave her a chance at his University of
Chicago laboratory in 1962 on a part-time basis after she finished
medical school, Mrs. Rowley said.
   ``She certainly convinced me that she was someone I should take
on,'' Jacobson said. ``She's always working, doing, thinking.''
   Now, Mrs. Rowley tries to do her bit for today's young
researchers.
   ``I'd like to be remembered for my scientific contributions,
which I think are important in understanding the link between
chromosomes and disease,'' she said.
   ``But I'd also like to be remembered as an honorable individual
who worked very hard to help young people in the lab and elsewhere
to further their careers.''
   Mrs. Rowley now oversees more than a dozen other University of
Chicago biomedical researchers. Her husband, Donald, is a pathology
professor at the university.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
