<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Community-ArmsControl     03-19 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Community-Arms Control,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Citizens Forum Addresses Arms Control Debate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet and U.S. governments should thaw out
the Cold War because their citizens are weary of the arms race, a
Soviet official and an American peace activist said Saturday.
   But Edward J. Derwinski, undersecretary of the U.S. State
Department, countered, ``There's nothing wrong with a `cold' war _
it means the absence of a hot war.''
   Derwinski, the Rev. William Sloane Coffin Jr. and Oleg Benyukh,
minister of public information for the Soviet Embassy in
Washington, D.C., were among officials, professors and peace
activists on hand to address a conference at Governors State
University in suburban University Park.
   Arms control ``has direct impact on every local community, so
each community should be part of this discussion,'' said Coffin,
president of SANE@FREEZE, one of the sponsors of the daylong event.
   ``I think Americans, as well as the Soviet people, are sick and
tired of the Cold War,'' Benyukh said in a telephone interview.
   Benyukh said the conference and similar meetings across the
United States and in his country are ``steps in the right
direction'' toward achieving peace.
   ``The mistrust we have today comes from not knowing each
other,'' Benyukh said. ``The more we talk the better we understand
each other,'' he said.
   ``And when we live in peace with each other, isn't it a waste to
spend so much money on armament?'' the Soviet official said.
   Citizens should assert their views about the direction the U.S.
government should take on arms control, because experts have lost
perspective on the subject, Coffin said in a telephone interview.
   ``I hope we do kick the cold war habit. It is politically and
economically disastrous,'' said Coffin, a former chaplain at Yale
University.
   But Derwinski said arms control is too complex an issue for
citizens to grapple with and will remain in the hands of the
experts.
   Saturday's conference was sponsored by the Chicago Sun-Times;
Star Publications, a suburban newspaper; a suburban chapter of
SANE@FREEZE, a non-profit, non-partisan community peace group; and
the university.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
