<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 2dLd-Writethru   03-19 0689</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 2d Ld-Writethru,a0621,0708</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israelis Keep Tight Control, Ban PLO Youth Wing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 1st graf with two grafs. Pick up 2d graf pvs:
Stone-throwing... Edits 10th graf pvs bgng: Also in Ramallah... to
conform</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOCELYN NOVECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers raided a Ramallah hospital
Saturday in search of Arab protesters and the government banned a
PLO youth group in the occupied territories, where violent
Palestinian demonstrations subsided.
   Also in Ramallah Israeli troops briefly detained four foreign
television crews.
   Stone-throwing youths confronted Israeli troops in scattered
clashes in the occupied territories, but no shootings were
reported. Hospital officials in the Gaza Strip said nine
Palestinians were admitted with beating injuries.
   A statement Saturday by the Defense Ministry said authorities
had outlawed Shabiba, the youth group of Yasser Arafat's Fatah wing
of the Palestine Liberation Organization with thousands of members
throughout the territories.
   ``Given its continuous involvement in the disruption of Israel's
law and order in the area, and since it is an inseparable part of
the PLO, it was declared illegal ... Members will be subject to
arrest and trial,'' the statement said.
   An army spokesman said troops moved into the Ramallah hospital
in the early morning ``to remove undesirable elements from the
premises and return control of the hospital to the doctors and
nurses.''
   The hospital, near the center of the West Bank city 10 miles
north of Jerusalem, has become a gathering place for young Arab
protesters. They have raised the outlawed Palestinian flag on its
roof, hurled stones at soldiers, and taken refuge in the hospital's
corridors.
   The army spokesman said troops removed ``those individuals who
disturbed the functioning of the hospital'' and retreated after
several hours, maintaining a guard at the entrance.
   However, the Arab-owned Palestine Press Service said soldiers
burst into the hospital, checking identification papers and
assaulting staff members. The agency said troops stationed at the
entrance also prevented relatives from visiting patients.
   The agency said doctors and nurses at the hospital carried out a
sit-in strike against the army action later Saturday.
   The foreign television crews detained in Ramallah included teams
from America's CBS and Cable News Network who the military said
defied an order to leave the area.
   Army commanders are empowered to close off areas under their
control at will.
   Eli Fastman, a cameraman for the London-based Visnews, said the
four two-man crews entered Ramallah after they were presented with
a closure order. They stayed there ``to challenge this crazy system
of closing us out of the territories,'' Fastman said.
   Fastman said the crews, which also included a team from the
London-based Worldwide Television News, were taken to a military
police station in Ramallah where they ``discussed the situation
with army officials.'' The army filed no charges and released the
crews an hour later, he said.
   The Palestine Press Service said a free-lance reporter working
for the New York daily newspaper Newsday, Nancie Katz, was also
briefly detained by troops near the city of Nablus for violating a
closure order.
   The army also arrested an Arab journalist in the West Bank town
of Tulkarm. The journalist, Adnan Damiri, works for the Palestine
Press Service, the agency and Israel radio said.
   Damiri was arrested during the night in connection with security
offenses, the agency said. He has already served 6{ years in prison
for security offenses.
   An army spokesman said he had no information on the arrest.
Israel radio said it was one of several during the night in Tulkarm.
   Also in Tulkarm, the army distributed leaflets calling on Arab
residents to refrain from protests, Israel radio said. The radio
quoted the leaflets, also distributed in the town of Qalqilya, as
telling inhabitants they would only hurt themselves by engaging in
disturbances.
   In the Gaza Strip, a curfew remained in force on the Shati
refugee camp and a section of Gaza City after sustained protests
there.
   Widespread disturbances began Dec. 8 in the West Bank and Gaza,
where 1.5 million Palestinians live. Israeli captured the
territories in the 1967 Middle East war.
   The United Nations reports that 102 Palestinians have died in
the latest unrest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
