<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Honduras-Glance     03-19 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduras-Glance,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honduras-Nicaragua At-a-Glance</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   With AM-Honduras Bjt
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a summary of the developments Saturday involving
Nicaragua, Honduras and the United States:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>HONDURAS:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Honduras ordered several more battalions of soldiers to
reinforce its 2,000 troops along the border with Nicaragua. The
troops are trying to oust Nicaraguan soldiers who entered Honduran
territory. President Jose Azcona Hoyo said he wouldn't hesitate to
seek more U.S. help.
   But a few hours after Azcona spoke, the Honduran armed forces
announced the Nicaraguans were withdrawing. Honduran officials said
the Sandinista troops had crossed the border last week in pursuit
of U.S.-backed Nicaraguan rebels.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>UNITED STATES:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan called for renewed aid for the rebels, known as
Contras. His administration sent 3,200 American soldiers to
Honduras last week. The Defense Department said the U.S. troops
probably will be in Central America for about 10 days.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NICARAGUA:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega said he is asking the International
Court of Justice in The Hague for an injunction preventing military
activities that could ``raise tension'' between Honduras and
Nicaragua. The tribunal, also known as the World Court, has no
power unless both sides of a dispute agree to its jurisdiction.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CONTRAS:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Nicaragua's rebels said they are willing to hold cease-fire
talks as scheduled this week with the Sandinista government,
despite threatening earlier to boycott them unless Nicaraguan
troops withdrew from Honduras. A Contra spokesman, Carlos Hurtado,
said the rebels were ready for Monday's talks in the southern town
of Sapoa near the Costa Rican border.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SOVIETS:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The official Tass news agency accused the United States of using
military threats to impose its will on Nicaragua and spoil peace
efforts in Central America.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>UNITED NATIONS:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A team of U.N. observers will visit Nicaragua as soon as
possible to investigate the border conflict with Honduras.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar decided to send the team
at Nicaragua's request. The group will include one political
officer from U.N. headquarters and an undecided number of military
observers, U.N. spokesman Mahbub Ahmad said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MEXICO:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Mexico said the crisis in Panama and at the Honduras-Nicaragua
border calls for ``great prudence and the need to use political
means to achieve a negotiated peace.'' Foreign Minister Bernardo
Sepulveda said Mexico opposes outside military intervention in the
region.
</TEXT>
