<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru a0588 03-19 0801</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0588,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US To Complain About Soviet Aid To Nicaragua, But Keep Summit On
Track</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 9th graf pvs bgng, `He sought,' with 3 grafs to UPDATE
with TASS comment; PICKS UP 10th graf pvs bgng, `Another State'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration will complain to
Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze this week about his
country's military aid to Nicaragua, but won't let the issue
disturb preparations for a superpower summit, officials said.
   Shevardnadze, due to arrive Sunday afternoon, will hold three
days of talks starting Monday with Secretary of State George P.
Shultz. Lunch at the White House with President Reagan is
tentatively scheduled for Wednesday.
   The aim is to clear the way _ especially on arms control _ for a
Reagan trip to Moscow in May or June to sign another U.S.-Soviet
disarmament agreement.
   The Soviet foreign minister will come at a time of preoccupation
in the capital with events in Honduras, where 3,200 U.S. troops
were sent after Nicaragua moved against guerrillas using
sanctuaries on Honduran territory.
   The Soviet Union supplies the Nicaraguan forces.
   In 1986, Moscow and its allies gave Nicaragua $500 million in
economic assistance and $600 million in military aid, including
helicopter gun ships, transport aircraft and more than 1,200
vehicles for probable military use, according to the Pentagon's
most recent report on Soviet military power.
   That aid, compared with what the United States sends to the
resistance and to U.S. client states in the region, ``makes us look
like paupers,'' State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman said
Friday.
   He called the Soviet effort ``massive'' and said the issue would
be raised during the talks with Shevardnadze.
   Shevardnadze may carry complaints of his own.
   The official Soviet news agency accused the U.S. government
Saturday of sending troops to Honduras to destroy a Central
American peace plan signed in Guatemala last summer. Tass said the
administration's support for the guerrillas in Nicaragua aids
terrorism.
   Redman sought to dispel the view that the issue would dominate
the talks, saying ``the Soviets know how we feel.''
   Another State Department official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said arms control, the situation in Afghanistan and
human rights in the Soviet Union were equally important topcs for
the talks.
   Shultz is expected to press Shevardnadze to clarify Soviet plans
for the withdrawal of its estimated 115,000 troops from Afghanistan.
   A Soviet spokesman said last week that even if United
Nations-sponsored negotiations in Geneva fail to produce a
political settlement in Afghanistan the Soviet Union would withdraw
its troops anyway.
   This appeared to be a change in Soviet emphasis, away from the
need for a Geneva accord and toward a unilateral pullout.
   ``The Soviets didn't need the Geneva accords to invade
Afghanistan so they certainly don't need the Geneva accords to
leave Afghanistan,'' Redman said. Nevertheless, he added, ``We do
believe it would be preferable if there were an agreed-to, orderly
basis for that withdrawal. We think that's something that would be
in the interest of all parties, including the Soviets.''
   The chief U.S. desire is an end not just to Soviet presence but
to Moscow's financial and military support to the Afghan government
_ which the State Department has labelled a mere ``faction'' among
political groups in the country.
   If the Soviets continue helping the Afghan government after a
troop pullout, the United States will continue its support to
resistance forces fighting the Kabul regime for almost a decade,
the State Department said.
   Shultz and Shevardnadze's last meeting, in Moscow in February,
was dominated by discussion of arms control, notably efforts to
reach an agreement on up to 50 percent cuts in long-range nuclear
missiles and bombers carrying atomic weapons.
   Negotiators have been trying to devise a pact in time for
signing at a summit.
   One of the most difficult-to-achieve ingredients of the arms
pact is a verification system that insures the destruction of the
weapons and satisfies both sides that armaments outlawed by the
pact are not subsequently deployed.
   Since February, each side has completed its drafts of how the
verification system should work and the negotiators are now trying
to narrow the differences in the documents.
   On Tuesday, Shevardnadze is scheduled to join Shultz in a
ribbon-cutting ceremony opening the U.S. end of
Washington-to-Moscow communication links known as ``risk reduction
centers.''
   The computer and telefax filled center, on the 7th floor of the
State Department, and a comparable communications post in Moscow,
will be used to help the two sides keep in touch at a minute's
notice if problems arise with treaties to limit weapons, incidents
at sea and the danger of accidental war.
   Center managers tested the high-speed communications link last
week by exchanging maps of the Moscow and Washington subway systems
by high-speed data transmitters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
