<DOCNO> AP880319-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 1823EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Fashion     03-19 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fashion,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dashing Trousers Shown By Montana, Luxury By Lacroix</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Claude Montana's winter ready-to-wear collection of
long trousers and Christian Lacroix's display Saturday of short
skirts showed that the two lengths can live in harmony.
   Montana's show featured long pants along with some skirts, tops
cinched at the waist and often with huge funnel collars.
   The designer has abandoned his big shoulders in favor of the
raised or large sloped collars and shoulder wraps.
   He has honed down the sharp silhouette to simplicity in great
fabrics and colors _ lots of caramels and a few pastels or black in
silk gabardines, ribbed jerseys, leather and shorn mink.
   For evening, he concentrated on ways to make the black suit
different. His black suits had satin scroll details over collars,
lapels and jacket hems, and some elegant swirled stitch patterns,
updating the tuxedo or smoking suit.
   Christian Lacroix's collection featured short coats with rounded
shapes in hot-colored mohair with fichu wrapped collars.
   From lean suit shapes to the familiar bell-shaped short skirts
or some bloomer-dresses for evening, Lacroix surprised viewers with
new velvets printed like Persian rugs or prints with small leaf
motifs.
   Givenchy also showed acres of luxury clothes, mainly shorter
lengths for daytime, just skimming the knee or slightly above.
   His man-tailored suits and waist-fitted suits with slightly full
skirts displayed elegance. In shades of raspberry or bright blues
or green, the tweeds are outstanding, as are some of the leather
cardigan jackets.
   The knit outfits were in bright colors or tan and beige,
sometimes with a wide-wrapped top.
   Guy Paulin was another designer who went in for simplicity. His
models displayed short suits with clinging stretch black skirts
topped by bordeaux and olive long piped jackets.
   Cable-knit or jersey trouser suits were best with boleros in
shades of khaki and caramel, or in pastel boucle knits.
   Long iridescent taffeta raincoats with elasticized waists over
full skirts or fitted coat-dresses in vermilion or emerald added a
lively touch to the sober gathering of winter clothes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880319-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 1839EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Saudi-Missiles     03-19 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Saudi-Missiles,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Saudi Arabia Says Missiles Would Be Used for Defensive Purposes
Only</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Saudi Arabian government said Saturday the
intermediate-range missiles it had acquired from the Chinese would
be used for defensive purposes to protect its territory and Islam's
holiest shrines.
   The Saudi information office, in a statement to the official
Saudi Press Agency, quoted an unidentified official as saying that
any nation has a legitimate right to defend itself by any means it
deems necessary but that Saudi Arabia would not arm the missiles
with nuclear warheads.
   The official said newspaper reports about the ``nuclear capacity
of these missiles does not lend itself to truth and is utterly
negated by the kingdom, as the steadfast and well-known policy of
the kingdom is based on the permanent efforts to make the Middle
East region avoid the dangers of the nuclear arms race and to
remain free from all its forms.''
   The State Department confirmed Friday that Saudi Arabia had
acquired Chinese missiles with a range of 2,200 miles, capable of
hitting all areas of the Middle East, including Israel.
   The missiles were described as Chinese CSS-2 rockets, similar to
those used in China's limited space program in the early 1970s and
capable of being outfitted with nuclear warheads.
   ``It is not a new or strange tendency that Saudi Arabia seeks to
secure its requirements of weapons for its armed forces from
different sources, in accordance with its defense needs and in
conformity with the prevalent circumstances in the region,'' the
statement said.
   ``This principle is based on its defense policy aimed at
bolstoring its capabilities, for the sake of the legitimate defense
of its territory and Holy Shrines, particularly in view of the
unstable situation and existing conflicts in the Middle East
region,'' the statement said.
   The official said Saudi Arabia is responsible for protecting the
holy shrines of Mecca, the birthplace of Prophet Mohammed, and
Medina, site of Mohammed's tomb, which are located in a western
region known as Hijaz.
   On the other hand, the official said the kingdom's defense
policy ``has never demonstrated any aggressive tendency. Its policy
was, and still is, based on keenness to avail security and prevail
peace throughout the region.''
   Therefore, the official said, any program ``aimed at fostering
its defense capabilities and protecting its legitimate interests is
not a menace to peace. On the contrary, the more its defense
capabilities are reinforced, the more it helps in propagating peace
in the region.
   ``On the basis of this principle, Saudi Arabia acquired this
Chinese-made medium-range surface-to-surface missile system,'' the
official said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
