<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Soviet-Grain     03-19 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Soviet-Grain,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US and Soviet Negotiators Complete First Round of Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and the Soviet Union on
Saturday completed the first round of negotiations by the two
countries on a new long-term grain agreement.
   Deputy Trade Representative Alan F. Holmer, U.S. team leader in
the negotiations, called the seven-hour discussion ``frank and
amicable with both sides presenting their respective point of
view.''
   ``No deadline has been set for completion of the agreement,''
Holmer said in a statement. ``However, both countries would like to
come to mutual terms over the next several months.''
   The current five-year agreement, which expires Sept. 30, calls
on Moscow to buy at least 9 million tons of grain annually and
specifies that the purchase include a minimum of 4 million tons
each of wheat and corn. The Soviets have the option of buying the
remaining 1 million tons as wheat, corn or soybeans, with every ton
of beans counting as two tons of grain _ up to a maximum of 1
million tons of grain equivalent.
</TEXT>
