<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-19 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Winter Goes Out With A Bang, Not A Whimper, in North-Central U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The last full day of winter made itself felt with a blast of
cold arctic air across the north-central United States on Saturday,
plunging afternoon temperatures into the teens in northern
Minnesota and Upper Michigan.
   Spring begins at 4:39 a.m. EST Sunday.
   Daytime temperatures remained below freezing from the northeast
half of North Dakota through much of the Great Lakes to New
England. Strong northerly winds ushering the cold air into the
north-central United States were expected to produce squalls and
heavy snow in parts of Ohio and Pennsylvania on Saturday night.
   Heavy snow warnings were issued for northeastern Ohio and
northwestern Pennsylvania, where 6 to 10 inches of snow was
expected.
   It was also unseasonably cool in parts of Texas, where morning
temperatures dipped into the 20s and 30s. Several cities set
low-temperature records for the date, including El Paso with 22
degrees; Del Rio, 29; Corpus Christi, 30; and Brownsville, 38.
   The upper Midwest and Northeast had scattered snow showers,
while the Carolinas and the mid-Atlantic Coast region had sporadic
light rain. Sunny skies prevailed across the south-central and
southwestern United States.
   A high wind warning was issued for southeastern Wyoming on
Saturday. Gusts of up to 52 mph were clocked at Cheyenne.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 16
degrees at Marquette, Mich., to 87 in San Diego, Calif. The
early-morning low for the nation was 3 degrees below zero at
Gunnison, Colo.
   Sunday's forecast called for scattered snow from the Great Lakes
and upper Ohio Valley to New England, with rain in the Pacific
Northwest, especially in western Washington state and northwestern
Oregon. Fair to partly sunny skies should prevail across the rest
of the nation.
   Afternoon highs should remain below 40 degrees from eastern
North Dakota through the Great Lakes region and Ohio Valley to New
Jersey and New England, with highs in the 20s and upper teens from
Minnesota across the Great Lakes to northern New England. Highs
should reach into the 70s from the southern Plains through southern
Arizona to California, climbing into the 80s in western Texas and
the desert Southwest. Highs in the 40s, 50s and 60s were forecast
for most of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
