<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HonduranBorder     03-19 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduran Border,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wide, Shallow Stream Forms Border in Conflict Area</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Honduras, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Separating Honduras and Nicaragua
where Sandinista troops entered Honduran territory to attack bases
of U.S.-backed Nicaraguan rebels is the the Coco River, a wide,
shallow stream.
   But the Coco is a confusing border, winding through a maze of
thick jungle and mountains, merging with enough tributaries to make
one uncertain of the side of the frontier he's on.
   The thrust of the Nicaraguan offensive has been in the area
around San Andres de Bocay, a border town 170 miles northeast of
Managua where the Bocay River flows from Nicaragua's Jinotega
province into the Coco.
   North of the Coco at that point is a series of small Honduran
mountain ranges and a broad plateau. Flat and parched during the
current dry season, it resembles parts of the American southwest.
   There are narrow valleys that provide relatively secure
locations for the bases of the rebels, known as Contras.
   South of the Coco, in Nicaragua, the swift-running Bocay tumbles
down a long series of rapids through the mountains of Jinotega
province and cuts through a deep valley named after it in its fall
to the low-lying Coco.
   Where the two join at the border, they look much alike, both now
in the six-month dry season that began in November and in the rainy
season when they carry enormous amounts of water.
   The Bocay Valley, extending from the Honduran border far into
Jinotega, has long been a strategic supply route for the Contras.
   Over the years, the jungled hills that rise hundreds of feet on
both sides have been laced with an narrow trails, first made by
local farmers and more recently by the Contras.
   From the Honduran border, the Contras send supplies down the
valley into Nicaragua in dugout canoes and other boats or on the
backs of mules and men who walk the jungle trails.
   On the Honduran side of the Coco where it is met by the Bocay a
small airstrip extends perilously along a bluff overlooking the
water. Supplies are landed or parachuted there by light planes that
bring them from other Contra bases inside Honduras.
   The area is just 43 miles northwest of Bonanza, a Nicaraguan
mining district. But Bonanza is too isolated and difficult to
defend for the Sandinistas to station troops there permanently.
   Instead, the Sandinistas have driven the Contras out of the
Bocay Valley several times as they did this month and have attacked
their bases inside Honduras.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
