<HEAD>Woman Who Claims to Be `Billie Jean' Sentenced To Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who claims she inspired Michael
Jackson's 1983 hit ``Billie Jean'' was sentenced to 303 days in
jail for violating a probation order to stay away from the pop
singer's home.
   Lavon A. Muhammad, 40, who was twice previously convicted of
trespassing on Jackson's estate and who is described as suffering
from delusions, was found guilty Friday of violating the terms of
probation for the 1986 convictions, which required her to remain a
mile away.
   Municipal Court Judge Michael J. Farrell, however, dismissed
several misdemeanor charges against Ms. Muhammad, including
trespassing and violating a court order.
   She was arrested at 3 a.m. Feb. 12 in Jackson's back yard after
scaling a 5-foot wall.
   Both prosecutors and her defense attorney say she suffers from
delusions and believes she is engaged to marry Jackson. She also
claims the superstar is the father of her 6-year-old twins.
   Jackson, 29, denies any involvement with Ms. Muhammad.
   In 1986, he obtained a four-year restraining order to keep the
woman away, said Deputy City Attorney David S. Kestenbaum.
   Kestenbaum said that Ms. Muhammad, despite her claims, was not
the inspiration for the song ``Billie Jean,'' which includes such
lyrics as, ``Billie Jean is not my lover'' and ``The kid is not my
son.''
