<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AT&T-Supremacists 2ndLd-Writethru a0652 03-19 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AT&T-Supremacists, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0652,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White Supremacist Group Gets Resolution on AT&T Ballot
^Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to add date of annual meeting.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A white supremacist group has forced
AT&T into asking shareholders to vote on ending the telephone
company's minority hiring program on the grounds that blacks are
intellectually inferior.
   The racist National Alliance offered the resolution on the
ballot for AT&T's annual shareholders' meeting in Denver, set for
April 20. The Securities and Exchange Commission ruled that it must
appear, with minor changes in wording, despite the company's
objections.
   AT&T's management has recommended that shareholders vote against
the proposal.
   ``AT&T has had a long-term commitment to the advancement of
women and minorities,'' said AT&T spokesman Herb Linnen in
Washington. ``It's ludicrous in this day and age to have it
suggested that women and minorities not be given their rightful
place based on their achievements in the workplace.''
   He said AT&T, the nation's largest long-distance telephone
company, has an ``outstanding record to point to (on affirmative
action), one which we're proud of and we intend to continue our
firm commitment in this area.''
   The National Alliance is a Washington, D.C.-based organization
that promotes the study of Adolf Hitler's writings.
   Its leader, William Pierce, also heads the white supremacist
Cosmotheist Church, with headquarters in Pocahontas County, W.Va.
He is the author of ``The Turner Diaries,'' a fictional account of
an all-out race war ending in the domination of a worldwide
Hitler-inspired regime.
   The National Alliance bought 100 shares of AT&T in 1986, and
Pierce told the Charleston Daily Mail that the group's members have
been working on the AT&T campaign for a year and a half.
   In a statement sent to shareholders, the National Alliance
claimed that ``only 1.1 percent'' of blacks possess an IQ of 114 or
above _ a ``desirable'' figure for most AT&T employees.
   ``We believe that to ignore data such as this in employment
practices sacrifices the essential long-term benefits of personnel
quality, for the short-term approval of pressure groups,'' the
statement said.
   The resolution says minority hiring has had ``negative effects''
on morale among white AT&T employees who could ``feel discouraged
and ignored when they notice that the company is actively seeking
to advance non-whites.''
   AT&T has disputed the group's allegations that its minority
hiring program has hurt morale.
   Ironically, AT&T management also has recommended a vote against
another proposal from a New Jersey shareholder who believes there
aren't enough women and minorities in executive positions.
   That proposal asks AT&T to reformulate affirmative-action
programs ``to ensure that racial minorities and women are not
under-utilized in upper-middle and executive levels of corporate
leadership.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
