<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru Rebels,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas attack state-owned coal mine, take two hostages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUANCAYO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Left-wing guerrillas attacked a
state-owned coal mine, stole dynamite, blew up equipment and took
two hostages with them as they fled, police reported Saturday.
   They said an estimated 100 guerrillas of the pro-Cuban Tupac
Amaru Revolutionary Movement were involved in the pre-dawn raid
Friday on the Cachi mine 30 miles west of this provincial capital.
   Police and army units are searching for the rebel band and the
two miners taken captive in the mountainous area about 130 miles
east of Lima.
   Authorities reported no one was injured in the attack. No
estimate of damage at the mine was given.
   The Tupac Amaru front emerged in 1984 as an urban guerrilla
group but in the past year it has extended its attacks to include a
few rural zones.
   It is considered less violent than Peru's largest guerrilla
organization, the Maoist Shining Path movement that has been active
for eight years. Government officials say more than 10,000 people
have been killed in violence related to the Shining Path.
</TEXT>
