<HEAD>`Roxanne' and `Moonstruck' Draw Writers Guild Top Awards</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steve Martin's screenwriting for
the movie ``Roxanne'' and John Patrick Shanley's work on the
``Moonstruck'' script won top honors at the annual Writers Guild of
America Awards.
   CBS was the big television winner during the 40th annual awards
presentation late Friday at the Beverly Hilton Hotel, taking top
honors in seven categories, including best TV spot news script.
   NBC and ABC each took four awards while the Public Broadcasting
Service had three and Home Box Office won one. Three of NBC's
awards came via a three-way tie in one category, best comedy
episode.
   The awards were presented on the 11th day of the 9,000-member
guild's strike against the Alliance of Motion Picture and
Television Producers, and references to the strike flavored the
evening, despite guild Executive Director Brian Walton's
admonition, ``This is a night to celebrate writers and writing.''
   Martin was honored for best screenplay based on material from
another medium.
   The comedian, who also starred in ``Roxanne'' with Daryl Hannah,
wrote the script for the summer comedy hit which was adapted from
Edmund Rostand's ``Cyrano de Bergerac,'' a story about a man with
an unattractive nose who uses well-chosen words to woo his lady.
   Shanley was honored for best original screenwriting on
``Moonstruck,'' which is nominated for six Academy Awards and stars
Cher as a Brooklyn Italian widow who finds herself engaged to one
man but in love with his brother.
   Broadcasting winners were:
</TEXT>
