<1ST_LINE>d a AM-MultipleTransplant     03-19 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Multiple Transplant,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Michigan Men Donate $14,000 To Five-Organ Recipient</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Michigan schoolteacher and a retiree
together raised $14,000 to help cover the medical expenses of a
toddler who's the longest survivor of a five-organ transplant.
   Moses Rutland, 71, a retired butcher, and John Ribner, 49, an
eighth-grade teacher, both of Flint, Mich., said contributors
ranged from the city's mayor to a child who gave $34 in pennies.
   The money was donated Saturday for Tabatha Foster, 3, of
Madisonville, Ky., who is recuperating from a five-organ transplant
she underwent Nov. 1 at Children's Hospital of Pittsburgh.
   She received a new liver, pancreas, small intestine and parts of
a stomach and colon during the experimental operation, which is not
covered by her parents' insurance. She suffered from short gut
syndrome, a congenital defect, and she would have died without the
transplant, according to doctors.
   Rutland said he began collecting money for Tabatha last November.
   ``It seemed like somebody in the world should try to help this
family,'' he said.
   Ribner later organized a two-week, $1,400 drive at Whittier
Middle School in Flint.
   ``I always stress to my students to help their community, to not
always take for yourself,'' he said.
   Joe Williams, a Pittsburgh attorney representing Tabatha and her
parents, Roy and Sandra Foster, said the $14,000 gift is the
largest one so far. It brings total contributions to $320,000,
leaving about $225,000 in unpaid bills.
</TEXT>
