<DOCNO> AP880319-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 2045EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WorldBridge     03-19 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-World Bridge,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in Three Countries Playing Same Bridge Game</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contract bridge players in France, Italy
and the United States sat down Saturday to play one another in a
computer-linked game.
   A computer dealt 32 bridge hands to 80 players in Milan, Italy;
80 in Paris; 100 in Houston, Texas; and 244 playing in Buffalo at
the North American Bridge Championships, sanctioned by the American
Contract Bridge League. Each table of four players in each city got
the same cards for each hand.
   The system, first demonstrated in Buffalo on Friday, dealt the
cards in trays in one city while dealing identical bridge hands in
the other cities.
   Dubbed ``Bridging the World,'' the international game was
described by Sherri Rosen of the bridge league as the first world
competition with computer-generated bridge hands and instant
scoring.
   ``It will give players here in Buffalo a chance to see how they
can compete against people in other parts of the world,'' she said.
   The scoring, she explained, was to be done in Paris and the
results transmitted to Buffalo.
   The Buffalo players also were competing among themselves in the
men's and women's pairs finals of the spring championships. At the
same time they were competing in the international game against
players in the other three cities.
   ``They came to Buffalo expecting to be in the men's and women's
pairs, but didn't expect to play an intercontinental match,'' said
Ms. Rosen.
   The 10-day spring championships, one of three major tournaments
that the American Contract Bridge League runs each year, have
attracted about 5,000 bridge players to Buffalo.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
