<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Kansas-Democrats 7thLd-Writethru a0670 03-19 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kansas-Democrats, 7th Ld-Writethru, a0670,590</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: TOP 12 grafs new with UPDATED Kansas results; change in
caucus and delegate numbers due to no-shows in two counties; picks
up 11th graf pvs, bgng, `Dukakis, who.'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LEW FERGUSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis won the
Kansas Democratic caucuses Saturday, fending off the urban strength
of Jesse Jackson who finished a surprising second.
   With 115 caucuses reporting, Dukakis had garnered 278 local
delegates for 36 percent, Jackson had 235 delegates for 31 percent
and Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. 125 for 16 percent. Another 114
delegates, or 15 percent, were elected in uncommitted status.
   Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt got only 12 delegates and
Illinois Sen. Paul Simon failed to pick up a single delegate.
Gephardt chose not to campaign in Kansas, spending his time instead
in Michigan ahead of its caucus on Saturday.
   No Democrats turned out in Greeley and Wichita counties in far
western Kansas, reducing the number of caucus sites from 117 to 115
and the number of local delegates elected from 768 to 764.
   ``It's terrific,'' Dukakis said at the Jefferson-Jackson dinner
in Detroit. ``We've had a major victory in Kansas and feel good
about it. Now we're on to Michigan and here we are.''
   The Massachusetts governor, asked about the significance of
winning in Kansas, said, ``I think it's the first farm and
agriculture state that I've won and won decisively. I think that's
a very good sign for the future.''
   Gephardt, speaking at the same Detroit dinner, said he wasn't
really concerned about Kansas.
   ``We really didn't mount much of an effort there,'' Gephardt
said. ``Our focus really has been on Michigan over the last week
and a half or two weeks.... I'm concerned about doing well Michigan
and I think we will.''
   Jackson beat Dukakis in Topeka and Kansas City, and held him to
a virtual draw in Wichita. Dukakis won in populous Johnson County,
which is suburban Kansas City.
   Dukakis won 42 delegates in Johnson County to 20 for Jackson and
19 for Gore, and Sedgwick County, which includes Wichita, with 44
delegates to 40 for Jackson and 31 for Gore.
   Jackson shocked most observers by winning Shawnee County, which
includes Topeka, with 32 delegates to Dukakis' 14 and Gore's four,
and claimed Wyandotte County, which includes Kansas City, as
expected, with 44 delegates to 13 for Dukakis and none for Gore.
   Twenty-six delegates were elected as uncommitted in the four
metropolitan counties. Gephardt got four of his delegates in
Johnson County, which borders Missouri, but none in any of the
other three big counties.
   Dukakis, who had been organized in Kansas far longer than any of
the other contenders, had been expected to do well. His state
chairman, Paul Feleciano of Wichita, had predicted Dukakis
eventually would claim between 20 and 25 of the Kansas national
delegates.
   The first larger county to report was Reno, just west of Wichita.
   Jackson, who didn't win any local delegates in Reno County four
years ago, got 75 votes from the 285 Democrats attending. Another
88 voted for Dukakis, 79 for Gore and 43 for Gephardt.
   Democrats attended 115 local caucuses, electing 764 delegates to
congressional district conventions on April 23 at which 26 of
Kansas' 43 delegates to the national convention will be picked.
Four state party officials are automatic delegates and the final 13
will be named on May 14 by the state committee.
</TEXT>
