<2ND_LINE>AM-Four Killed, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0645,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Dead In Shooting; Suspect Charged, Ordered Tested</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to recast, clarifying that shootings
occurred in same building where parents lived but not same
apartment; and to UPDATE with suspect transferred back to county
jail. Picks up 6th graf pvs, `Authorities had...'. SUBS 10th graf,
`One investigator...', to add that bodies found in upstairs
apartment.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FRANCIS X. QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGOR, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man shot to death four people, including
his brother and a pregnant woman, for playing a stereo too loud,
police said.
   Earl Losier Jr., 32, of Bangor was arrested at his parents'
apartment, in the building where the shootings occurred, and was
later charged in District Court with murdering his 26-year-old
brother, Stephen, authorities said.
   More charges were expected to be brought in connection with the
other slayings, said Fernand LaRochelle, chief of the Maine
attorney general's criminal division.
   Police identified the other victims as Peter Prendergast, 26, of
Brewer; Michael Prendergast, 31, of Bangor; and Sharon Prendergast,
23, of Bangor. Preliminary autopsy findings indicated that Ms.
Prendergast was pregnant, authorities said.
   Losier, who entered no plea to the charge, was ordered held
without bail and taken to the Augusta Mental Health Institute for a
psychological examination. He was transferred Saturday evening to
the Penobscot County Jail in Bangor.
   Authorities had not determined how the Prendergasts were related
and what their relationship to the suspect was, said police Lt. Don
O'Halloran.
   Bangor police Detective Roy E. McKinney said in an affidavit
filed in court that Losier told another policeman that he shot the
four ``because he was taking cough syrup and because they were
playing the stereo too loud.''
   O'Halloran also said that it appears Losier was upset about
noise ``but we really don't know ... why it escalated so rapidly.''
   In his affidavit, McKinney told the court that two policemen
were sent to the building and were told of a shooting by the
defendant's mother, Carol Losier.
   One investigator went to an upstairs apartment and found four
people with gunshot wounds, McKinney testified. A .45-caliber
semi-automatic handgun was seized at the scene, police said.
   According to Jeffrey Hjelm, an assistant attorney general
assigned to the case, two of the victims were taken to local
hospitals for treatment but did not survive.
   Hjelm would not elaborate on the circumstances of the shootings.
He said the case would probably be taken before a county grand jury.
</TEXT>
