<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SupremacistMarch     03-19 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Supremacist March,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White Supremacists March to Protest Black Boycott in Mississippi
Town</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NATCHEZ, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A handful of white supremacists led a
peaceful march and rally Saturday to protest a three-month black
boycott of white-owned businesses, while some 300 blacks stood
silently on the sidelines.
   White supremacist Richard Barrett and about eight supporters
gathered on the steps of the Adams County Courthouse after a short
downtown march.
   Barrett, of Jackson, and his followers marched despite efforts
by Natchez officials to prevent it.
   Last month, the Board of Aldermen passed a parade ordinance that
stipulated a 30-day waiting period. Barrett said he notified the
city of his intent to march before the ordinance was passed and
filed for a temporary restraining order in U.S. District Court.
   City officials agreed out of court to grant Barrett the permit.
   ``We come to you in the name of freedom,'' Barrett told the
group, which included about 100 white onlookers. ``Those of you who
rob a merchant of his trade are guilty of breaking the law, `Thou
shalt not steal.'''
   Black residents started the boycott against white-owned business
after charging that the school system was discriminatory against
black students and educators.
   Natchez-Adams County Public School Superintendent Claude Porter
recently resigned after weeks of pressure from boycotters. One of
the signs carried by the white supremacists read ``Back Porter.''
   Some of the boycott organizers, including state Rep. Barney
Schoby, Natchez Alderman George Hardin and Adams County Supervisor
Phillip West, flanked Barrett and his followers on the courthouse
steps, but remained silent.
   Blacks carried signs that read ``We will be here when you're
gone,'' and ``We've paid our dues.''
   Natchez Police Chief Ken Farily said 40 police officers in riot
gear stood by during the parade and rally.
  
</TEXT>
