<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Noriega-Probe     03-19 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Noriega-Probe,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carter Administration Reportedly Stalled Noriega Indictment in
1980</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega
might have been indicted in 1980 for illegal arms purchases but the
Carter administration did not want to upset the delicate
relationship it had with Panama at the time, The Washington Post
said in Sunday's editions.
   ``We had evidence to indict him for conspiracy,'' David Kimbler,
a former agent with the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms who
was one of the key investigators, told the Post. ``But ... the
Justice Department didn't want it.''
   The case stayed alive for several years, but Noriega was not
indicted, the newspaper said. Separate charges against several of
Noriega's alleged co-conspirators were filed in 1979 and dropped
because of a technical flaw. Those charges also were not pursued.
   ``The State Department didn't want to see this case go to
trial,'' David Goodhart, the lawyer for one defendant, told the
Post. ``Noriega had a rabbi.''
   The criminal case against Noriega, then head of Panama's
intelligence service, developed during a delicate time in
U.S.-Panamanian relations.
   In December 1979, Panama helped the Carter administration by
giving refuge to the deposed shah of Iran.
   Six weeks later, on Jan. 31, 1980, U.S. Attorney Jack Eskenazi
of Miami wrote a letter to a senior Justice Department official
advising that U.S. Customs agents had sufficient evidence to indict
Noriega for the illegal export of $2 million in arms, the Post said.
   Eskenazi asked the Justice Department to decide how to proceed.
   The Post, which published a copy of the confidential letter,
quoted Eskenazi as saying: ``Unfortunately, those of us in law
enforcement in Miami find ourselves frequently attempting to
enforce the laws of the United States, but simultaneously being
caught between foreign policy considerations over which we have no
control (and often, no knowledge).''
   Officially, the Justice Department responded by asking for more
information. Unofficially, the department made clear that the State
Department did not want the case to go forward, the Post said.
   State Department officials who dealt with Panama at the time
told the Post they could not recall any effort to prosecute Noriega
on gun running. ``I really don't remember,'' said Brandon Grove,
who was deputy assistant secretary of state for inter-American
affairs at the time.
   Robert Pastor, President Jimmy Carter's National Security
Council staff member responsible for Latin America, expressed
surprise when told of the Eskenazi letter, according to the Post.
   ``It is incredible to me that anyone in the Carter
administration would have tried to prevent prosecution of any
Panamanian involved in arms trafficking or that anybody would have
blinked or ignored such information regarding Panamanians involved
in arms trafficking,'' Pastor told the Post.
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
