<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Swap     03-19 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Swap,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Detain Two Participants in Racial Exchange</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAMELODI, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black churchworker and a white
student staying at his home as part of a church-run interracial
exchange program were detained Friday by police, the program's
organizers said.
   The student was freed several hours later, but the black
remained in custody, organizers said.
   The white man ``was released because of his white skin, while
his host is still detained because of his black skin,'' said the
Rev. Nico Smith, a Dutch Reformed minister and an organizer of the
interdenominational program.
   Smith was the first white the government allowed to live in the
black township of Mamelodi, the main black township outside the
capital of Pretoria.
   Murray Hofmeyr, who is white, and Sandy Lebese, a black, were
picked up there early Friday, according to the Rev. Kevin Cochrane.
   Hofmeyr, 29, was among 170 whites who moved in Wednesday for
four days with black families in Mamelodi. In turn, 40 blacks were
sent to live with whites in Pretoria.
   Hofmeyr, a doctoral candidate in theology, was staying with
Lebese, a field worker with the Pretoria Council of Churches.
Lebese, 31, was imprisoned from 1977 to 1983 on a sabotage
conviction.
   Colleagues speculated that Lebese was detained because of his
membership in the Mamelodi Youth Organization, an anti-apartheid
community group. Five other group members were detained Friday,
according to Anthea Tasker, a spokeswoman for the exchange program.
   Police were asked about the detentions but had no immediate
comment.
   Participants in the exchange issued a statement expressing
``shock and horror'' at the police action: ``It is incomprehensible
to us that these two good Christian men could be detained at the
very time they were working toward real peace in our land. Such
action raises very serious questions about the true motives of the
security forces''
   One of the participants in the exchange, Nick Paton, is the
grandson of novelist Alan Paton. The younger Paton said police came
to the Mamelodi home he was visiting at 2:30 a.m. Friday, woke him
to ask what he was doing there, and left.
   On Thursday, Hofmeyr spoke enthusiastically of his first night
in a black township. He said he went disco-hopping while new-found
black friends bought his drinks.
   Lebese said at the time, ``A lot of whites don't even know if
it's legal for them to come to Mamelodi.
   ``They think we're a bunch of dangerous radicals,'' he added.
``This week everyone has a chance to talk in a relaxed
environment.''
   Most South African blacks know more about how whites live
because blacks often work at white homes and businesses. Whites
seldom venture into black townships.
   Henry Lederle, a white theology professor, said participating
whites are already committed to ending apartheid, the system of
racial segregation in South Africa.
   ``The whites still need this type of exposure,'' he added.
``It's one thing to say you want to end apartheid; it's another to
learn about the problems it creates.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
