<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 0703EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ArmyRadon     03-19 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Army Radon,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Will Test Its Buildings for Radon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army announced Friday it would follow the
lead of the Air Force and begin testing buildings on its bases for
the natural radioactive gas radon.
   ``The first structures to be tested will be day care centers,
hospitals, schools and living areas,'' the Army said in a statement.
   ``The next set of structures to be tested will be those having
24-hour operations such as operations centers, training areas and
research, development, test and evaluation facilities. Last to be
tested will be all other routinely inhabited structures.''
   ``All radon measurements will be completed by the end of fiscal
1991 (Sept. 30, 1991),'' the service said.
   Each building will be screened initially for 90 days, and any
structure showing a radon level greater than 20 picocuries per
liter of air will be scheduled for corrective action in six months
or less, the Army said.
   Ultimately, any structure showing a radon level of 4 picocuries
per liter or more will receive corrective sealing, the Army added.
   Radon is a colorless, odorless natural product of decaying
uranium in the soil. Medical research has indicated that exposure
to high levels of radon may increase the risk of lung cancer. The
Environmental Protection Agency's guideline for radon exposure is 4
picocuries per liter of air.
   The Air Force announced plans to begin testing buildings on its
bases around the world for radon last November. The Navy and Marine
Corps are said to be considering similar moves.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
