<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SugarExplosion     03-19 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sugar Explosion,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Burned in Explosion and Flash Fire at Sugar Refinery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MARIA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion and flash fire at a
sugar refinery burned at least seven workers Friday, three
critically, officials said.
   The blast caused heavy damage to the Union Sugar division of
Holly Sugar Corp. plant, said Charlie Johnson, a Santa Barbara
County Fire Department spokesman.
   Fire Capt. Jim Trask said that the blast was caused by sugar
dust but that investigators had yet to determine what ignited it.
   Johnson likened the accident to grain elevator explosions, in
which fine particles of wheat often are ignited by a spark. ``It
appears to be very similar to a dust explosion common in the
Midwest,'' Johnson said.
   Three workers were in critical condition at Marion Medical
Center and were transferred to the burn center at Sherman Oaks
Community Hospital, said Ethel Donati, a nursing supervisor at
Marion.
   Four victims were in satisfactory condition at Valley Community
Hospital, said nursing supervisor Maureen Shannon.
   The blast occurred on the second floor of a six-story brick
warehouse in a room where workers said different grades of sugar
are sorted. The fire was contained quickly, Johnson said.
   The plant, which produces beet sugar, is isolated from other
buildings about 5 miles outside this town 125 miles northwest of
Los Angeles.
   Fire investigators were joined by inspectors from the state
Occupational Safety and Health Administration, building inspectors
and county health officials. Holly Sugar Corp. has headquarters in
Colorado Springs, Colo.
</TEXT>
