<1ST_LINE>r w AM-EasternAirlines 1stLd-Writethru a0768 03-19 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern Airlines, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0768,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge To Announce Penalties Against Eastern Airlines on Monday</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 9th graf pvs bgng, `He isn't,' with 3 grafs to UPDATE
with reax from machinists' union president; PICKS UP 10th graf pvs
bgng, `But John'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines ``isn't above the law'' and
should be penalized for trying to sell its East Coast shuttle
operation in violation of a court order, the union for the
carrier's mechanics told a federal judge Friday.
   But U.S. District Judge John H. Pratt said he would not grant
the labor organization's request that he force Frank Lorenzo,
Eastern's chief executive, to appear before him to promise that he
would halt efforts to shed the shuttle.
   Pratt said at a hearing called to determine sanctions to be
levied against Eastern that he would announce the penalties Monday.
   ``We're not going to, at this juncture, order Mr. Lorenzo to
come in here and genuflect,'' Pratt told lawyers for the
International Association for Machinists and Aerospace Workers.
   The union also had asked Pratt to order Eastern to halt all
efforts to gain federal permission to sell the shuttle, restore
jobs to workers who retired after learning of the shuttle sale
proposal, and fine the carrier $20,000 per day for any future
violations of the judge's orders.
   On March 10, Pratt found the Miami-based carrier in contempt for
trying to sell its profitable shuttle service to its parent
company, Texas Air Corp., for $225 million. Lorenzo also heads
Texas Air.
   Pratt ruled that in trying to sell the shuttle, the financially
ailing Eastern was violating his July 2, 1987, injunction ordering
the airline to maintain the status quo of its contract with the
machinists.
   The union, which represents 12,000 employees, has argued that by
selling the shuttle to another company set up by Texas Air, the
labor group's bargaining power with Eastern would be weakened
seriously. The sale would have required the transfer of 6,000
Eastern employees to the new company.
   ``We believe that, as a result of the order, negotiations will
be normalized and we hope to reach agreement in a collective
bargaining process that will be both satisfactory to the company
and the union,'' said Charles E. Bryan, president of machinist's
union at Eastern.
   ``Judge Pratt was very straightforward and objective in his
enforcement'' of the law, Bryan said in a statement. ``He has
restored our confidence in the federal courts and provided justice
for all Eastern Airlines employees.''
   Joseph Guerrieri, Jr., lawyer for the machinists, said of
Lorenzo, ``He isn't above the law. Eastern Airlines isn't above the
law. I think he has to come to understand that.''
   But John J. Gallagher, the attorney representing Eastern, said
the airline was now complying with Pratt's orders and that there
was no reason to compel an appearance by Lorenzo. He said the
machinists have long had a hostile relationship with Eastern
executives, even before Lorenzo acquired the carrier.
   ``Now there's a new management so there's a new black hat,''
Gallagher said.
   Labor and management at Eastern have been battling for years.
Under Lorenzo, Eastern has tried a series of moves that the airline
says are designed to increase efficiency but the union has claimed
are efforts to break their power.
   The Eastern shuttle serves Washington, New York and Boston.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
