<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PuertoRico-Drugs     03-19 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Puerto Rico-Drugs,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indictments Accuse Seven of Belonging to Drug Ring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGLISA CAPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury indicted seven
people in Puerto Rico, New York and Florida on charges of belonging
to a drug ring that sent cocaine and heroin to Puerto Rico, the FBI
announced Friday.
   Three of the suspects were taken into custody in San Juan and a
fourth was arrested in New York, according to FBI spokesman Angel
Berlingeri.
   He said arrest warrants have been issued for two suspects in
Puerto Rico and one in Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
   All seven are charged in the indictments opened Friday with
distributing and selling cocaine and heroin, Berlingeri reported.
   He said more arrests are expected as a result of an
investigation that started in the late 1970s of drugs shipped from
New York and Florida to Puerto Rico for sale on this U.S.
commonwealth island.
   Authorities reported one suspect, Alberto Aviles Rodriguez,
appeared voluntarily before U.S. Magistrate Justo Arenas Friday
morning. They said Juan R. Berganzo Romero and Armando Serrano
Miranda were arrested in San Juan and taken into court in the
afternoon. Arenas ordered all three held without bail.
   The FBI said Guiseppe Tabbita was arrested in New York, but did
not elaborate, and that a man identified as Guiseppe Pellerito was
being sought in Fort Lauderdale.
   It said the others named in the indictment and being sought are
Puerto Rican residents Miguel Reyes Pantojas and Joaquin Beltran
Robles.
   The latest indictments came after Hector Rivera Martinez and 15
other people were arrested in San Juan on Dec. 7. The FBI claims
Rivera Martinez headed the ring.
   According to the FBI, the suspects sold heroin to undercover
agents in July and August 1987. It did not specify the amount of
heroin allegedly involved.
   Conviction is punishable by from 10 years to life in prison and
fines up to $4 million, according to authorities.
   The indictments alleges that Rivera Martinez was involved in
drug trafficking in Puerto Rico since the 1960s. It says he hired
Tabbita and Pellerito to send heroin and cocaine from New York and
Florida to Puerto Rico for processing and distribution, and that
Rivera Martinez engaged in money laundering in Puerto Rico.
   After Rivera Martinez was arrested, authorities confiscated
property valued at $1.5 million and a 16-foot boat.
</TEXT>
