<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Falwell-CivilRights 1stLd-Writethru a0792 03-19 0736</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Falwell-Civil Rights, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0792,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Civil Liberties, Church Groups Fight Falwell Attack on Civil
Rights Bill</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Inserts 2 grafs after 12th graf bgng: Warner said ... to
UPDATE with Cochran saying he will vote to sustain veto. Picks up
13th graf pvs bgng: The measure ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Civil liberties and religious organizations
announced plans Friday for a radio, newspaper and telephone
campaign to combat fundamentalist preacher Jerry Falwell's assault
on a major civil rights bill facing a Senate vote Tuesday.
   ``Jerry Falwell is a liar, and the truth is not in him,'' said
the Rev. John H. Buchanan, chairman of People for the American Way,
the liberal lobbying group that is organizing the blitz with the
support of major Roman Catholic, Jewish and Protestant
organizations.
   Falwell, chairman of the conservative Moral Majority
organization, prompted a deluge of phone calls to senators' offices
_ reportedly 80,000 calls in a single hour on Thursday _ with his
charge that the bill ``is the greatest threat to religious freedom
and traditional moral values ever passed.''
   In a ``special memorandum to pastors'' circulated last week,
Falwell said the bill, which he called the ``Civil Rights Sodom and
Gomorrah Act,'' might force churches to ``hire a practicing active
homosexual drug addict with AIDS to be a teacher or youth pastor''
and allow the government to dictate sermons preached from the
pulpit.
   Buchanan, a Baptist pastor in Washington and former Republican
House member from Alabama, joined mainline religious leaders and
civil rights organizations at a news conference in denouncing
Falwell for ``spreading hysteria'' with ``scare tactics'' and
``obvious falsehoods'' about the bill.
   The measure, vetoed by President Reagan on Wednesday, was
approved earlier this year by margins of 75-14 in the Senate and
315-98 in the House, more than the two-third majorities necessary
to enact the legislation over Reagan's objections.
   The Senate is scheduled to vote Tuesday on overriding the
president's veto, and House action will follow. Approval by both
chambers is required to put a vetoed bill into law.
   Buchanan said that ``to help set the record straight,'' his
organization will place radio advertisements in major listening
areas over the weekend and will run newspaper ads in The Washington
Post and USA Today on Monday.
   In addition, he said, People for the American Way will spend the
weekend phoning its 270,000 members nationwide to urge them to
lobby members of Congress in support of the bill.
   The anti-Falwell ad campaign also will concentrate on newspapers
in Alabama, Florida, South Carolina and Louisiana, Buchanan said.
   The bill's foes, meanwhile, succeeded in persuading at least one
senator who had voted for the bill, John W. Warner, R-Va., to
change his mind.
   Warner said Friday he had decided to vote to sustain Reagan's
veto after his Senate office received ``thousands of calls from
Virginians questioning how the law will be implemented and how it
will impact their daily lives.''
   Sen. Thad Cochran, R-Miss., who voted for the bill, said he also
would vote to sustain Reagan's veto, primarily because of the
bill's unfavorable impact on homebuilders, farmers and some
religious groups that the measure ``may encroach on separation
between church and state.''
   Cochran said Assistant Senate Minority Leader Alan Simpson,
R-Wyo., told him he also intended to defect. But Mary K. Hill, a
spokeswoman for Simpson, said Simpson had not decided which way he
would vote.
   The measure was intended to overturn the Supreme Court's 1984
Grove City decision, which restricted the scope of
anti-discrimination laws. The court said the laws cover only
specific programs receiving federal funds, rather than the entire
colleges, corporations or other institutions under which the
programs operate.
   Advocates of the vetoed bill say it merely would restore
institution-wide coverage that Congress intended when it passed
legislation banning discrimination against minorities, women, the
handicapped and the elderly in federally financed programs.
   In an attempt to avert a House and Senate override of his veto,
the president proposed an alternative that would narrow the scope
of the vetoed bill.
   Among the groups joining the campaign in support of the bill
were the Leadership Conference on Civil Rights, American Jewish
Congress, U.S. Catholic Conference, American Jewish Committee,
Evangelical Luthern Church in America, American Baptist Churches
USA, United Methodist Church, Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.),
Episcopal Church, Church of the Bretheran and the National Council
of the Churchs of Christ in the U.S.A.
</TEXT>
