<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 0720EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-GreatLakes     03-19 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Great Lakes,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Warming Climate May Cause Serious Drop In Water Levels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Water levels in the Great Lakes could drop as
much as seven feet in the next 100 years because of a warming
climate caused by man-made changes in the atmosphere, a federal
hydrologist said Friday.
   The forecast by Dr. Frank H. Quinn of the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration came as the Great Lakes Commission at
its semi-annual meeting criticized lakes-research budget cuts
proposed by President Reagan.
   Quinn, speaking in Chicago, said precipitation over Lakes
Michigan and Huron since 1965 has exceeded the average for the 20th
century.
   The wet and cool climate of the past 20 years pushed the lakes
to record high levels and may have produced a new norm for the
lakes.
   ``However, this could be offset in the future by climate
warming, which would have the opposite effect on lake levels,''
Quinn said.
   Computer simulations, based on expectations for the
concentration of carbon dioxide and other chemicals in the
atmosphere, suggest the warming climate could lower Lake Michigan
and Lake Huron by three feet to seven feet in the next 100 years,
and Lake Erie by two feet to four feet, said Quinn, who heads
NOAA's Great Lakes Environmental Research Laboratories in Ann
Arbor, Mich.
   The simulations suggest an average temperature increase of seven
degrees over the Great Lakes Basin, Quinn said.
   In Washington, the Great Lakes Commission, an interstate
organization that coordinates policy on issues affecting the lakes,
released an analysis showing the Reagan administration's budget
would cut Great Lakes research funding nearly in half.
   The Reagan budget for 1989 proposed $17.1 million in Great Lakes
spending by the Environmental Protection Agency, Department of
Commerce and Department of the Interior, Martin said. Congress
approved $32.7 million in spending on the programs in 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880319-0179 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 0725EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSEmbezzling     03-19 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Embezzling,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Say Former Banker Gave Embezzled Funds to AIDS Charity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former banker dying of AIDS has been charged
with embezzling $1.3 million and giving some of it to gay charities.
   A federal indictment, made public Thursday, accused William
Patrick Debenport, 27, of using his position as manager of a First
Texas Savings and Loan branch to misappropriate the money.
   If convicted on all 15 counts, Debenport could receive up to 75
years in prison and $75,000 in fines.
   Debenport's attorney, J. Stephen Cooper, said in November that
Debenport used the money to buy luxuries for himself and friends
but also donated some to gay charities, including $175,000 to a
Dallas home for AIDS victims.
   First Texas has sued to recover the money from the home.
   Debencourt was fired in June. Cooper said his client began
taking the money after being told by a doctor he had AIDS and had
only a short time to live.
   Cooper said Debenport donated a small amount to a predominantly
gay church and gave sums ranging from several hundred to several
thousand dollars to as many as 15 friends.
   He also bought himself a luxury car and a $217,000 home, Cooper
said.
</TEXT>
