<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 0727EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Palau     03-19 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Palau,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Warning to Congress from Palau Lawmakers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven Palau lawmakers accused a House
subcommittee Friday of unreasonably delaying their country's
independence with unfounded and unproven charges of corruption and
narcotics trafficking.
   They warned that if the delay continues, the mid-Pacific island
chain will face a financial crisis and meanwhile might explore
``other political status alternatives'' than that already chosen,
free association with the United States.
   The seven Palau senators admitted that the islands had drug and
other problems. But they had been ``permitted to develop
unchecked'' during 40 years of U.S. rule, and could be attacked
more effectively now by the new sovereign government with financing
promised under the recently-approved compact with the United States.
   The Palau senators raised the issues in a letter to Ron de Lugo,
the Virgin Islands delegate, who is chairman of a House
subcommittee on insular and international affairs.
   The letter took issue with charges of Palau wrongdoing raised by
de Lugo and Rep. Morris K. Udall, D-Ariz., chairman of the House
Interior Committee, in a March 2 letter to the chairman of the
House Foreign Affairs committee, Rep. Dante Fascell, D-Fla.
   Udall and de Lugo said in their letter that Palau was used as a
transhipment point for heroin moving from Southeast Asia to the
United States and that several unnamed ``senior Palauan government
officials have been identified to us as being connected'' with the
traffic.
   Palau, the last Pacific territory still under U.S. trusteeship
since World War II, has entered into a compact of free association
with the United States, now awaiting implementation by Congress.
Other Senate and House committees have voted final approval but de
Lugo and Udall earlier this month held up action and raised the
charges against unnamed officials of the government in Koror,
capital of the new republic.
   They also cited violence last summer surrounding a plebescite
weakening Palau's constitutional ban on nuclear weapons to
accommodate the U.S. military, which counts on Palau as a backup
base if its forces are asked to leave the Philippines.
   Udall and de Lugo have said the resolution implementing the
compact won't be acted on until Palau's courts rule on the legality
of the plebescite approval, or opponents of it declare they won't
renew a court challenge they had said earlier they withdrew because
of intimidation.
   ``We urge that you do not permit the issue of alleged wrongdoing
in Palau to become tied to the approval of compact
implementation,'' the seven senators said in their letter.
   Palau, which has a population of less than 15,000 in its 200
islands, had repeatedly asked U.S. help against drug cultivation
and trafficking but its requests were rarely honored, the letter
said, asserting that subcommittee allegations of corruption and
criminal acts lacked documentation.
   Most of them ``are absolutely spurious and unfounded, and were
made by a small group of discontented Palauans under the influence
of unknown outside elements ...'' it continued.
   ``We also believe that certain government officials including
members of this National Congress have been fueling this concern
about irrelevant issues to further their individual political
ambitions,'' it said.
</TEXT>
