<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Iditarod     03-19 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iditarod,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Founder of Sled Dog Race Finishes In the Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOME, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 70-year-old founder of the 1,150-mile
Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race crossed the finish line Friday in
fifth place, more than a day and a half behind the winner but still
in the money.
   Joe Redington of Knik collected $15,000 as one of the top 20
finishers in the annual Anchorage-to-Nome trek. Herbie Nayokpuk of
Shishmaref was a minute and 16 seconds behind as they arrived
shortly after noon.
   For Redington, who organized the first Iditarod in 1973 but has
never won, it was the fifth time he has finished fifth. Nayokpuk
will collect $12,000 for the No. 6 spot.
   Susan Butcher won the race Wednesday night for the third time in
a row. She finished in 11 days, nearly 15 hours ahead of her
nearest rival, Rick Swenson of Two Rivers.
   Redington pumped hard over the final couple of miles as he and
Nayokpuk made their run along the Bering Sea ice.
   ``I really had to work,'' Redington said at the finish line.
   Forty one mushers continued on the trail Friday. Some were more
than four days from Nome. The race began March 5.
</TEXT>
