<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 0829EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EasterSeriesI Adv29   03-19 1097</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Easter Series I, Adv 29,1128</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tue AMs, March 29, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Strangers No Longer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Part I: Past Church Opponents Join Hands as Partners</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This first story in a four-part Easter series,
``Strangers No Longer,'' deals with the new companionship among
Protestants and Roman Catholics in the quest for Christian unity.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   On the flood-lit, greenery-bedecked platform stood the Roman
Catholic pope, his raised hands joined with those of U.S.
Protestant and Eastern Orthodox leaders as they intoned the Lord's
prayer together.
   ``Our Father, who art in heaven, hallowed be thy name...''
   Out across Williams-Brice Stadium in Columbia, S.C., a sea of
65,000, mostly Southern Baptists and other Protestants, also lifted
clasped hands aloft, the prayer resonating in concert:
   ``Thy kingdom come, thy will be done, on Earth as it is in
Heaven ...''
   It was an unprecedented interlude, there in the overwhelmingly
Protestant South on Sept. 11, 1987, as Pope John Paul II led a
Billy Graham-style service, using Graham's advisers, pulpit and
sound equipment, in conjunction with the widest array of American
church officials ever assembled with a pope.
   ``We stand, side by side, to confess Jesus Christ, the one
mediator between God and man,'' he said, ticking off the varied
denominational leadership participating with him: Methodist,
Baptist, Lutheran, Pentecostal, Presbyterian, Reformed, Episcopal,
Catholic, Orthodox, Disciples of Christ and others.
   ``Brothers and sisters ... Let us rejoice in this fellowship.
And let us commit ourselves further to the great task which Jesus
himself urges upon us: to go forward along the path of Christian
reconciliation and unity.''
   That impulse for unity, germinating among divided churches after
centuries of conflict and antagonism, was implored by Jesus on the
night before his crucifixion.
   ``Father, the hour has come,'' he prayed in that dark, tearful
vigil on the Mount of Olives, pleading his followers ``may all be
one ... so that the world may believe.''
   That imperative, reiterated through the New Testament, was a
given for Christians _ that having one Lord, they were inherently
one community. Yet for centuries, they fragmented into hostile
camps, spurning and vilifying one another.
   ``Schismatic sects, apostates,'' Rome labeled Protestants, who
inveighed against Roman Catholicism, ``the Roman Babylon, popism,''
and vied caustically among themselves. Scattered pockets of that
rancor remain.
   However, in a sweeping and comparatively brief span of the 20th
century, the bitter enmity has largely vanished. The last 20 years
have witnessed broad inter-church friendship and collaboration.
   ``The whole atmosphere has changed,'' said religion historian
Harry S. Stout of Yale University, noting that in television
sermons it is generally impossible to tell a Catholic from a
Protestant.
   ``It's one of the most important trends of the 1980s and it's on
the rise,'' he said in an interview. ``Christians of different
denominations are coming together, recognizing a common enemy,
whether you call it atheism, materialism or secularism. Faced with
a common enemy, they're realizing that they need each other, that
they're in the same boat.''
   Congregations and pastors, once stiffly aloof and
uncommunicative, have become trusting, sharing retreats and working
together.
   For Christ ``is our peace, who has made us both one, and has
broken down the dividing wall of hostility,'' says Ephesians 2 of
differently descended believers. ``So then you are no longer
strangers and sojourners, but ... fellow ... members of the
household of God.''
   The contemporary change began in the century's first half as
Protestantism and eventually Eastern Orthodoxy joined in councils
and compacts, followed in the last 25 years by Catholicism's
transforming plunge into the convergent stream.
   It's called the ``ecumenical movement,'' meaning a global coming
together. Lately it has developed some uncharted currents beyond
official banks _ or anticipation.
   ``It has moved far beyond the tinkling of teacups and the
initial exuberance,'' said the Rev. Thaddeus Horgan, assistant
ecumenical officer of the U.S. Roman Catholic bishops. ``It has
become so common it's often unnoticed. It has moved from
adolescence into young adulthood.''
   But the most prominent characteristic of the movement recently
has been its growing power among the rank-and-file, creating an
utterly new companionship and teamwork among Protestants and Roman
Catholics.
   ``A tide is rising and soon it will be felt on the quarter
deck,'' said United Methodism's foremost theologian, Albert Outler
of Dallas.
   It's like a half-full glass, he said, which, instead of filling
from above, now is rising from the bottom. ``It's bubbling up in a
way that it can burst out in new forms.''
   Outler, among the pioneering Protestant observers at
Catholicism's reforming 1962-65 Second Vatican Council, which
unleashed the church's ecumenical involvement, added:
   ``Christians have discovered that they can live and work
together, with or without official sanction or what used to be
called organic unity. There's a sort of paralysis at the top, but a
very vigorous grass-roots development and exploration _ not only in
cooperative social action but in joint study, discussions and
sharing in church life _ while official leadership has settled down
into a kind of quiescence. ...
   ``It's beginning to be the case that Christian lay folk in
general no longer believe that structural tinkering has much real
impact for change, and they're turning to what may be more
authentic, doing it themselves.
   ``The younger generation is growing up in this atmosphere, and
denominational identities are being blurred. ... The new
developments can't be calendared or predicted ... but I think we're
actually moving more realistically in terms of basic essential
ventures of Christian unity than when we were so entranced by its
theatrics.''
   But the growing sense of community still has its dramatic
moments. Such was that juncture in the heavily Protestant territory
of Columbia, S.C., where the pope met in an unparalleled
interchange with the broadest cross-section ever of American
Protestant and Orthodox leadership, black and white, mainline,
evangelical and Pentecostal.
   The 26 church leaders, in a joint statement read by African
Methodist Episcopal Bishop Philip Cousins, said the ``prayers and
hopes of many American Christians'' were for further steps in
``reconciling the divided people of God.''
   Later, at the end of the vast stadium service, the pope and the
church leaders together raised their hands, pronouncing blessing on
the multitude in unison:
   ``The Lord bless you and keep you. The Lord make his face to
shine upon you, and be gracious to you. The Lord lift up his
countenance upon you and give you peace.''
   Across that Bible Belt city of Columbia, the church bells pealed.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>TOMORROW: Traditions Drawn Together by Common Book</HEAD>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tue AMs, March 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880319-0185 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 0831EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EasterSeriesII Adv30   03-19 1210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Easter Series II, Adv 30,1243</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, March 30, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Strangers No Longer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Part II: Traditions Drawn Together by Common Book</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The second story in a four-part Easter series,
``Strangers No Longer,'' reports on efforts for Christian unity,
dealing with the quiet, seldom-noted ties among Roman Catholics and
Protestants in Bible scholarship and worship.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   In a gray stone building called Adams House at Princeton
University, 30 scholars pray, discuss their agenda and progress
reports, then divide in half and go to work in separate rooms.
   Each is stocked with reference books, reproductions of Hebrew
and Greek manuscripts, grammar books and biblical commentaries.
   The participants are Protestant, Roman Catholic, Eastern
Orthodox and Jewish experts on the Bible, and in the two sections _
Old Testament and New _ they are working on a revised translation.
   ``So far as this book is concerned, we're essentially at one,''
said the Rev. Bruce Metzger, a Presbyterian and head of a committee
working on a new Revised Standard Version, the Protestant-sponsored
Bible that also has Roman Catholic approval.
   ``Biblical scholars of Roman Catholic and Protestant affiliation
approach their work in terms of scholarship with little if any
differences remaining,'' Metzger said in an interview. ``The lines
of distinction have meted away.''
   That common treatment and usage of the Bible has become a
powerful undercurrent in their advance toward unity. Work on the
book is seen as the inner glue, acting from within to mend the
ruptures.
   ``Traditional differences are not relevant,'' said Catholic Old
Testament scholar Conrad L'Heureux of the University of Dayton.
``We have lots of debates, but they don't fall along denominational
lines. ... It's become second nature to get at what the text says
objectively without bringing the perspective of your own church
into it.
   ``In an odd sense, biblical scholars are ahead of the crowd.''
   ``It's a wave of the future,'' agreed Catholic Bible scholar
William Holladay of Andover-Newton Theological Seminary in
Massachusetts. ``It may well bring everybody else along.
Confessional differences may seem to divide people on Saturday and
Sunday, but they don't make any difference when it comes to
biblical work.''
   Besides the joint scholarly work, most American Christians hear
identically worded biblical passages each week in worship services.
   ``For the most part, they aren't aware of it,'' said the Rev.
Monsignor Alan Detscher of the U.S. Catholic Conference's liturgy
office in Washington, D.C. ``They generally experience only the
Scripture readings in their own church and aren't aware the
passages are now mostly identical that Sunday in other churches.''
   This synchronization of Scripture readings came about through a
widely used common lectionary, the three-year cycle of Bible
lessons read in church and based on the Roman lectionary developed
since the reforming 1962-65 Second Vatican Council.
   In most mainline denominations, Roman Catholic, Episcopal,
Lutheran, Presbyterian and United Methodist, ``the readings now are
generally the same and follow the same pattern,'' Detscher said.
   For instance, last weekend on Palm Sunday, March 27, marking
Jesus' triumphant entry into Jerusalem a week before his arrest and
crucifixion, the epistle read in most Protestant and Catholic
congregations was Philippians 2:6-11, saying in part:
   He ``emptied himself, taking the form of a servant, being born
in the likeness of men. And being found in human form, he humbled
himself and became obedient unto death, even death on the cross.''
   Provisions are made for shorter or longer readings and for
alternative passages. The weekly pattern may get off schedule by a
week or two, longer in periods not linked to major Christian
seasons, and the simultaneous passages are not adhered to in
evangelical-style congregations.
   In many places, neighboring Protestant and Roman Catholic
pastors ``get together to prepare their homilies because common
Scripture materials are being used,'' Detscher said.
   Sharing the same texts on which to preach, they trade ideas for
sermons, something that also makes for intellectual
cross-pollination.
   The Rev. Roland Murphy of Washington, D.C., a Catholic Bible
scholar, said that people's ``hearing the word of God Sunday after
Sunday in the same readings, more or less, is creating a bond of
unity that didn't exist before.''
   Protestant and Catholic liturgies also have become increasingly
parallel structurally, so that a casual visitor cannot tell in most
respects whether he's at a Catholic, Episcopal or Lutheran service.
   ``People no longer feel uncomfortable going to one another's
churches,'' Detscher said. ``From total separation in worship we've
moved to a commonality in worship. Slowly but surely, we've come a
long ways toward unity. Now that we're beginning to pray the same
way, maybe we'll start believing that way.''
   Of course, the touchstone Catholic-Protestant barrier remains
officially in Holy Communion, the central act of worship in which
joint participation is so far barred. But even that sharing happens
occasionally, quietly.
   ``In places, it's taking place casually, although it's not
really kosher,'' said United Methodist theologian Albert Outler of
Dallas. ``All kinds of Protestants are at Roman Catholic altars,
and Catholics at Protestant altars. They're beginning to think of
ways to have pulpit and altar fellowship without the bureaucrats
bothering them.''
   However, one of the strongest approved links is common
appreciation for the Bible and study of it, something formerly
inhibited by Catholicism but now heartily encouraged.
   The transition came at the Second Vatican Council, which urged
general reading of the Bible, including translations produced in
cooperation with Protestants.
   Previously, ``reading or studying the Bible was regarded as a
Protestant characteristic,'' said a Catholic New Testament scholar,
the Rev. Raymond E. Brown, adding ``that picture has changed
dramatically.''
   Brown, who teaches at New York's interdenominational Union
Theological Seminary, said American Catholicism had ``moved from
scarcely mentioning the Bible to a situation where the Bible has
become a fundamental referent in Catholic theology, spirituality
and religious discussion.''
   The fresh, broad regard for the Bible prompted a mutual
searching of ecumenical origins, a refocus on roots, drawing
churches closer to that common ground.
   In academic circles, Catholics and Protestants commonly teach at
each other's schools and seminaries. Protestant and Catholic
scholars, now often members of the same professional organizations,
have become an interacting, underlying intellectual stratum that
nourishes the whole enterprise.
   ``Sometimes there is greater loyalty among those in professional
societies than to their own seminary or denomination,'' said Yale's
Paul Minear, a United Church of Christ Bible scholar. ``They're
building lines of communication that simply ignore denominational
identities.''
   He said Scripture scholars and theologians are ``much more
united than church hierarchies. It just shows that what preserves
the different denominations is a set of non-theological factors.
Historic conditions keep them apart institutionally.''
   With theological training becoming more similar, with Protestant
and Catholic worship and sermons more alike, with scholars working
together, it's ``going to make an enormous difference in the long
run in creating a sense of commonalty,'' said Lutheran theologian
George Lindbeck.
   Asked if this common undergrowth might eventually sprout into
full-scale Christian unity, he said:
   ``If the urge becomes stronger, then the similarities will make
it much easier. Things could take off very quickly. But it's likely
to require major external events, something to catalyze it.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NEXT: Dialogues Produce World Accord on Basic Beliefs</HEAD>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, March 30, and Thereafter</NOTE>
