<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EasterSeriesIV Adv01   03-19 1189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Easter Series IV, Adv 01,1222</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, April 1, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Strangers No Longer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Part IV: Christian Connections Spreading at Grass Roots</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The fourth and final installment of an Easter
series, ``Strangers No Longer,'' focuses on grass-root activities
in Protestant-Catholic efforts toward Christian unity.
 
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   In the little town of Beaverton, Ore., the Mission of the
Atonement has both Roman Catholic and Lutheran members. Across the
country at Holy Apostles' Church in Virginia Beach, Va., members
included Episcopalians and Catholics.
   ``We're one model of how the church can put itself back
together,'' the Rev. Ray Barton, Catholic co-pastor of Holy
Apostles', said in an interview. ``It's a harbinger of the future.''
   Added the Rev. Donald Gross, Holy Apostles' Episcopal co-pastor,
``It's a sign of how it might be possible for the two traditions to
live together, a sign of the church united.''
   The combined congregations, authorized by bishops on both sides,
worship together in opening services. Then they split in two, as
church rules now require, for their main liturgies, including Holy
Communion, using in weekly turns the sanctuaries or adjacent
fellowship halls.
   About everything else _ Sunday school, adult Christian
education, home study and social outreach _ is done together.
   ``It seems critical that the Christian church give an example to
the world of how to express our unity and yet respect our
diversity,'' said the Rev. Dale Jamtgaard, Lutheran co-pastor in
Beaverton.
   ``It may be a little like royalty getting hitched between
nations,'' said Beaverton's Catholic co-pastor, the Rev. Mathias
Tumulty. ``It's a way to get to know and understand each other
personally and care for each other. If it's possible here, maybe
it's possible elsewhere.''
   Such signs of the underlying bonds get a rousing display May
21-25 when an expected 3,000 Protestants, Evangelicals and
Catholics hold a national ``Gathering for Christians'' in
Arlington, Texas.
   It is to bring out that ``we are no longer strangers'' and to
``honor and proclaim Jesus Christ whose cross and resurrection
bring peace with God and humanity,'' said the Rev. Eileen Linder,
ecumenical officer of the National Council of Churches, which is
putting together the event.
   This inter-Christian linkage has grown dramatically, showing up
in myriad Protestant-Catholic covenants and compacts at national
and local levels.
   ``I'm always struck with the developments of the last two
years,'' said the Rev. John Hotchkin of Washington, D.C., the U.S.
Catholic bishops' ecumenical officer, ``the neighborhood
coalitions, the working together in programs for the elderly, for
people in need, recycling clothes, common feeding pantries, drug
counseling for young people, shelters for the homeless.
   ``There's not much about it in the press, and people don't sense
anything remarkable about it anymore, but it's really quite
striking.''
   The alliances take many forms. In Brooklyn, N.Y., churches
joined in a huge interfaith project to build 5,000 low-cost houses
for poor families. Called the Nehemiah Project after the
fifth-century prophet who rebuilt ravaged Jerusalem, churches have
pooled $15 million, with 1,000 houses already up.
   In Houston, about 200 congregations are involved in a citywide
AIDS education and care effort.
   ``In this crisis, denominationalism is just religious history,''
said the Rev. Earl Shelp, the Baptist co-coordinator of the program.
   Churches in Seattle outfit rooms for the homeless.
   Through the Center for Corporate Responsibility in New York, 19
Protestant denominations and 210 Catholic orders and dioceses use
their $10 billion in stock holdings to sway business practices for
social good.
   Leaders of 40 denominations are involved in the Religion
Alliance Against Pornography, with local units functioning around
the nation. Included are churches of the National Association of
Evangelicals, which generally shun ecumenical efforts.
   Catholics and Protestants have banded together in such groups as
Bread for the World, Witness for Peace, Clergy and Laity Concerned,
Interfaith Hunger Appeal, the American Bible Society and even an
organization for laughs, the Fellowship of Merry Christians.
   They've teamed up in civil rights causes, the farm crisis, the
sanctuary movement to shelter Central American refugees, backed one
another's declarations on the American economy and against nuclear
weaponry.
   Spiritually, the togetherness shows up with uninhibited fervor
among groups of charismatic Christians, 40,000 of whom met in New
Orleans Superdome last July, an ecumenical jamboree of prayer,
singing-in-tongues and arms-high praises to God.
   Local ``covenants'' have developed, with participants promising
to pray for each other, to share resources, retreats, studies and
facilities and work together in social betterment projects. More
than 100 such covenants are estimated functioning between Catholics
and Episcopal, Lutheran, United Methodist, Presbyterian and other
Protestant congregations.
   In Riverside and North Riverside, Ill., eight congregations _
two Roman Catholic, two Lutheran, two Presbyterian, one Episcopal
and one United Methodist _ are linked in a covenant, with an eye to
eventual unity.
   Covenants pairing two congregations, usually Catholic and
Episcopal or Lutheran but also involving others, have arisen around
the country _ in Kentucky, Massachusetts, Wisconsin, New York,
Oregon, Rhode Island, Colorado and elsewhere.
   ``They keep popping up here and there,'' said Sister Ann Teresa
Nagy of the Graymoor Ecumenical Institute in Garrison, N.Y. ``As a
result of dialogues and meetings, they realize how close they are.
... They're learning how to live together, work together and be at
one.''
   In Wyandanch, N.Y., the parishes of Trinity Lutheran and Our
Lady of Miraculous Medal once asked the Vatican to permit
inter-communion, but were turned down ``for the time being.''
   Catholic and Episcopal dioceses have entered covenants in Kansas
City, Mo.; San Diego; Little Rock, Ark.; Seattle; Providence, R.I.;
Milwaukee and Chicago.
   In local communities, churches often ``are working together more
closely than they are with their national headquarters,'' says
veteran ecumenical theologian Paul Minear. ``Something is happening
there by way of real Christian unity that does not follow
traditional church lines.''
   Additionally, major mergers among Protestants are being
discussed or have occurred, two sealed in the 1980s reuniting
Northerners and Southerners in the Presbyterian Church (USA) in
1983 and merging three Lutheran branches into the Evangelical
Lutheran Church in America at the start of 1988.
   Another gradually unifying process is at a decisive stage among
nine U.S. denominations.
   ``This year is a watershed for us,'' said the Rev. Gerald Moede,
general secretary of the Consultation on Church Union. Five of the
nine denominations will act on the plan in 1988 _ the Episcopal
Church, United Methodist Church, Presbyterian Church (USA), the
African Methodist Episcopal Church and the African Methodist
Episcopal Zion Church.
   The United Church of Christ and Christian Church (Disciples of
Christ) decide next year. The two others already have approved _
the Christian Methodist Episcopal Church and the International
Council of Community Churches.
   ``We're looking for a new common identity in which we'd be
related, yet preserve our diverse traditions,'' Moede said, noting
the ``covenanting'' plan would maintain present structures but
bring sharing in ministry and communion.
   ``The objective is not one huge institution,'' he said. ``One
thing we've learned is that not everything should be given up or
changed. The early church had great diversity, and we want to
preserve that diversity.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, April 1</NOTE>
