<NOTE>$adv 20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions March 19-20</NOTE>
<HEAD>Calm In Credit Markets Means Stable Interest Rates</HEAD>
<HEAD>Lasergraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond traders are frustrated and would-be
homeowners thrilled by the eerie calm that has overtaken the credit
markets during the past several weeks. For the first time in quite
a while, you can almost bank on interest rates.
   ``This has been one of the quietest periods I've ever seen,''
Elliott Platt, an economist at Donaldson Lufkin & Jenrette
Securities Inc., said in describing recent trading for bonds, notes
and other debt-related products.
   ``If there was a word that could be milder than calm that would
be appropriate,'' added F. Ward McCarthy, chief financial economist
for Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
   In the Treasury market, trading has slowed substantially.
According to the Federal Reserve, the average daily dealer
transaction was around $90 billion in the week ending March 9, at
least $10 billion below the norm.
   Some economists say the flatness in the credit markets, which
set the trend for consumer and business rates, can be attributed to
conflicting economic signals. Others say the markets are just
taking a break after starting the year on a somewhat volatile note.
   Whatever the reasons, most predict that interest rates will
remain fairly stable, at least through the spring.
   ``From the consumer standpoint I think the fact that we've had
some stability has been reassuring. Volatility in recent years has
taken its toll on consumer confidence,'' said McCarthy, who
described as comfortable the current level of interest rates.
   The yield on the Treasury's 30-year bond, the most-watched debt
security, has remained in a fairly narrow range since late January,
fluctuating around 8.5 percent _ the same level as the current
prime lending rate.
   Mortgage rates have inched their way downward so far this year
but have remained fairly level in recent weeks, too.
   The average rate charged by commercial lenders on a fixed-rate,
30-year mortgage has been just below 10 percent since early
February, according to the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. The
rate on adjustable mortgages has hovered around 7.5 percent in
recent weeks, Freddie Mac said.
   Compared to a year ago, there isn't too much change. However,
rates are at least two percentage points lower now than they were
around the time when the stock market crashed last October.
   After the market plunged, the Fed eased its credit policies,
allowing interest rates to fall, to prevent the economy from
falling into a recession. Lately, some signs of economic growth
have surfaced, mingled with reports to the contrary.
   In light of the mixed signals, analysts say the Fed has
indicated it will maintain a fairly stable policy through the
spring.
   ``The government has intimated it was more concerned about high
inflation than a recession,'' said Elizabeth G. Reiners, assistant
director of money market reserach for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
``It looks like inflation is at a comfortable level.
   ``If you keep policy stable, you're looking at stable rates.''
   Among the benefactors of stable rates have been homebuyers and
those looking to refinance loans or borrow for other big purchases.
   Knowing that rates aren't likely to swing wildly ``means that
people have more freedom of choice about when to do their home
buying and moving,'' said Carol A. Stone, a senior economist at
Nomura Securities Inc.
   Corporations and municipalities looking to sell their bonds and
notes also have felt less pressured.
   ``If they're considering a deal it gives them a little more
leeway ... because the market isn't moving wildly,'' said Mrs.
Reiners.
   But the big losers, Mrs. Reiners said, have been bond traders,
who make their money on the ups and downs of the market and
investors looking for high-yielding securities.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions March 19-20</NOTE>
