<1ST_LINE>a f BC-Week'sBusiness Adv19-20-2Takes   03-19 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Week's Business, Adv 19-20-2 Takes,0694</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 19</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions March 19-20 and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Airlines Taking Bold Gamble With New Fare Hikes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's airlines embarked on a big gamble
this past week.
   They hope their steeper fares and tighter restrictions on
discount tickets won't overly upset customers, who have come to
take for granted the cheap fares nurtured in recent years by the
cut-throat climate of the deregulated U.S. industry.
   Emboldened by robust passenger traffic in recent months, the big
airlines put through major fare increases several weeks before they
normally do _ jumping the gun on the peak travel season that starts
in April.
   The October stock market crash triggered fears that consumer
nervousness could cut sharply into air travel, but the major U.S.
carriers have posted an average increase in traffic of 7 percent to
8 percent since New Year's Day from the same period last year.
   Flush with those results, the airlines have increased their
first-class, economy and discount fares by 15 percent to 85
percent, depending on the destination. They also tightened
restrictions on their popular ``MaxSaver'' discount fares,
requiring that tickets be purchased seven days in advance instead
of two.
   Some discount tariffs were eliminated altogether. The changes
hit hard at consumers who have to fly on short notice, especially
business travelers.
   The fare increases amplified the upward trend in air fares that
has prevailed for the past four or five months.
   ``It would seem the airlines run a very real risk of going too
far,'' said Paul Schlesinger, an airline analyst for Donaldson,
Lufkin & Jenrette Securities Corp. ``Empty planes don't carry the
debt.''
   Other analysts agreed that the airlines, in their bold grab for
more revenue, could force themselves into a ``Catch 22'' situation
whereby the higher fares and restrictions scare too many potential
passengers away.
   If that happens, fares could come back down as quickly as they
went up. Since the domestic airline industry was deregulated in
1978, it has become an increasingly nimble ``quick-change'' artist
in responding to shifting market conditions.
   ``What you're really seeing is a marketing of airline travel the
way retailers market,'' said Robert Joedicke, who follows the
industry for Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. ``Fare policy is going to
be a continual adjustment game.''
   Joedicke suggested that rounds of fare cuts are becoming as
common as ``white sales'' of linen and other items offered
regularly by department stores.
   This means that the latest increases in the cost of flying,
while steep, do not necessarily signal a move toward a full-fare
airline industry.
   Besides, skeptics noted, some of the recent rise in traffic
could be coming from passengers taking free trips on frequent-flier
travel bonuses and triple-mileage awards. An estimated 8 million
Americans are enrolled in frequent flier programs and may be
bumping paying passengers.
   Many major airlines, believing that the frequent-flier giveaways
have gotten out of control, have imposed restrictions on the plans
or are thinking of doing so.
   In fact, some of the recent push toward higher fares may be an
attempt to compensate for lost revenue from frequent fliers.
   ``The airlines take a negative risk with the triple mileage,''
said Andrew Geller, a transportation analyst for Provident National
Bank in Philadelphia. ``The question arises of who's got to pay for
it _ the normal-fare people?''
   All this does little to reassure the individual customer, who
has been hit with a near-doubling of fares to some destinations.
   ``It's created a problem for us,'' said David Perlman, president
of DMS Travel, a retail travel agency in midtown Manhattan. ``It
just creates havoc with everybody.''
   He noted, for example, that a one-way, unrestricted economy fare
from Newark, N.J., to Chicago jumped under the new changes from
$185 to $280. A first-class, round-trip ticket between New York and
Aspen, Colo., now costs a hefty $1,200, up from $800.
   Perlman said he has spent much of the past week explaining the
changes to bewildered customers.
</TEXT>
