<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FmHALawsuit     03-19 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FmHA Lawsuit,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ranch Woman Accuses FmHA Of Sex And Age Discrimination</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB IMRIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 72-year-old rancher who said she was
forced into bankruptcy because the Farmers Home Administration
thought she was ``an old woman who should quit farming'' is suing
the government lender for $3 million.
   Beulah Jorgenson, who her attorney said has operated a ranch for
many years, claims in the lawsuit that FmHA denied her a $300,000
emergency loan in 1986.
   The Bowman County FmHA County Committee found her eligible for
the loan, but it was denied by County Supervisor Ronald Holtz,
according to the lawsuit.
   The suit, which names Holtz and the FmHA as defendants, said
Mrs. Jorgenson was forced to file under Chapter 12 of the Federal
Bankruptcy Act to reorganize her debts after foreclosure
proceedings began. Chapter 12 is a relatively new provision of the
act intended to help financially strapped farmers.
   Holtz told Mrs. Jorgenson she could not pay off the loan but he
``specifically declared to other persons that he was rejecting the
plaintiff's FmHA application because ... the plaintiff was an old
woman who should quit farming and ... and stop bothering FmHA,''
according to the lawsuit.
   Bob Zimmerman, chief of FmHA farm programs in North Dakota, said
Friday the agency had not seen a copy of the lawsuit, which accuses
Holtz and the FmHA of age and sex discrimination. The suit was
filed Wednesday in U.S. District Court.
   FmHA is the government's lender of last resort for farmers and
ranchers.
   Mrs. Jorgenson ranches on 3,000 acres near Bowman in
southwestern North Dakota with one hired man, said her attorney,
Rolf Sletten of Bismarck.
   ``Her husband is in a nursing home and has been for many years.
She has been running (the ranch) herself for many years,'' Sletten
said.
   Mrs. Jorgenson needed the emergency loan to pay off some
higher-interest loans she owed the Production Credit Association
and the Federal Land Bank, Sletten said. ``She hadn't had any loans
from the FmHA,'' he said.
   Holtz wrote Mrs. Jorgenson on April 4, 1986, telling her that
the loan was denied because Holtz believed she couldn't pay it back
and all her property was already mortgaged, according to court
documents.
   Mrs. Jorgenson is still ranching while her bankruptcy case is
pending, Sletten said Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880319-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 0840EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-WeeklyWallStreet Adv19-20   03-19 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Wall Street, Adv 19-20,0622</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 19</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions March 20-21</NOTE>
<HEAD>Recession Fears Thawing as Spring Begins</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As winter gives way to spring on Wall Street,
investors' worries are much different from what just about anyone
imagined three months ago.
   Increasingly, fears of an impending recession are being quelled
by signs of persistent strength in the economy. The stock market,
after suffering what looked like a knockout blow in October, has
bounced back with an impressive show of vitality.
   So the pessimists have turned to worrying not about hard times,
but rather too much of a good thing.
   Consider the position of the Federal Reserve. In the midst of
the crash last fall, it stepped up with a promise to provide as
much money to the system as was necessary to keep it from suffering
grave damage.
   Now, Alan Greenspan, the Fed's chairman, is sounding warnings
about the possibility that growth at too strong a pace could revive
inflationary pressures.
   The trade deficit, a primary focus of concern last fall, has
improved to the extent that some people now interpret it as a
signal of an economy heating up to potentially dangerous
temperatures.
   The bond market has grown increasingly jumpy lately over much
better-than-expected growth in employment, for fear that it might
soon exert upward pressure on inflation and interest rates.
   All this has a familiar ring. It was the kind of mood that often
set in during the great bull market of 1982-87.
   In the bond market memories remain fresh of the wrenching rise
in interest rates, and accompanying drop in bond prices, that
started right about this time a year ago.
   ``The stock market is approaching a critical juncture,'' says
Joseph Barthel, an analyst at Butcher & Singer Inc. ``Bonds must
rally to ward off a correction, or worse.''
   All this suits many of Wall Street's bulls just fine. Stocks
seem to be ``climbing a wall of worry,'' in the time-honored phrase
used to describe bull markets.
   In the past week, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials gained
52.39 points to 2,087.37, reaching new highs since the October
debacle.
   The New York Stock Exchange composite index rose 3.20 to 152.65;
the American Stock Exchange market value index was up 3.02 at
299.11, and the NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter
market added 6.10 to 381.58.
   Volume on the Big Board averaged 175.26 million shares a day,
against 199.77 million the week before.
   In the view of Mitchell Held, chief financial economist at Smith
Barney, Harris Upham & Co., ``the Fed is likely to hold policy
steady for the time being, and consequently we expect to see little
movement in short-term rates for now.
   ``Should the economic data continue to exceed general
expectations, as we anticipate, inflation expectations are likely
to rise, and short-term rates will probably rise either in reaction
to or in anticipation of Fed action.''
   However, if inflation is planning a comeback it is disguising
its intentions pretty well. The producer price index of finished
goods fell 0.2 percent in February.
   ``Consumers seem to have found a degree of price consciousness
and budget discipline,'' said David Ressler, chief economist at
Nomura Securities International.
   ``They seem willing to increase purchases of certain items such
as a car when there are significant price discounts, but to balance
that added spending with more restraint on other items.
   ``Such price sensitivity will make it difficult for any
broadbased cost pressures to be passed on to consumers.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions March 19-20</NOTE>
</DOC>
