<1ST_LINE>r f AM-DigitalDown 1stLd-Writethru   03-19 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Digital Down, 1st Ld-Writethru,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Analysts Downgrade Digital Third-Quarter Earnings Estimates</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 5th graf with closing stock price.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Digital Equipment Corp. said Friday that sluggish
sales of expensive computer systems have forced analysts to
downgrade third-quarter earnings estimates for the computer
industry giant.
   Mark Steinkrauss, Digital's investor relations director, said
the company is forecasting lower earnings for the fiscal quarter
ending March 26 because of the lag.
   ``While aggregate demand is very good and consistent with the
level we expected in the last couple of years, there's been a mix
shift to low-end products,'' he said.
   After discussions with analysts, Digital, based in Maynard,
Mass., agreed to cut its quarterly earnings forecast to about $2.30
a share from $2.50 a share. The company earlier this month agreed
to cut forecast to $2.50 from $2.70.
   Digital stock fell $1.50 a share Friday to $110.75 in composite
New York Stock Exchange trading. The stock fell $5.375 on Thursday.
   Wang Laboratories, Prime Computer and Data General all have
indicated recently that business is sluggish due to slumping
high-end demand, confirming a trend in minicomputer sales, analysts
said.
   ``Things are generally somewhat slow in the minicomputer sector
right now,'' said Bruce Watts of Needham & Co. ``Digital has been
reasonably candid that its product mix has shifted to less
expensive machines.''
   Steinkrauss said Digital has been unable to meet an unexpectedly
high demand for its less expensive equipment, including
workstations and terminals.
   ``The unanticipated shift caught us a little bit by surprise,''
he said. ``We didn't know demand was going to be as strong for
workstations and products at the low end and we didn't have the
capacity to ship it all this quarter.''
   Digital last week unveiled its 8800 Series of mainframe
computers in another challenge to industry leader International
Business Machines. But analysts said the impact of the new line
won't be felt for several months.
   ``The sales of high-end equipment are going slowly,'' said Jean
Orr of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. ``Customers are apparently
hesitant to make a commitment to the expensive equipment.
   ``We don't know for certain how long the hesitation will last,''
she added. ``My view is that it's going to be a quarter or two that
we see an effect.''
   Watts said Digital stock probably will fall some more in the
short-term but that its long-range prospects remain bright.
   ``I think there's no question that DEC has established
themselves as the leader in the minicomputer business and is
starting to take on IBM in the big computers, he said.
   Analysts also have dropped Digital's yearly earnings estimates
to $10 to $10.25 a share compared with $10.50 a share earlier this
month. For fiscal 1987, Digital reported profits of $1.14 billion
on $9.39 billion in revenues, or $8.53 a share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
