<1ST_LINE>r f AM-KaiserSteel     03-19 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kaiser Steel,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kaiser Steel Files Bankrutpcy Reorganization Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FONTANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kaiser Steel Corp., operating under
Chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings for 13 months, said Friday a
joint plan of reoganization had been filed by Kaiser and
representatives of retirees, other unsecured creditors and the
United Steelworks of America.
   Under the plan, filed in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Colorado on
Thursday, a percentage of proceeds from the sale of assets and the
settlement of litigation will be distributed to creditors.
   In addition, some claims against the company will be converted
into common stock in the reorganized concern, to be known as Kaiser
Holdings Inc.
   The plan provides, in part, for 30 milion common shares of the
new company to be distributed to retirees, Kaiser's unsecured
creditors, holders of preferred stock and, at the discretion of the
new board, as incentive options to management.
   Kaiser's current common stock, which is privately held, will be
canceled.
   The plan is endorsed by Kaiser and certain of its subsidiaries
as debtors; the company's official unsecured creditors committee;
that committee's retiree subcommittee, and the union.
   Upon emerging from bankruptcy proceedings, Kaiser said, it
intends to develop its 900-acre steel mill in Fontana as an
industrial park, modernize and operate its existing liquid-waste
treatment facility at the Fontana site and seek to create a
landfill for non-hazardous solid waste at its Eagle Mountain iron
ore mine in Riverside County.
   Although most of its holdings remain in Fontana, the company's
headquarters were moved to Colorado Springs, Colo., after a
leveraged buyout of several years ago.
   The Fontana plant was built by industrialist Henry J. Kaiser
during World War II to provide steel to build Liberty Ships on the
West Coast.
   The plant was located about 50 miles inland to protect it from
possible enemy attack during the war. But that location proved
fatal to the operation in later years, as high transporation costs
made it impossible for steel from Fontana to compete with low-cost
imports.
</TEXT>
