<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Griffin-Resorts-International 1stLd-Writethru   03-19
0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Griffin-Resorts-International, 1st Ld-Writethru,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Delays Ruling on Resorts Bid; Trump Sues Griffin</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 5th graf with closing stock price.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Delaware judge declined Friday to approve a
settlement of shareholder suits against Resorts International Inc.
that would have allowed investor Donald Trump to proceed with his
$22-per-share tender offer designed to take Resorts private.
   Instead, Chancery Court Vice Chancellor Maurice Hartnett put off
a decision until later, following a 2{-hour hearing.
   The action increases pressure on Trump, the New York real estate
developer, to raise his offer by giving wealthy entertainer Merv
Griffin more time to press his rival $35-per-share cash bid for
Resorts, the Atlantic City-based operator of hotel-casinos in New
Jersey and the Bahamas.
   ``Every continuance is a good thing for us in this situation
currently,'' said Mark Gill, a spokesman for Griffin, noting that
Trump's $22 offer expires on Monday.
   Resorts stock rose 50 cents a share Friday to $25.75.
   While Griffin's bid offers shareholders more money, it is
contingent on a number of conditions, including a decision by Trump
to support the deal and to terminate a five-year operating pact
with Resorts worth an estimated $100 million.
   Trump, who holds 88 percent of Resorts' voting power by owning
most of its Class B stock that carries 100 votes per share, has
said he wouldn't agree to either condition. As a result, Resorts'
directors Thursday declined to pursue Griffin's proposal on grounds
that it was moot.
   In separate developments Friday, Griffin, based in Los Angeles,
said he was dropping certain other conditions relating to
financing, and Trump announced he had filed suit against Griffin
seeking more than $250 million in damages.
   Trump's suit, filed in U.S. District Court in New York, names as
defendants Griffin, his privately held investment concern, The
Griffin Co., and Fidelle V. Scutti, who owns about 5 percent of
Resorts stock.
   Scutti, who has said he is dissatisfied with Trump's offer,
helped convince Griffin to make the competing bid.
   Trump's suit accuses the defendants with violations of federal
securities laws, fraud and tortious interference with Trump's
contractual relations with Resorts
   It claims the defendants took part in a scheme to manipulate the
market price of Resorts stock by making false and misleading
comments about their intentions and by making a $35-per-share offer
that the suit said was ``completely delusory'' because of its
highly conditional nature.
   In a statement, Griffin termed Trump's suit ``totally without
merit and solely for the purpose of attempting to coerce Mr.
Griffin to withdraw his offer.''
   Griffin said the suit of ``of no concern'' and that he intended
to filed unspecified counter-suits against Trump.
   Griffin has previously said he expected to file suit against
Trump and directors of Resorts for breach of fiduciary duty to
shareholders.
   The conditions Griffin eliminated from his offer were
requirements that financing be arranged for the merger and that
financing be arranged in advance to complete Resorts' giant and
luxurious Taj Mahal, a 42-story, 1,250-room hotel-casino being
built in Atlantic City.
</TEXT>
